<HEADLINE>Old Firm to boycott league of gentlemen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468442</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
ONLY a week after football club chairmen lined up to pour scorn on the
suggestion that a meeting had been organised to discuss league
reconstruction, some of them will rendezvous in Edinburgh this morning,
and although the agenda was not disclosed, it would be naive to believe
those who show up will discussing the weather or the price of team
balls.
Calls were made in the middle of this week, asking chairmen or their
representatives to convene at 11am at Hopetoun House, which is where the
Hearts chairman, Chris Robinson, bases his Wheatsheaf catering offices.
Robinson was one of those who, last week, suggested secret meetings on
reconstruction were not on, and, of course, at that time he was correct,
but many things can change in one short week in football. Perhaps the
game's chairmen believe the issue and its implications should now be
discussed.
There has been talk that some clubs were concerned that Aberdeen, who
are struggling against relegation and not providing great hope of their
survival, could be lost to the top division and that something would
have to be done to rescue them. But reconstruction for that particular
end would be morally wrong and insulting to clubs like Partick Thistle,
Falkirk, and Dundee United, who also are in jeopardy.
It is also the case that many of the larger clubs are not in favour of
changing the system so soon after the current set up of four divisions,
each of 10 clubs, was introduced. Last year, when this structure was
agreed, it was decided to stick with it for at least five years.
There are enough club chairman concerned about the possible adverse
effects on sponsorship income from yet another alteration to cast doubt
on further change.
In fact, I believe that Rangers will not attend today's meeting, and
neither will Celtic.
Without the Old Firm, any moves to enforce change would be doomed to
failure and, in fact, it required only the withdrawal of Celtic's
support from the move to create a Superleague last year to end that
particular drive. The Superleague perished with several chairmen
severely critical of Celtic's behaviour, and one can only wonder what
might be achieved this morning in the absence of the country's two most
powerful clubs.
If change is to be introduced through normal procedure, by having it
placed on the agenda of the Scottish League's annual meeting -- the next
one will be in May -- a two-thirds majority would be required. But if
change is to be pushed through in time for the start of next season, an
extraordinary general meeeting would have to be called. But a 75%
majority of votes cast would then be required, and that would be much
more difficult to achieve.
It is my understanding that one or two others who have been invited
will not attend this morning, which would mean the gathering might even
be meaningless. Then again, perhaps the meeting has been called merely
to allay fears that plans are afoot to change the set-up.
Perhaps Robinson and co will let us know, or maybe they will keep try
to keep their meeting secret.
</TEXT>
