<HEADLINE>Graham fights back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468443</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEORGE Graham came out fighting yesterday after a Caribbean holiday --
and claimed that actions taken against him amounted to a #1m fine
''without anything proved against me.''
Graham, sacked by Arsenal last month in the wake of the Premier
League's ''bung'' inquiry, was this week charged with misconduct by the
FA. He welcomed that move, in a statement through his solicitors, saying
that a properly constituted inquiry was the only way he could clear his
name.
''The Premier League inquiry was a travesty,'' said Graham. ''They had
already made their minds up and were demanding my dismissal from Arsenal
before the evidence had been presented.
''Acting on the advice of my lawyers, I declined to answer further
questions and so the FA's proceedings will be the first time that my
side of the story will be told.
''I have been given a fine of at least #1m without anything being
proved against me.''
</TEXT>
