<HEADLINE>Burns calls on fans to lift players</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Celtic played their first match at home under new manager Tommy
Burns, he had the problems, which have beset him throughout the season,
exposed in stark relief. Yesterday, as he prepared for tonight's
Scottish Cup quarter-final clash with Kilmarnock, Burns recalled that
day when he saw for himself the crisis of confidence which has struck so
many of his players.
''We had been in Ireland for three games,'' he recalled, ''and the
lads had looked good. Then we came back to Hampden to play Flamengo and
we drew the curtains back and saw all the problems we had.
''We saw players who were frightened to go out and perform at home.
They were frightened to play in front of their own fans. It has not been
so much the worry of playing at Hampden instead of Parkhead, it has been
this lack of confidence. They had had the worry of not having won a
trophy for five years and some of them have been slaughtered by the
support. But I cannot have players who are afraid to go out in front of
their own fans.
''Look, we are not talking about bad players here. Just because they
have not had success it doesn't follow that they are poor players.
Things have been very difficult here for everyone. I have arrived to
take up five years of frustration -- but I can handle that. The players
have to learn to handle their problems too. It is as simple as that.''
So far it has not been simple. It has been Burns' major problem, and
it has led him to make changes, some dramatic. Club captain Paul McStay
has been dropped this season, John Collins joined him last Sunday, and
Burns has stressed that players must show consistency if they want to
stay in the side.
He added: ''I want the support to get behind the team tomorrow night.
We need that. I know how they are feeling. Remember I am a Celtic fan
myself. I want them to place their trust in me. I will not insult them
by bringing inferior players here. But, right now, I want them to lift
the players. I don't think some fans realise how important they can
be.''
Meanwhile, Burns continues to move unwanted players out of Parkhead.
Paul Byrne has gone to Brighton on a month's loan and Mike Galloway will
stay with Leicester for a further two-month spell. After that it seems
certain the move will become permanent for a fee of around #250,000.
