<HEADLINE>Russians in step</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468446</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TITLE holders Oksana Grischuk and Evgeny Platov remained on course to
retain their ice dance crown at the World Figure Skating Championships
in Birmingham yesterday.
The Russians, who defeated Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean last
year, will lead going into today's free dance climax after having won
the original dance section at the NEC.
But Finnish couple Susanna Rahkamo and Petri Kokko, who took the
European title last month when their rivals were absent, could still
snatch gold if they win the free dance.
Rahkamo and Kokko were ranked first in the original dance by the
British judge, but the other eight judges came down in favour of the
Olympic and World champions.
Grischuk and Platov also won the compulsory dances to show they are
determined to win, despite talk of a stormy off-ice relationship and
Platov's reported knee injury which kept them out of the Europeans.
Slough's Michelle Fitzgerald and Vincent Kyle, competing in what is
usually their strongest dance, slipped two places to twenty-first
overall.
Meanwhile, Nicole Bobek -- the American who courts controversy off the
ice just as much as she thrills on it -- returns to centre-stage again
this afternoon when the women's competition gets underway.
But the 17-year-old is not expected to figure among the medals when
the event finishes tomorrow afternoon, even though she will be the
darling of the crowd.
Favourite Surya Bonaly makes her first appearance today hoping to take
the initial step to adding finally the world crown to the five European
titles she has collected.
The ''Black Pearl of France'' as she is known, will never have a
better chance, with last year's winner, Yuka Sato, and Olympic champion
Oksana Baiul both missing after having turned professional.
</TEXT>
