<HEADLINE>Stirling Tories trim the bill again.  A unique cut as average council taxes rise by 6%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>Council Tax Levels Council Tax Figures</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>TABLE</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY councillors in Stirling have repeated their feat of being the
only district in Scotland to achieve a cut in council tax bills.
Their decision to reduce the average Band D level by #3 followed
Central region's freeze on its part of the council tax, and a #1 cut in
water charges. Overall, a Band D household in Stirling will pay #623
next year, down 0.6%.
While only a small decrease, it compares favourably with a national
average rise of more than 6%, and with the increases levied on residents
in neighbouring districts in Central -- Clackmannan (4.8%) and Falkirk
(1.9%).
Last year, Stirling cut #50 from its Band D rate, although that was
partly offset by a #28 increase in the regional elements.
Other Scottish district authorities have managed to reduce their
charges this year, but found increases in the regional and water taxes
have pushed up the overall bill to residents.
Stirling's Tory group leader, Councillor Keith Harding, told
yesterday's council meeting that his budget was realistic and prudent,
and took account of the Conservatives' commitments to reduce council
tax, improve core services, and retain adequate reserves.
It meant, he added, that since taking power from Labour two years ago,
the Tories had cut the tax by 30% in real terms.
''The council is now much leaner, fitter and more efficient, and this
augurs well for staff and their jobs in the difficult period of
reorganisation and the years ahead,'' said Mr Harding.
''We look forward to taking on regional services and their budget,
with all its fat. We will take great pleasure in rendering this down --
slashing the council tax, cutting out bureaucracy, and putting more
monies into front-line services such as schools, police and social
services.''
Before the meeting, council staff hung three black balloons on
railings outside the municipal buildings in protest at the sacking of
three senior staff.
Mr Harding said the redundancies of the marketing director, Mr Paul
Crake; the head of estates services, Mr Steve Smith; and the executive
director of policy and strategic planning, Mr Phil Harding, were
regrettable, but would save #125,000 a year.
A change in council financial strategy had led to a reduction in work,
he said. ''We cannot justify paying for some staff who would not be
fully utilised.''
The council's opposition Labour group declined to produce an
alternative budget after being refused a request for a four-hour
adjournment to study the figures.
Labour leader Councillor Gillie Thomson accused the Tories of
''mortgaging the family silver'' by increasing borrowing to help pay for
the tax reduction.
* SHETLAND councillors also achieved a record yesterday when they set
the lowest tax in Scotland for the third year in a row.
Islanders will have to pay an extra 4% next year, but the #547 figure
for Band D houses is still #15 below the next lowest, set by Kincardine
and Deeside in Grampian.
However, there was little celebration at yesterday's meeting in
Lerwick, which was seen as signalling the end of the 20-year spending
bonanza of Shetland's oil era.
An 8.2% reduction in all council budgets is expected to mean some
redundancies for primary and specialist teachers, ferry passengers
facing big fare rises, and up to 500 job losses among construction
companies, as the council has halved its ambitious building programme.
Council convener Canon Lewis Smith said: ''The blame does not lie with
the council. The blame lies with the Scottish Office and the Treasury.
We have to live within the budget.''
He warned that, if the council did not make economies now, its capital
reserves would be exhausted early in the next century and would then
face cuts ''too horrific to imagine''.
* TAYSIDE councillors last night voted through a 6.8% increase in the
authority's council and water tax levels.
It will mean an extra #35 on bills for Band D households in Angus and
in Perth and Kinross, where district councillors had earlier agreed to
freeze their charges at last year's rate.
However, Dundee residents will have to pay an additional #47, as the
district authority yesterday agreed to levy an increase of #12, or 5.4%.
</TEXT>
