<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Joe still has the ball at his feet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468448</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JUST short of 20 years ago, Joe McBride was the wonderboy of Scottish
football, the teenage winger every club wanted to sign, the young man
who was offered a staggering #8000 signing on fee to join Arsenal.
The money on offer was the talk of Scottish football and his father,
Joe McBride Sr, scorer of so many goals for Celtic and Hibs among
others, guided his son through the negotiations.
Young Joe finally went to Everton. Then to Rotherham, Oldham, Hibs,
Dundee, East Fife, and now he is playing part-time for Albion Rovers,
arguably the worst senior team in Britain.
From someone who made his first-team debut for Everton in a European
clash with Feyenoord, it is quite a comedown now to be picking up #40 a
week plying his trade in front of a few hundred fans.
Yet McBride, now 34, retains his enjoyment of the game which once
promised him so much only to snatch stardom from his grasp. He will not
even blame the sport for the disappointments which dogged him and
brought him to Cliftonhill this season.
''I was silly for myself,'' he said. ''Just a stupid young kid really.
I was in the first-team squad at Everton but I wanted more. I was asking
for a guaranteed first-team place, and when that was not going to be
available I decided that I had to move on.
''That was the decision which damaged my career more than any other.
It was also the one major decision I made without consulting my old man.
If I had spoken to him then, things might have turned out differently.''
It was Emlyn Hughes who talked Joe into joining Rotherham. Hughes was
manager at the time but disastrous results led to relegation for the
Yorkshire team, Hughes was sacked, and McBride on his way to playing for
Joe Royle at Oldham.
''It's difficult to believe now when I'm playing up here in Division 3
the big names who were in the same Everton team as I was,'' he recalled.
''Brian Kidd was there and Bob Latchford. Then there was Asa Hartford
and Colin Todd and Gary Stevens came into the side just around the time
I was leaving.
''I know now that I should have stayed. After that it was all kind of
downhill. Rotherham turned out badly and then after Oldham I came back
home to Hibs.
''For a spell there it was good, but when Alex Miller took over it
became obvious that I was not the kind of player he wanted. So I went to
Dundee, and again things started well but didn't work out.
''After that it was East Fife but the travelling to and from Methil
for training was too much. I more or less walked out on them and it was
Tom Spence who persuaded me to play for Rovers.
''I had played with Tom at East Fife and he was manager at Cliftonhill
so that's how I ended up here. I can get to training in 20 minutes and
that means I can still spend time at home when I finish work instead of
being away in Fife and getting home at all hours.''
Basically McBride plays on because even at 34, and even at the bottom
of Division 3, he still enjoys playing. ''Once I lose the enjoyment
that's when I'll stop,'' he said. ''Whether you believe it or not there
are still good times in the game, still moments when you think to
yourself, that was really good.
''It doesn't matter at what level you are playing you can still find
yourself doing something which might still be a little special.''
Sometimes his dad goes to watch and take reports home for his grand
children, Sean and Joseph, who are six, and Jessica, who is four. Joe Sr
has always been there to run a critical eye over his son.
''He has never been the kind of father who looked on and said his son
was wonderful,'' said McBride Jr. ''He used to tell me that I could do
better. And he wanted me to go south initially because he didn't want me
lumbered with the whole thing of being 'Joe McBride's son,' and he was
right. I never encountered that until I went to Hibs.''
This weekend, though, young Joe's memories will become particularly
bitter-sweet. Tomorrow he will play for Rovers at Ross County -- 24
hours later he will sit in his Bishopbriggs home watching Everton face
Newcastle in the quarter-final of the English Cup.
And 24 hours after that, he will be reporting for work with
Strathclyde Region roads' department with only a few regrets for what
might have been.
After all, he did make the big time and those memories remain.
Amazingly, he collected a signing-on fee from Everton which was six
times as much as his Dad got when he joined Celtic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time for Roy to blow the bugle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>INSIDE VIEW,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979468449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is as much room for sentiment in the modern football game as
there is for a right half (remember them?) and perhaps it is no surprise
that the reaction to Aberdeen's plight ranges from indifference to
disguised glee among many neutral fans around the country. That is a
very disappointing and painful reality which the leaders of the club at
Pittodrie have to confront as they attempt to lift their side from
second bottom place in the division.
If the team suffering this indignity was Rangers or Celtic, the glee
would be undisguised, of course, but that reaction would be predictable,
given the wealth and domination these two have enjoyed over the years.
If there is no great gnashing of teeth over Aberdeen's crisis, there
has to be an explanation why this has happened to a club that had many
thousands of sympathisers from the central belt when it was taking on
and beating the Old Firm at their own game during the eighties.
Perhaps it is not too difficult to unearth. Throughout that halcyon
decade the northern team was not only excellent on the park but
dignified and civilised off it. There was an image, however accurate it
may have been, of a family club with a firm commitment to principle and
compassion.
The moment that stance appeared to be abandoned was the day the club
sacked Alex Smith, a decent man and, in retrospect, a pretty good
Aberdeen manager.
There was an inescapable sensation in football's chattering houses
that the dismissal of Smith was the beginning of the end of the Aberdeen
of old, a decision taken on purely business terms and one which has
since proved to have been been misguided. Nothing that was to happen
afterwards, even if the club had gone on to greater success than Smith
achieved (which it has not), could have erased the awareness that an era
had passed. Not only has that turned out to be true on and off the park
but there is a real danger that an alarming destiny awaits the club if
they succumb to relegation for the first time in their history.
Let me divorce myself from the glee club who may be enjoying their
discomfort. No-one should forget the debt we owe to Aberdeen for their
contribution to the Scottish game in the eighties when, along with
Dundee United, they showed that the Old Firm can be challenged
successfully. In fact, under Alex Ferguson they became the best team in
the country and for that, every non-Old Firm fan in Scotland should have
been grateful.
The dominance of either one of the Glasgow clubs can induce apathy in
fans of the other teams, a kind of what's-the-point syndrome, and the
consequence of that is not difficult to envisage.
From a practical aspect, neutrals might ponder the chances of any of
the other struggling sides, however noble their battle against
relegation is being fought, being able to challenge for the championship
one day in the future. If Aberdeen go down to the first division, where
the competition to return is immense, the Scottish game will be very
much the worse off.
The Pittodrie side must tackle a different type of competition from
now until the end of the season, one that requires the ferocity of
commitment that a fight for survival demands. They need a player who,
however well or badly he is playing himself, will metaphorically lift
his mates by their shirt tails and hurl them into the action.
Do they have one such? The caretaker manager, Roy Aitken, ought to
know the answer. If I was in his shoes, I would take them off and put on
my boots at Firhill tomorrow. It is time to blow the bugle, Roy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
