<HEADLINE>Locals are in the running</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH-trained runners should represent good value at the Ayr
two-day meeting which starts today.
Last month local handlers sent out six of the seven winners, when Pit
Pony, from David Robertson's small yard in Kilmarnock, sprang the big
surprise.
At the televised meeting in January, it was five out of seven when Len
Lungo's Sheelin Lad saw off the opposition from south of the Border in
the #12,000 feature novices chase.
At both meetings the going was heavy, stamina playing a crucial part.
It will be the same again over the next two days when conditions will be
extremely testing.
Clerk of the course Sam Morshead expects racing to go ahead on both
days despite the forecast of more rain. ''Safety is the main
consideration and as long as they don't try to go too fast, there should
be no problems,'' he said.
The prospect of heavy ground has kept today's entries low, with only
three runners in the main feature, the #5000 Mad March Hare Handicap
Chase, in which Dawn Goodfellow's Ceilidh Boy takes on course specialist
Cornet and Ninfa.
Lungo has four runners, including Noyan and Oat Couture in the Doon
Handicap Hurdle.
Sheelin Lad returns after his shock defeat by Pit Pony last month,
hoping to win the Hollybush Novices Chase, but is again burdened by top
weight.
Youandi, a recently disappointing beaten favourite at Edinburgh, will
be strongly fancied in the Lagg National Hunt Novices' Hurdle.
Sue Bradburne's Off The Bru returns after an enforced lay-off of 11
months in the Amateur Riders' Handicap Hurdle in a bid to recapture his
confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
