<HEADLINE>Docherty at home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOMMY Gilmour has won the purse bidding to stage the final eliminator
for the British featherweight championship between his own boxer, Wilson
Docherty, and former champion Peter Harris, of Wales.
The Glasgow promoter beat off opposition from Wales for the contest,
and it will now go ahead at the St Andrew's Sporting Club in Glasgow on
April 24 -- a huge boost for Docherty, who suffered the biggest
disappointment of his career in January when he lost on points to
Paisley's Michael Deveney for the vacant title.
Now the man from Condorrat, younger brother of British bantamweight
champion Drew, is back on course to make it a family double of
champions, and he has the confidence of knowing he already holds a
decision over the 32-year-old Harris.
That came in August last year when Docherty, making a defence of the
Penta Continental title, beat Harris over 12 rounds in Cardiff in what
was his best performance since turning professional.
If he can do the double over Harris, who has fought such as current
world featherweight champion Steve Robinson and former world champion
Paul Hodkinson, Docherty, will then have a second chance at the title
against either Deveney or England's Jonjo Irwin, the No.1 challenger,
who meet in Doncaster on April 21.
Said Docherty: ''This is just the boost I needed, because I have been
so down since losing to Michael. I thought I won that fight, but there
is no point looking back.
''The best thing I can do is concentrate on the Harris fight, then
make sure I don't slip up when I get another crack at the title.
''I am just very happy that Tommy Gilmour has managed to get this
eliminator for Glasgow, even although I've already beaten Harris on his
home territory.''
</TEXT>
