<HEADLINE>McRae on right road</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN HORTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468452</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Portugal's round of the world rally championship reached
two-thirds' distance in Viseu, Colin McRae, driving a Subaru Impreza,
was in third place overall.
McRae, navigated by Glasgow's Derek Ringer, swapped places with
Frenchman Didier Auriol, who overturned his Toyota Celica in yesterday's
thirteenth special stage.
The Lanark driver's normally sharp, competitive edge appears to be
blunted by mechanical problems and self-imposed pressure to ensure he
finishes this rally after having retired on the two previous
championship rounds.
Leading after 21 of the scheduled 31 gravel-track special stages is
last year's winner, Juha Kankkunen, in a Toyota Celica. The Finn,
navigated by Welshman Nicky Grist, regained the advantage from Carlos
Sainz, McRae's Subaru team-mate, and has opened a 22-second gap over the
Spaniard.
On their Portuguese debut, Richard Burns and Perth's Robert Reid,
driving an Impreza, are in eighth place. The event finishes in the
Atlantic resort of Figueira Da Foz this evening. Interim results after
21 of 31 special stages:
1, J Kankkunen/N Grist (Toyota Celica) 3hr 48min.00sec; 2, C Sainz/L
Moya (Subaru Impreza) 3-48.22; 3, C McRae/D Ringer (Subaru Impreza)
3-49.27; 4, D Auriol/B Occelli (Toyota Celica) 3-49.52; 5, A Schwarz/K
Wicha (Toyota Celica) 3-51.03; 6, B Thiry/S Prevot (Ford Escort)
3-54.01.
* THE Jim Clark Trophy has again been awarded to Colin McRae in
recognition of his achievements during last year. The trophy is awarded
annually to the Scottish driver contributing most to the sport.
</TEXT>
