<HEADLINE>Lochay farmeruses #60,000to build a shed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was almost three years ago that the former NFU president John
Cameron received the news that he was to receive #1m in compensation
from Scottish Natural Heritage for not planting a series of six 200-acre
shelter belts on his 22,000-acre Glen Lochay estate near Killin in West
Perthshire.
The judgment by the Lands Tribunal for Scotland was greeted on all
sides with incredulity. But now a more sanguine view is being taken on
all sides -- not least by the original protagonists.
Earlier this week, Mr Cameron played host to an open day at Glen
Lochay which has six Munros in its rugged terrain. More than 250 farmers
and other interested parties arrived to find out how Mr Cameron had
spent some of the compensation money. Most of them left happy with what
they had seen, if perhaps still wondering why there had been such a
fuss.
Mr Cameron has invested #60,000 in a new building to house the 1000
gimmers from his flock of 5000 blackface ewes. They certainly looked
happy and decidedly welfare friendly in their new abode. So too was Mr
Cameron.
''We can get some pretty rough weather up here with an average
rainfall of 107 inches which is 2[1/2] feet more than 30 years ago. Over
the last two or three years we've only been achieving a lambing
percentage of 40 with the gimmers and I just couldn't sleep at night
with that,'' he said.
Mr Cameron demonstrated how he had done his budgeting which showed
that with 90% lambing, the project is viable on a 30-year depreciation
scale. He also put forward another aspect to which there is no straight
financial answer. ''I believe that taking the sheep off the hills for
100 days in winter will ease grazing pressure and be good for the
environment.''
There were, of course, those in the audience who quietly wondered what
had become of the #940,000 balance from the SNH cheque. #40,000 has
already been spent on another building and more than #20,000 on an
imported go-anywhere-in-any-weather tracked vehicle from Canada.
After the proceedings were over, Mr Cameron discussed the details of
the case. He said: ''The award was, in the first instance, #650,000
which was reckoned to be the difference in the value of the property by
not having the trees and their shelter and that which the court felt it
would be worth if my plans had gone ahead.
''The rest was made up by interest charges at a time of very high
rates in the three years it took for the appeal to be heard, plus my not
inconsiderable legal costs.''
Asked whether he would rather have had the trees or the cash, Mr
Cameron responded: ''I'm a traditionalist and on balance I think the
shelter belts would have been better for the glen as a whole helping the
entire flock and the cattle and not forgetting the deer who gain nothing
from the new shed.''
Mr Cameron said that he could have done nothing at Glen Lochay with
the money and instead could have bought a yacht in the West Indies. But
he added: ''That's not for me. I am a farmer and the balance of the
money will come back into agriculture.
</TEXT>
