<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boost for Cousins</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STEVEN Cousins produced the best performance by a British male skater
for 15 years when he finished eighth at the World Figure Skating
Championships in Birmingham last night.
The 22-year-old Deeside skater's hopes of a first major medal were
dashed when he dropped two places in the long programme as Elvis Stojko
of Canada retained his title.
But it was an improvement on his tenth spot in Japan last year -- and
the highest placing by a Briton since his namesake, Robin, won the
silver medal in Dortmund in 1980.
America's Todd Eldredge, who had led after the short programme, had to
settle for second place with Frenchman Philippe Candeloro taking the
bronze medal.
Clive Shorten of Stevenage revelled in the huge British support at the
near capacity 7000 crowd at the NEC also toproduce the best performance
of his career to finish nineteenth.
Cousins -- dressed in a Sgt Pepper's outfit as he skated to a medley
of John Lennon and Paul McCartney tunes -- paid for a fall during one of
his triple jumps as he dropped from his sixth place in the short
programme.
But he will be delighted for Stojko -- the duo train under the same
coach, Doug Leigh, in Canada -- who defied an ankle injury to take the
title for a second time.
Stojko clinched gold with a near-perfect performance -- and indeed one
judge gave him a perfect 6.0 for technical merit. There were also five
5.9s for merit and another four for interpretation.
Cousins, the six-times British champion, was last to skate -- doing
the high fives with Stojko as the 23-year-old Canadian left the ice
knowing the gold medal was his.
But despite the support of the huge home crowd, and another impressive
interpretation of the music, it was not enough to achieve the miracle
Cousins felt he needed to take a medal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
