<HEADLINE>One-time hell-raiser is back on track.  McGillivary ready to put the foot down</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Barcelona,
AILEEN McGillivary used to be a hell-raiser. The fast lady of Scottish
athletics, with more national sprint titles than any other woman, she
also has a record of putting the needle into the red off the track --
not just in her car, but in her social life as well.
Today, however, the multi-titled national sprint champion will channel
her zest for life into what she does best, when she makes her senior
debut for Britain over 60 metres at the World Indoor championships in
Barcelona.
She admits to having paid the penalty for fast driving in her
1.6-litre Escort, and for topping up her personal tank with an
occasional excess of Southern Comfort. ''When I was younger, I was a
nightmare to my coach, Stewart Hogg,'' she confessed. ''We used to fall
out -- but I'm older now, more mature. I know where I am going, and we
get on great.''
More than 15 years of working with footballers at Ibrox, Tannadice
and, whisper it, most recently at Pittodrie, did not necessarily equip
former British professional sprint champion Hogg to deal with a
precocious tearaway with exceptional talent.
For a spell she arranged her own sessions, because the ones which Hogg
had set out interfered with her social life. ''I wanted to be out with
my chums every Friday, Saturday, and Sunday night,'' she said. ''I
wanted the best of both worlds. I was awful.''
Hogg discovered she had not trained with the group. ''He hung up the
phone on me,'' said Aileen. ''I called him after nearly a fortnight. I
found out that he was on the brink of writing, advising me to go to
another coach.''
Hogg confided this week that what infuriated him was his certainty
that McGillivary had real ability, but that she was wasting her talent.
In addition to winning the British pro 120-yard title in 1967, Fifer
Hogg also ran second in the Powderhall Sprint, experiences which he put
to good use, helping Tom Boyle build a sprint finish into European 3000m
champion Yvonne Murray.
''I was hard on Aileen because she told me she wanted to be the best
in Britain,'' said Hogg. ''But she did not understand what was required.
She wanted to have her cake and eat it. But once Aileen realised what it
was about, she never made the same mistake twice. She is a very fast
learner.''
McGillivary, 24, admits however that she found it particularly hard to
confess to Hogg that she and boyfried Greg were having a house built,
and planned to set up home. ''But my running has got better and better
since we moved in together.''
Greg, a rugby winger with Cumbernauld, regularly helps out with
training. ''He can beat me out of the blocks -- the first time,'' said
Aileen. ''But once we have done a few reps, he finds it hard to catch
me.''
Some years ago, McGillivary gave up the chance of playing football in
Italy. ''I played with Cumbernauld Cosmos, and was to go for a trial.
I'd to choose between football and athletics. I have no regrets.''
She began athletics life as an 800m runner, coached by her dad,
Harvey. ''I used to jog round, then sprint the last 100m,'' she said.
''When I did take up sprinting, I remember we worked out that I was
seventeenth fastest in the West District over 100m. I thought it was
great.''
Mum Agnes, also a qualified coach, trained Aileen until she won her
first Great Britain vest as a junior over 200m. ''I think she panicked
then,'' said Aileen. ''She worried that if I didn't go it might be her
fault -- that she might not have done me justice. Mum spoke to Hoggy,
and that's how we got together.''
She agrees that she perhaps became too intense, but it did not stop
her winning the Europa Cup sprint for Britain, East Germans et al. ''I
have learned how to relax now, not to take myself so seriously,'' she
said. But her commitment is unquestioned.
The Halifax Building Society in Falkirk, where she works as a customer
service assistant, have given her six months' unpaid leave to pursue her
ambition of a 200m place at the World outdoor championships this year.
Ayrshire building contractor Alex Moir, who has backed her for the past
five years, is making up the lost wages.
Under Hogg's guidance McGillivary has won six Scottish 100m titles,
surpassing Margot Wells' record of five. In nearly eight years with Hogg
she has become faster every season, save last year, when injury struck.
She qualified for the Commonwealth Games in Victoria on the final day,
but then was injured again in Canada. ''I was in a room with five other
competitors. I laughed and joked my way through the Games. But as soon
as my event went on track, I cracked up. I flew home the next day, and
was in tears as I watched the closing ceremony on TV.
''I've had my problems -- had to sleep on the floor for a month, with
back trouble, but the worst was the hamstring, and then the calf last
year.''
Hogg, through his football contacts, arranged two costly magnetic
resonance image scans, which finally identified the problem. David
McLean, the SRU fitness advisor helped put McGillivary back together
again.
''But I could only rebuild my lost confidence myself -- it is a
fragile thing, but paramount in sprinting. I have regained it indoors
this winter.''
Despite being beaten by her pal, Melanie Neef, the first Scot to do so
in five-and-a-half years, McGillivary has run inside her previous best
for 60m four times this winter, and now holds the national record
jointly with Neef at 7.36. That could easily fall today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
