<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BTR results should restore confidence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE, CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIAL conglomerate BTR gave the City a big fright last September
when it reported that first-half margins were under pressure from higher
raw material costs and had dipped from 15.7% to 15.2%.
Later in the year it sought to allay these fears by promising a better
second half but the shares have remained under a cloud.
Yesterday's full-year results, though, should go some way to restore
confidence in the share price and also encouraged an upgrading in
analysts' forecasts for 1995.
Profits for the year emerge up 10.8% from #1274m to #1412m ahead of
tax. At the operating level ahead of disposals and interest they rose
13.6% from #1298m to #1475m on sales of the continuing operations up
12.2% to #9111m.
Margins for the year have been boosted to 16.2% reflecting a
second-half surge to 17.1% and the outlook generally is regarded as
promising.
Shareholders are to receive a better-than-expected 10.2% rise to 13.5p
with a final, up from 7.3p to 8.3p. This is covered 1.8 times by
earnings per share of 24.5p.
BTR chief executive Alan Jackson is able to report that the improving
trends in sales and orders have continued through the last quarter of
1994 and into the early months of 1995. And he reassures the market that
during this period BTR has continued to be successful in mitigating the
impact of the rise in raw material costs by price increases and through
productivity and buying improvements.
Productivity and efficiency savings added some #78m to operating
profit last year. Volumes are also improving.
The better trading conditions which the company has seen in many of
its major markets in the last quarter of 1994 were particularly
noticeable in the US and Australasia. Many of BTR's US-based groups have
experienced buoyant order positions.
Demand in the automotive and construction sectors remained strong in
Australia throughout the year. And despite some commentators' forecasts
for slower growth in the economy later in 1995, progress in most of
BTR's groups in Australia is expected to continue this year. Group
operations in South-east Asia have continued to benefit from
above-average growth rates.
In the UK the picture is more cloudy. Economic growth has been less
marked although most operations in the automotive, industrial
manufacturing and construction sectors have improved on 1993. But
against a background of some political uncertainty and rising interest
rates, together with sluggish order activity in rail and electric power
contract business, patchy growth at home is expected to continue.
In Continental Europe it has been a year of consolidation after the
steep decline into recession in 1993. BTR reckons that decisive
management action has left it well placed to benefit from the gradual
growth anticipated in most major European markets in 1995.
Analysts welcomes the results and also the company's decision to
retreat from issuing warrants after six years. The conversion of
warrants restricts pace of earnings per share growth in the short term.
BTR is looking for a further increase in sales and profits in 1995,
supported by the current improving trend in orders. The company will
continue to focus on improving its results by ongoing attention to cost
control, productivity, seeking profitable growth opportunities to its
existing businesses and, inevitably and fashionably, by searching for
acquisitions which will add to the core businesses.
At 312p, up 4p yesterday, BTR is selling at just under 13 times
historic earnings on a yield of 5.8%, a rating which could now be due
for an upward adjustment.
Mr Jackson retires at the end of the year and is to be succeeded by
the highly-regarded Ian Strachan, formerly deputy chief executive of
mining conglomerate RTZ.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rolls-Royce fliespast #100m mark</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROLL-Royce propelled profits past #101m in 1994, ahead of City
estimates, as it continued to slash its workforce, figures released
yesterday showed. The aero-engine giant lifted taxable profits from #76m
the previous year.
Restructuring at the company has continued ahead of plan, said
chairman Sir Ralph Robins. He believes the company is in good shape to
cope with poor market conditions in its two main businesses of aerospace
and industrial power.
At the year-end the workforce stood at 41,000, a reduction of 10% in
the year and more than 20% since the programme was announced in 1993.
During the year, Rolls-Royce's job cutting cost #95m in restructuring
charges. Sir Ralph said there were no plans for any further provisions
or major plant closures although the drive for cost reductions and
efficiency gains will continue.
The company's research and development spending is set to fall sharply
because the company has completed development of its new Trent engines
which were principally designed for the new Airbus A330 and Boeing 777
airliners.
Group sales fell to #3200m against #3500m in 1993, reflecting the
anticipated decline in military engine deliveries and reduced level of
business in industrial power. In a highly competitive market, just over
400 civil aero engines were delivered and important contracts were
secured in the industrial power business.
In aerospace, sales declined by 8% and by 13% in the industrial power
group. In the aerospace business, the fall was attributable to the lower
level of activity in the military sector, which had been expected. Sales
were flat in the commercial sector, both for engines and spares.
The chairman said that the 1994 results, despite lower sales,
reflected ''both the greater efficiency arising from our continued
restructuring and the successful development of the Trent 700 and 800
engines which have passed significant milestones in the past year''.
The group's order book stands at #5900m compared with #6200m a year
ago. Its balance sheet is strong with net cash at the year-end of #285m.
Dividends are pegged at 5p, in line with expectations, on earnings of
6.62p against 5.95p. The shares gained 1[1/2]p to 149[1/2]p.
HILLSDOWN Holdings expects 1995 to be as tough as 1994 for the food
industry but hopes that cost savings and small bolt-on acquisitions will
enable profits to continue to advance.
Pre-tax profits rose 6% to #172m in 1994 which encouraged chairman Sir
John Nott to be less defensive than hitherto. The dividend total was
increased from 8.8p to 9.2p with a 7p final. The shares dropped 7p to
173p where they yield 6.6%.
Profits were down sharply in meat and produce but poultry and ambient
salads were well ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
