<DOCNO>GH950310-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bus giant told to sell Mainline stake Government ruling puts the skids on Stagecoach shares</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Stagecoach Holdings hit the skids yesterday, after a
Government competition ruling which analysts believe casts doubt on its
aggressive expansion strategy.
The Department of Trade and Industry took an even tougher line than
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission on Stagecoach's acquisition last
summer of 20% of the Mainline Partnership bus group in South Yorkshire.
Corporate Affairs Minister Jonathan Evans ruled that Stagecoach must
sell its entire holding after the MMC said the Perth-based company's
stake might be expected to operate against the public interest.
Stagecoach, the UK's largest bus operator, will also have to give up
its seat on the Mainline board, although it is taking legal opinion and
may seek judicial review.
The MMC had merely proposed a bar on Stagecoach acquiring any more of
the company.
Shares in Stagecoach, whose #8.3m acquisition of a 20% stake in
Glasgow's Strathclyde Buses is currently under investigation by the MMC,
tumbled 28p to 209p.
The MMC is also investigating bus services in the north-east of
England. Operators there have complained about alleged anti-competitive
behaviour by Stagecoach-owned Busways Travel Services.
The Perth-based company's aggressive growth strategy contrasts sharply
with that of one of the sector's few other quoted companies,
Aberdeen-based GRT Bus Group. GRT has expanded more slowly and bought
with cash.
With Stagecoach shares on a relatively high rating, the City is
perhaps now worried there will be an insufficient profits stream from
mainly paper acquisitions to compensate for the resultant dilution of
earnings per share. It may require some convincing by the company.
Bill McCall, a director of stockbroker Tilney &amp; Co, said: ''There are
a couple of other referrals to look at. There is a bit of doubt and the
last thing the market wants is uncertainty.''
However, Brian Souter, executive chairman of Stagecoach, stressed
there would be no change in strategy.
Believing the City's reaction overdone, he added: ''I think it
probably comes from all the nonsense there has been in the last
fortnight from regulators in other industries. I think it results from a
misunderstanding of what happens in the bus industry.''
Earlier investigations have normally ended with Stagecoach giving
assurances about the levels of fares and frequency of services.
The DTI has only twice before issued a divestment ruling. In
Portsmouth, Stagecoach ultimately negotiated partial divestment, while
in Hastings it eventually satisfied the DTI with undertakings.
Reluctant to predict the outcome of the Strathclyde Buses'
investigation, Mr Souter stressed the MMC took each case on its own
merits.
He said the DTI ruling did not stop Stagecoach, whose minority
holdings account for a quarter of its 8400 buses, acquiring companies in
areas where it had no existing presence.
The MMC concluded the relationship between Stagecoach and Mainline was
a significant deterrent to new entrants to the South Yorkshire bus
market, had reduced actual and potential competition between the two
operators, and enhanced Mainline's ability to weaken smaller companies.
It concluded that a merger situation had been created because
Stagecoach had the ability to exercise material influence over
Mainline's policy.
</TEXT>
