<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#1500 fine for trainer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAINER David Nicholson has been fined #1500 after having been found
guilty of violent and improper conduct and bringing racing into
disrepute by the Jockey Club.
Five days before the Cheltenham Festival he was convicted of
threatening and using obscene language towards Edward Whitaker, a racing
photographer.
After a long hearing yesterday, Nicholson emerged from the inquiry
claiming to be ''delighted, but not with the fine. I was found not to
have hit Whitaker.''
The trainer was summoned to Portman Square following a fracas that
followed the running of the King George VI Chase at Kempton on Boxing
Day.
He clashed with Whitaker as the photographer attempted to take
pictures of Nicholson consoling his jockey, Adrian Maguire, who had been
unseated from Barton Bank at the last fence.
Whitaker claimed Nicholson had struck him, and at yesterday's hearing
produced a witness.
Nicholson said: ''I didn't hit him and that's been proven. I expect
some apologies from somewhere. It's a stiff fine but nothing a large
brandy wouldn't cure.''
Jenny Pitman was the last trainer to be punished when she was fined
#200 for striking Jamie Osborne in the face at Ayr in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Torrance trails Cejka</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALEXANDER Cejka, already being hailed as the next German superstar to
follow Bernhard Langer, equalled the course record with a six-under-par
66 in the first round of the Moroccan Open in Agadir yesterday.
Only last Sunday 24-year-old Cejka gained his first European PGA tour
victory, when he carried off the Andalucia Open title in Spain, and he
is determined to prove it was no fluke.
Yesterday, despite taking pain-killers and medicine to combat water on
the knee, he tamed the King Hassan-owned Royal Golf Links with a round
that included only 26 putts.
Cejka leads Scotland's Sam Torrance by one shot with five other
players, including Irishman Eamonn Darcy and Sheffield's Malcolm
Mackenzie, on 68.
Torrance, who is playing well enough to win a Ryder Cup place for the
eighth successive time this year, set the early pace when he birdied six
holes and had only one bogey for his 67.
''That's as nice as I can play,'' said Torrance. ''I had a long rest
in the winter and it has done me the world of good.''
It looked as if Torrance would lead, but Cejka, starting late from the
tenth, went to the turn in a four-under-par 32 and then birdied the
first and third to go to six under. He parred the last six holes.
On two-under-par 70 were four more Scots -- Gary Orr, Craig Ronald,
Gordon Brand Jr, and Andrew Coltart. Leading scores (British or Irish
unless stated):
