<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pillars of decency crying out to be built around</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>CONFERENCE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979468466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AND so to Inverness for what, I fear to think, must be my twenty-first
Scottish Labour Party Conference. Particularly in this venue, it is a
chance to meet old friends and re-visit familiar arguments. The nights
will be late and the humour good, but there my predictions end.
The tragedy, which must form the backdrop to everything we say and do,
is that 16 of these years have been spent without a Labour Government.
For those here this weekend under the age of 30, there is no first-hand
recollection that government can be a force for good. It is an article
of faith and common sense.
This is a vacuum which our opponents seek to fill with false history
and doctrines of despair. But the attacks of Toryism and sneers of
nationalism disguise the essential fact of post-war politics -- that
none of them would dare reverse the great social legislation which
Labour alone has given to this country in the teeth of opposition.
Yes, an enormous amount has been eroded since 1979. But the pillars of
decency which Labour put in place -- the NHS, welfare state,
comprehensive education, equal opportunities, and the rights of working
people -- are still just about in place; crying out to be reinforced and
built around.
I sometimes think that a party political broadcast should be devoted
simply to listing the lasting monuments to Labour Governments for the
benefit of a generation which might be deceived into believing that
''they're all the same''. They are not, never were, and never will be.
After 16 years in opposition, there are few in Labour's ranks who have
held ministerial office. I doubt if that is such a bad thing. On so many
fronts, there will be the prospect of radical thinking and a fresh
start. Inadvertently we have skipped a generation. I would hope and
expect that the Labour Government of 96 or 97 is more self-confident and
less in awe of the Sir Humphreys than any that has gone before; that its
determination to achieve will have been sharpened by the long wait.
But first we have to get there and anyone who believes it is in the
bag is suffering from self-delusion. In the months leading up to the
election, the Tories, their press, and their financiers will fight like
cornered vermin.
One need look only at the vast unearned wealth currently slushing
around in the privatised utilities to understand the size of the stakes.
I simply don't believe these stories about the Tories going into an
election under-funded. There are too many vested interests for that to
happen.
The Labour Party has been set a simple test by Tony Blair. It is to
say what we mean and mean what we say. If we can pass that test with the
electorate, we will be unstoppable. But first we have to pass the
internal examination.
There is a large school of thought which maintains that the Clause 4
debate should never have been opened up. Let sleeping albatrosses lie.
That is neither a radical nor particularly honest position, even if it
has a very obvious appeal when we are 20% or 30% ahead in the polls.
I certainly don't expect a watered-down form of words to emerge from
this process. And the ones which are finally approved will have the
force and relevance which comes from being written in 1995 rather than
1917.
A commitment made during the First World War can be dismissed as an
antique, held in affection but not meant to be taken seriously. That is
indeed the story of Clause 4 as it stands, behind the protestations that
it is immortal, timeless, and enshrines everything we hold dear.
It doesn't and never did. But whatever summary of our aims and values
emerges from the current process will be incapable of concealment or
denial, because it will have been newly minted for the express purpose
of defining what we stand for.
We're often told that Clause 4 is never brought up on the doorsteps as
a reason for not voting Labour. True enough. But how often do Labour
Party members feel bold enough to raise it in a positive way, by pulling
out the party card and saying: ''Look! This is what we are about''?
There is no argument for no change, other than that the debate should
not have been opened. And that isn't really an argument at all.
So let's have a good conference, a passionate debate, and a vote which
will take us one step closer to the only function which justifies
political activity for socialists.
And lest we forget, that is the exercise of power in a way which will
advance the interests of the many rather than the few, and bequeath to
our children a better world than the one which we inherited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rise in cow slaughtering</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468467</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAIRY farmers concerned at the cost of exceeding milk quota limits
have contributed to a sharp rise in cow slaughterings in the final
quarter of 1994. The January total, including adult bulls, was estimated
to have reached 93,000 head, an increase of 40% over the previous
January.
Despite high slaughterings, prices have risen. The grade one average
was 92.4p a kg, an increase of 4p over the same period last year.
The Meat and Livestock Commission expect that the current pressure to
cull cows will ease during the second quarter of this year.
A Likely reduction in the level of slaughterings, combined with
progressively lower availability of manufacturing beef from stocks
across the European Union, should continue to provide strength to the
cull cow trade as the year progresses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Welcome rest for Nicol</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Peter Nicol claimed his place in the semi-finals of the
#30,000 Portuguese Open in Lisbon yesterday without striking a ball when
opponent Anthony Hill was forced to withdrew through illness.
The Australian world No.9, winner of the Stroh Open in Calcutta last
week, had visited hospital with breathing problems following his
second-round win over England's Paul Johnson on Wednesday.
''X-rays showed that I had a lung infection, which I suspect I picked
up in India,'' said the 25-year-old, who had reached the last eight with
two convincing victories.
''I've been put on antibiotics, and it's not worth taking the risk of
playing in what would be sure to be a very hard match against Peter.''
For Nicol, the removal of a potentially punishing clash came as a
great relief. The world No.5 has also suffered health problems with a
bout of tonsilitis in the build-up to this week. He said: ''It's good
for me that I have had an extra day's rest.''
Winner of the US and Singapore Opens this season, 21-year-old Nicol
now meets world No.1 and defending champion, Jansher Khan. He defeated
his unrelated namesake Zarak Jahan Khan.
Nicol's aim tonight will be to repeat his Welsh classic win of 13
months ago against Jansher, although in their most recent meeting the
Pakistani scored an easy win in the final of the Hong Kong Open.
In the other semi, England's World No.2 Peter Marshall meets
Australia's Rodney Eyles, who is just one place lower. Quarter-final
results:
(4) P Nicol (Scotland) beat (7) A Hill (Aus) w/o; (2) P Marshall
(England) beat (9) S Elopuro (Finland) 15-12, 15-10, 15-6; (3) R Eyles
(Australia) beat (5) Simon Parke (England) 15-11, 15-9, 6-0, retired
injured; (1) Jansher Khan (Pakistan) beat (8) Zarak Jahan Khan
(Pakistan) 15-5, 15-5, 15-11.
