<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MLC survey shows upsurge in beef exports to Continent</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE INGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEEF exports appear to have staged a remarkable recovery from the
severe disruption caused last autumn by German attempts to ban British
supplies and the restrictions imposed under the EU compromise aimed at
settling that dispute.
Latest indications are that sales of British beef into Continental
markets were actually higher in the first few weeks of this year than in
early 1994, although trade with Germany virtually ceased.
Totally reliable figures are not available because a new trade
recording system is not yet fully operational. It replaces customs
statistics which ended with the advent of the single market two years
ago.
However, Meat and Livestock Commission staff now run a regular survey
of trading companies and have calculated that British exporters shipped
nearly 8% more beef to other EU states in January than 12 months
earlier.
German demand evaporated in the light of fears of catching ''mad cow
disease'' but fears that BSE panic might spread across the Continent
have proved groundless. Germany was not a particularly significant
market for the British industry, although a couple of individual
companies will have been badly hurt by the loss of trade.
Much more important for livestock producers in general is France. The
French meat trade, in particular its catering sector, is traditionally
by far the biggest outlet for British beef exporters.
The commodity the French want predominantly is cowbeef, which
indicates why the BSE controversy was potentially so devastating.
The threat was not primarily from consumers terrified by BSE, because
the French are not usually much concerned with such issues. Instead,
exporters fretted over the risk of losing the trade for bone-in cow
carcases and cuts because trade restrictions authorised by the European
Commission, in an attempt to pacify the Germans, discriminated against
these products.
Exporters have overcome the obstacles. The MLC's latest survey shows
that January shipments to France are back up to within about 10% of the
volumes sold a year earlier.
Exporter demand to serve this revived trade probably helps explain the
surprising strength of cow prices in the face of the extremely high
culling rates over recent months.
The most startling aspect of the trade has been demand from the
Italian market, where Inverurie-based ANM Group is particularly active.
Italy's purchases of British beef more than doubled between January 1994
and the first few weeks of this year, according to the MLC's new
figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faldo maintains form</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBINSON HOLLOWAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE presence of so many Europeans in Florida this month has
temporarily made the US Tour seem like the world tour that Greg Norman
once envisaged -- and the Europeans are more than justifying their
places in the Honda Classic field here in Fort Lauderdale, Florida.
Nick Faldo, winner last week at Doral, shot a four-under-par 67 to
finish the first round in third place two off of the lead, held by Jim
McGovern, and one behind 1989 Open champion Mark Calcavecchia.
One behind Faldo was Ian Woosnam, while Severiano Ballesteros hit his
only bad shot of the day into water on his last hole. The Spaniard ended
on 70, still a strong score given the strong winds.
The Europeans who played in the afternoon also fared well, with Colin
Montgomerie shooting a 69 that included two chip-ins, one for eagle, the
other time for one of his three birdies. Bernhard Langer, who played
with McGovern, shot 70.
Faldo had four birdies on Weston Hills' front nine, the first time he
had seen that stretch this week. He had planned to play them in the
pro-am, which was cancelled.
He said: ''I played very solidly. It was tough out there and I got off
to a good start. Most of the day I was looking at 25 feet or better on
the greens. The back nine was really tough with the wind. But I only
made one mistake, underclubbing on the thirteenth.''
Woosnam, playing his first competitive round since December, played
his front nine in three under par. He said: ''On the front nine I played
fantastic. I had a putt for birdie on every hole. I couldn't believe
that I hadn't played for three months.'' Leading scores (Americans
unless stated):
65 -- J McGovern.
66 -- M Calcavecchia.
67 -- N Faldo (England), D Barr (Canada).
68 -- I Woosnam (Wales), M Wiebe, M Sullivan, M O'Meara, L Rinker.
69 -- K Clearwater, S Rintoul (Australia), G Sauers, C Montgomerie
(Scotland), B Claar, S Stricker, B Lohr, J Haas, V Singh (Fiji), L
Janzen, A Magee, K Fergus.
Other scores included: 70 -- S Ballesteros (Spain). 71 -- D Feherty (N
Ireland). 72 -- J Parnevik (Sweden).
</TEXT>
