<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Powerful dressing.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ROAD TESTS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay marks the big German's progress
THE coffee stop on our first drive of the Audi A4 was at the famous
Prescott Speed Hill Climb Course near Cheltenham. Roy Lane, several
times British hill climb champion, runs a competition driving school
there, and we were invited to chauffeur him up the hill in a much faster
Audi laid on for the occasion -- a Porsche-modified Avant RS2.
Having watched Roy hurtle his almost Formula One-specification
single-seater up climbs like Doune and Fintray, I thought that was an
absolutely ludicrous suggestion. It would have been like going to
Murrayfield and asking Gavin Hastings to watch my pitiful attempts at
kicking a penalty goal. So I insisted that Roy drove me, then sat back
and enjoyed the experience, being amused to see that, turning down the
return road, he slightly muffed a gear change. Ah, I said loftily, Audi
has never built a decent gear change yet.
For a company so intense about its high-tech design work, Audi seems
unable to get away from a rather sloppy gear lever, although the A4's is
better than some. On the other hand, there is nothing remotely sloppy
about the brake pedal action. Look at it sideways and the anchors slam
on. I would prefer a more progressive approach.
If this report so far makes the A4 seem something of a dog, we had
better move on to the good news. It is a far more stylish car than the
Audi 80 it replaces, impeccably built, and a great advance on the
earlier model in terms of engineering, finish, performance and economy.
The A4 has a revised choice of engines, a brand new interior, and
front suspension from the elegant, mostly aluminium A8. It is far more
refined than any model of the 80 series ever managed to be.
On the launch, I tried a 1.6-litre which starts at #14,920, and a 1.8
which starts at #16,745. The basic range includes a turbo diesel, a
1.8-litre turbo sport, and a couple of 2.6-litre V6 variants, topped by
a quattro at #22,845. There are also special equipment models at prices
from #16,450.
The 1.8 is the first car in this class with a five-valve layout --
three inlet and two exhaust per cylinder. Better gas flow is the result,
not so much to increase power output as to enhance the torque and fuel
consumption. The power is there, all the same, because the A4's 125bhp
is 10bhp more than you get from the superseded two-litre Audi 80, and a
high figure for the class. Torque is up too, although I am surprised
that the peak comes at a much higher engine speed than in the older car.
You can expect to whistle the 1.8 to 60mph in about 10.5 seconds, and
it has a test track maximum above 125mph. But Audi makes sturdily built
cars these days and, while the A4 is lighter than the 80, it does not
have an entirely favourable power to weight ratio.
However, there are few complaints about its fuel economy. The Audi
cannot match a lean-burn engine in this department, but it should return
something like 48mpg at 56mph, 37 at 75 and 28mpg in town.
Handling and ride quality are in a completely different league from
the 80's. Like the braking system, the steering is uncommonly light, for
a European car, anyway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Halifax and Leeds seek High Court approval.  Investors in line for share bonanza</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Halifax and the Leeds Permanent Building Societies' members could
get around 600 shares each as a basic allocation in addition to perhaps
another 5% arising from balances between #1000 and #50,000.
The two societies are seeking High Court approval on March 20 which
would allow them to be more generous in the extent of their offer in the
proposed merger than Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester which is being taken over
by Lloyds Bank.
Any investor who has at least #100 in share accounts with either
society or is a holder of their permanent interest-bearing securities
will qualify for the basic distribution of a fixed number of free
shares.
In addition, those of two years' standing and with share account
balances of between #1000 and #50,000 will receive a variable
distribution depending on the size of the total balance. But unlike at
C&amp;G where there were legal restraints, borrowers will be entitled to the
fixed amount of shares as long as the loan is in excess of #100.
The court judgment is expected soon after the hearing and is necessary
as there is ambiguity in the Building Societies Act between Sections 108
and 109 as to whether members who have invested for less than two years
have the right to any distribution.
Halifax chairman Jon Foulds said that there had been very friendly
discussions with the Building Societies' Commission on this point and
which approached the court to determine its legality.
If the court agrees, then members will be asked in the spring to agree
the merger which will create Britain's third-largest bank with assets of
around #90bn. It will considerably increase competition in the financial
services area such as personal loans although there is a consequent risk
of upwards pressure on costs to the disadvantage of both investors and
housebuyers.
There will be a separate vote to convert the combined group to plc
status with the subsequent issue of shares.
Mr Foulds said he would be disappointed if the market capitalisation
was less than #8000m but he did not expect it to exceed #10bn. He was
non-committal as to whether the enlarged Halifax would seek new capital.
With around 10 million accounts, the merger will create by far the
largest share register in the world with some 7.5 million investors and
2.5 million borrowers as well as employees and pensioners who will get
the fixed number of shares.
The allocation of shares will be loaded towards the basic rights of
membership, Mr Foulds said, but he would give no indication as to what
the weighting would be. Analysts are expecting that on the basis of an
#8000m market value about #6000m would be appropriated to the basic
distribution with the other #2000m being disbursed according to
qualifying balances.
The matter has been complicated by the allocation of free shares being
influenced by the lowest qualifying balance on each account on a number
of reference dates -- the first being midnight on November 25 last year.
Other dates will be announced in due course and some of these may be
retrospective. There will be a number of variable narrow bands with a
minimum of #1000 and a maximum of #50,000 to qualify for the free
shares.
There is a Halifax-Leeds merger helpline 0800 888 844.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Art in print</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is disappointing that your critic, Clare Henry, is not more
positive about the current exhibition, Contemporary British Art in
Print, at the Scottish National Gallery of Modern Art.
The keeper and his staff should be congratulated not castigated for
their initiative. This exhibition is the first since the 1980 show at
the Tate devoted to the Kelpra Studio to acknowledge the contribution
made to British art by a print publisher.
The contribution is all the more remarkable for its high quality in
this case, as it has been made by an individual working in collaboration
with a series of different print workshops, both north and south of the
Border.
Exhibitions of the kind at present on display at Belford Road,
accompanied by very informative catalogues giving full credit to the
artists and printers involved in similar print publications across the
Atlantic, are regularly mounted by leading American museums and are
highly acclaimed internationally.
It is no accident that Scotland has been the venue for this exhibition
but a tribute to the strength of its contemporary printmaking.
Let us hope that this show, devoted to the Paragon Press, is the first
of a series and that future exhibitions, held not just in Edinburgh but
in other British cities, will highlight the best publications of the
Scottish printmaking workshops among others.
Martin Hopkinson,
Curator,
Hunterian Art Gallery,
University of Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drinks level</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANN SHAW described research into a new drug for the management of
alcohol-related problems being evaluated at the Royal Edinburgh Hospital
(February 23).
She correctly quoted the Guidelines for Sensible Drinking as 21 units
a week for a man or 14 units for a woman, but can I emphasise that one
unit is the amount of alcohol contained in half a pint of beer, in one
single measure of spirits, or in one glass of wine.
Dr Bruce Ritson,
Consultant,
Alcohol Problems Clinic,
Edinburgh Health Care
NHS Trust,
Royal Edinburgh Hospital,
Morningside Place,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
