<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enterprise Oil seesprofits ease by #6m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENTERPRISE Oil had some comfort last year in that it was able to
increase oil production by 27% and can look forward to a 38% increase by
1997.
Chairman and chief executive Graham Hearne does need some consolation
after losing the bitter #1300m battle to acquire fellow independent
Lasmo and to make up for the rotten oil price.
The average price received was down by over #1 a barrel -- from #11.58
to #10.34 -- and there are few bulls around at present who expect to see
much forward movement in the short to medium term.
As already known, the Lasmo bid cost about #24m, including the
write-down on the 9.8% stake in Lasmo to 150p (now 153p).
Pre-tax profits eased #6m to #94m but at the attributable level there
was a 25% decline to #71m. The dividend is being held at 16p as it has
since 1992 and just covered by earnings of 16.8p before allowing for the
Lasmo costs.
Fortunately cash flow, excluding the investment in Lasmo Exploration
last year, is very positive and resulted in 23 wells being drilled, of
which half had a positive result. This time, some 40 wells will be
drilled which will boost the budget by #40m to #130m.
The offset is the continuing attempt to reduce operating costs. These
fell by a sixth in 1994 to #2.83 and finance director Andrew Shilston
expects to cut another 30p off this year when production should start
rising further towards the 1997 peak of 250,000 barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A personal view</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WRITE to express my profound disappointment that James Allison,
Labour Party Scottish Organiser (1977-1991), has chosen to reward the
unquestionable loyalty of party members and staff with an autobiography
penned in his own inimitable style (March 6,7,8).
I do not wish to contest the remarkable 20/20 hindsight or the
accuracy of the selective quotations from the many entries in Allison's
famed diary. I simply wish to point out to your readers that this is a
highly personal view of the recent history of the Labour Party in
Scotland.
As a member of the Labour by-election team and having worked closely
with many of those named in Monday's extract, most notably Donald Dewar
and Murray Elder, I am offended by Allison's contemptuous tone.
It is my belief that the humiliation at the hands of the SNP at Govan
was the catalyst for modernising Labour's by-election team, both
candidate support and campaigning techniques. In contrast to Allison's
obdurate dismissal of these developments, it is a testament to the
humility, talent, and political maturity of most members of Labour's
team that they were able to learn from the experience of defeat.
And go on to secure the subsequent victories in Glasgow Central and
Paisley North and South.
It is all too easy for an embittered employee of an organisation to
embark on a personal vendetta against those whose ideas and
determination to modernise he could not accept nor democratically defeat
while in office. It is indeed fortunate for the Labour Party, if not
your columns, that all the other participants in these debates have put
the duties of their office to the fore.
I hope that this letter expresses the sentiment of myself and others
who have recently been, or continue to be, entrusted with Labour's
campaigning responsibilities. Their trust and respect for
confidentiality is beyond question, and willingly given.
Mike Veitch,
Ewing House,
16 Holyrood Park Road,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Respecting human rights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A. Findlay McFadzean advises readers to think about the idea that we
have no rights, only duties (March 3). If we take his advice we will see
this idea presents us with a problem.
I have a duty towards A which I acknowledge. Does A then have the
right to expect me to do my duty towards him? If so, do I not have a
justifiable right to expect A to do his duty towards me? I think it is
rather obvious that rights and duties are reciprocal and that you can't
have one without the other.
But what is this duty we have towards one another? My grandmother
often taught me about ''the Golden Rule''. It was based on the Christian
admonition to ''love your neighbour as yourself'' and was that ''you
didn't do anything to other people that you wouldn't like them to do to
you''.
Inherent in this teaching is the idea that people have a common sense
of justice and are resentful of injustice.
It is in recognition of this at the state/people level that the
preamble to the Universal Declaration of Human Rights says, ''It is
essential, if man is not to be compelled to have recourse, as a last
resort, to rebellion against tyranny and oppression, that human rights
should be protected by the rule of law.''
Human rights are no artificial construction and if governments were to
do their duty and respect human rights there would be a lot less crime
and social disruption within states and fewer wars between them.
F Gillingham,
39 Cessnock Place,
Kilmarnock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000040</DOCID>
