<HEADLINE>Motorway protests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CERTAIN reports concerning the protest against the M77 have attempted
to portray the participants as primarily unemployed and ''outsiders'' --
some migrant band of ''professional activists'' with no base in the
community.
As someone conducting research into the M77 protest, I must say that
such a portrayal does a grave injustice to the many local people from a
variety of backgrounds who are involved in the protest.
There are, certainly, some folk who have moved to Glasgow in order to
protest the construction of the M77. However, the resistance against the
motorway has also seen the involvement of several community groups, an
array of Glasgow-based professionals -- including academics, planners,
social workers, cartographers, physicians, and environmental workers --
and many adults and school children from local communities such as
Pollok and Corkerhill who will be most affected if the road is built.
To portray such a broad coalition as ''outsiders'' is to enact an
exclusionary politics of the most undemocratic kind.
Dr Paul Routledge,
Department of Geography
and Topographic Science,
University of Glasgow.
</TEXT>
