<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Elderly in society</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468483</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is rarely possible for anyone to be truly objective in any
discussion regarding care of the elderly in society, particularly those
of us who are involved in the caring sector.
However, the facts are simply that private nursing homes are facing a
crisis which will bankrupt many and at the same time disadvantage the
frail elderly men and women who rely on their services.
I have read the excellent letters of Dr Colin Barron, John Shearer,
and others regarding their concerns and views and I support them
wholeheartedly.
Residential homes and nursing homes must never be confused. Only
nursing homes require professionally qualified nurses in charge at any
time of the day or night. Regrettably there have been those which have
been poorly run, a fact which has reflected badly on the owners but
equally on the regional councils responsible for standards in
residential homes and health boards which register and monitor private
nursing homes.
These few unacceptable homes have distorted public perception of a
profession which is absolutely central in offering the best option at
the best price for those who require help.
The truth of the matter is that private nursing homes are now the most
closely monitored and keenly legislated establishments in existence, a
circumstance encouraged and promoted by federations such as the one I
represent.
Loneliness, rarely mentioned in these debates, is the most potent
factor in the physical and mental decline of an elderly person. Nursing
homes create an environment where loneliness simply cannot occur.
No matter the political view, it is simply ludicrous to ignore the
huge costs involved in placing elderly people in social work
department-owned homes and in NHS hospital beds when the private sector
can offer every bit as good a service, and in many instances a much
better one, at infinitely lesser cost to the patient and to us all as
taxpayers.
The present legislation endangers this right of patient choice, and
with the explosion in numbers of elderly people in society over the next
five years, the problem has to be addressed by central Government.
It is a pious hope to believe that all those people needing care can
be kept in their own homes irrespective of cost. The truth of the matter
is that fewer and fewer people will receive the help they need as the
Community Care Act in its present form bites deeper and the funding is
unwisely allocated.
Joe Campbell,
Vice-Chairman,
Ayrshire Nursing Home
Federation,
54a Holmston Road,
Ayr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000044</DOCNO>
