<TEXT>
AS a distinguished former administrator, Mr Drummond Hunter will
appreciate that achieving health gain in the developed world takes time
and concerted effort (March 2).
At a national level, accredited information provides real evidence
that the new NHS is treating more patients with waiting lists falling.
Importantly, the alliances with local authorities and voluntary agencies
are ensuring the needs of the elderly, and other priority groups, are
being met in a more comprehensive way. They remain top priority in the
Scottish NHS.
At a local level, the first and second wave NHS Trusts -- 17 of them
-- have presented their annual reports. These reports evidence
innovation and imagination in health care delivery which is benefiting
patients.
They are of course available for public and academic scrutiny. From
April, 1995, NHS Trusts will provide agreed health care programmes for
all of mainland Scotland. On the basis of progress so far, improvements
for patients will be considerable.
D McNeill,
Chief Executive,
South Ayrshire Hospitals
NHS Trust,
Ayr.
