<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Debt to J B McLaren</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468486</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DON'T suppose readers are much interested in how their Herald is
produced, or the people who produce it, as long as it is available to
them in the morning, but I really do feel they should know a little more
about people like James McLaren, The Herald's one-time Motoring
Correspondent, whose death you reported (March 4).
Jim was a first-class journalist in every way, as a writer and
technician. In the late 1940s when I became the Herald's night and crime
reporter Jim and I were the only ones on duty in the early hours of the
morning.
I would phone in my stories and Jim would allocate them a space in the
paper and ensure that they fitted that space. Night after night he
performed miracles with my copy and helped to bring The Herald into the
post-war world. Then he would race home madly on his motor bike at 4am.
Sir William Robieson, our editor, must have winced often at the things
the rather dignified Herald published when he had gone home for the
night -- murders, fires, accidents, floods, train crashes -- but he was
a real journalist, too, and realised that the paper could no longer
afford to ignore the kind of thing other newspapers were publishing with
success, although it was still considered by The Herald hierarchy that
the most important items in the paper were the births, marriages, and
deaths on the front page.
The kind of news in which McLaren and I dealt didn't appear on page
one until October, 1958.
Even with modern technology the production of a daily newspaper is
still a miracle of co-operation among many departments and skills, but
it was the Jim McLarens of this world who led the way. Journalism owes a
lot to his kind.
Harry Diamond,
27F Greenholme Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sterling sags as Major rejects rejoining ERM</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is no prospect of sterling rejoining the Exchange Rate Mechanism
(ERM), said Prime Minister John Major yesterday.
His comments came as sterling failed to maintain its earlier firm tone
and sagged in late European trading.
It continued to follow the dollar lower in the face of the market's
continued preference for mark investment. Traders ignored the
disappointing industrial output figures but if more weak economic data
emerges it will start to impact the pound.
Against the mark, sterling eased back to DM2.2503 compared with
DM2.2517 overnight and $1.6170 from $1.6175, while its trade-weighted
index dipped 0.1 to 85.9.
The US currency continued to recover following comments from the
Federal Reserve about the need to remain vigilant on inflation.
Elsewhere the Mexican peso slid back despite news that Mexico is shortly
to announce a new economic plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scratch cards</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM writing to express concern at the introduction of ''scratch
cards'' by Camelot. I question whether the introduction of such cards is
socially wise or morally justifiable (March 1).
Despite the proferred purpose of raising money for good causes,
Camelot will gain and that is their prime purpose.
There are many people in this country who see no way of escaping the
unsatisfying grind of existence except by accumulating a large sum of
money. They have no way of gaining such a sum except by a real stroke of
luck or by a criminal act.
There is a difference between the Lottery (or Ernie) and scratch cards
in that only in the latter is there a promise of immediate
gratification. Those who are at most risk are those who are unable to
defer immediate gratification.
Scratch cards, like gaming machines, pander to that personality and
are designed to tempt such people to buy and scratch in the hope of
immediate gratification.
I fear there are many families who will suffer in order to increase
Camelot's profits.
J C Ballard,
8 Houston Mains,
Uphall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why regulator turned on the power</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE day last September I had a minor contretemps with Professor
Stephen Littlechild and his retinue. The director-general of Offer, the
Office of Electricity Regulation, had travelled to Glasgow to announce
details of his review of distribution and supply price controls for the
two Scottish electricity companies.
We were invited to a hotel press conference at 11.00am to hear the
details. I was, therefore, taken aback to hear Littlechild on the radio
that very morning, at just after 8.00, revealing all. He was able to do
so because the details had just been announced to the Stock Exchange
minutes before, right at the start of the day's trading.
This practice of getting market-sensitive announcements out early to
grab a sound bite or two on radio or breakfast television is
increasingly popular among listed company bosses. It is, naturally, much
encouraged by our friends in the electronic media.
It gives chairmen and chief executives two bites at the cherry -- the
brisk on-air interview one morning, the more in-depth coverage in the
printed media, 24 hours later. It also leaves newspaper types like me
feeling distinctly disadvantaged.
How these companies choose to handle major announcements is, at the
end of the day, up to them. But, arguably, when a regulator responsible
to Parliament makes a major announcement affecting millions of consumers
and investors he has a duty to be more even-handed in how that news gets
from Offer to the masses.
I made that point, as forcibly as I could, to the Littlechild team in
the hotel corridor, before the briefing began. The professor stayed in
the background. I was confronted by his patrician deputy, who
disdainfully suggested that, whoever I might be, I simply did not know
what I was talking about. Offer had an obligation to inform markets
first and that's what it had done.
That, of course, was not my point. Offer certainly has that obligation
to inform markets first. But it didn't have to do it at 7.30 in the
morning to get the prof on the airwaves at eight, while the rest of us
were forced to wait until 11, with no chance of getting the story across
to our readers until the next morning.
My mind flipped back to that incident this week as I watched the
hapless Littlechild get himself into a right old pickle with his warning
of a tougher rethink on the price controls he imposed on the English
regional electricity companies last August.
Market-sensitive timing? The electricity regulator could not have been
more insensitive about announcing his U-turn. He could not have wreaked
more mayhem in the sector if he had announced that four RECs had
rendered themselves insolvent through derivatives trading, Leeson-style.
To choose last Tuesday to reveal his mounting doubts about whether he
had been tough enough on the RECs last year, to drop his bombshell the
day after the Government sold its remaining 40% stake in National Power
and PowerGen, and three days before Trafalgar's offer for Northern
Electric closes, betrays, at best, naive otherworldliness, at worst,
reckless incompetence.
Singlehandedly Littlechild has wiped billions off the value of
electricity shares. He has pushed the Northern board into recommending
Trafalgar's #11 a share cash offer but, thanks to Northern's plunging
share price, he has also put the bid itself back in the melting pot. He
has left new investors in the two English generators licking their
wounds and has dealt a fresh blow to the London market's reputation for
probity after the Barings fiasco. Who knows what will now happen to the
planned sale of National Grid?
Champions of the consumer interest may be tempted to see in all this
the emergence of Saint Stephen, a diminutive bearded David-like figure,
bringing down a high-voltage Goliath, not with a slingshot, but with a
tougher ''RPI minus X'' price control. But Littlechild had his chance to
be that tough with the RECs last August and, frankly, had the wool
pulled over his eyes.
The way the markets received his five-year settlement then, with REC
shares soaring skywards, said it all. The professor's attempts to
explain that away as a natural reaction to the ending of a period of
uncertainty are hogwash. He got it spectacularly wrong then. And, to
suggest that he can put it right now but, in the process, turn the
market into a disorderly bear pit, simply compounds the doubts. He is
not up to the job.
In his Tuesday statement, Littlechild said he was responding to ''what
appears to be widespread public concern'' about the price controls he
had already proposed. That hardly sounds like a decisive basis for
action. Yesterday, in a further explanation penned for the FT,
Littlechild perhaps gets nearer the nub.
''I believe that a suitably revised price control will increase public
confidence in the regulatory regime,'' he writes. In other words,
Littlechild is trying to restore his own credibility, regardless of the
consequences for others. It will not do.
The creation of a new breed of independent regulators was part of the
Faustian bargain the Government entered into when it decided to
privatise the former monopoly utilities in Britain. Would-be investors
had to be encouraged to part with their money, with the prospect of
rising share values and mounting dividends. But consumers had to be
reassured that they wouldn't pay for it all through rising phone,
electricity, and gas bills.
Giving the regulators the power to enforce real cuts in prices means
that the market in these privatised stocks, far from being free --
dictated only by the law of supply and demand -- is, in a very real
sense, rigged. Striking the right balance between returns to investors
and savings for consumers calls for consummate skill and judgment.
Professor Littlechild has been found lacking in that this week. But,
with a second five-year appointment already safely in his pocket, who
now regulates the underperforming regulator? If he won't resign, who can
sack him?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kingfisher chief takes #300,000 pay cut</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KINGFISHER, the Woolworths-to-Comet group, announced yesterday that
four ousted directors are to share #3m compensation.
The company also announced that chief executive Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy,
who stepped down as chairman in January, is to take a dramatic cut in
his pay to #700,000.
Sir Geoffrey was bitterly criticised last year when his pay was
increased to more than #1m.
Shares in Kingfisher fell sharply through 1994 and in the early weeks
of 1995 after the group announced that Woolworths suffered poor
Christmas sales for the second successive year and electrical retailer
Comet had fallen into a loss.
In a brief statement to the Stock Exchange, Kingfisher said:
''Compensation for the four Kingfisher directors leaving the company as
a result of the board changes announced on January 27 and February 13
will not exceed a total of #3m.
''The remuneration, excluding pension contributions, of chief
executive Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy for the year ended January 28 will not
exceed #700,000.
''This reflects a decision by Sir Geoffrey to waive his long-term
incentive bonus and a reduction in his performance-related bonus.''
In a major about-turn, the company also said it is to replace
executive directors' three-year rolling contracts with two-year rolling
contracts.
The four former directors -- chief executive Alan Smith, finance
director James Kerr-Muir, corporate affairs director Nigel Whittaker and
strategy and international development director Tim Breene -- were on
three-year rolling contracts.
Smith was believed to have earned #635,000 to #640,000, Whittaker
#495,000 to #500,000 and Kerr-Muir #410,000-#415,000, while Breene
earned a salary near the bottom end of these levels. The figures exclude
pension contributions.
Kingfisher has yet to report results for the year to the end of
January.
In the six months to July 30, 1994, the group made pre-tax profits of
#88.1m compared with #82m in the corresponding period the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adams propaganda coup</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is no point in attempting to minimise the seriousness of the
rebuff administered to the British Government by President Clinton
yesterday. The decision to allow Gerry Adams of Sinn Fein to visit the
United States, to invite him to meet President Clinton, and to attend a
St Patrick's Day dinner with American leaders (even if loyalists and Mr
Ian Paisley have also been invited) is bad enough. It is made even more
serious by President Clinton's determination to allow Mr Adams to open a
new Sinn Fein office in Washington and to raise funds for his party in
the United States. Mr Adams will relish the propaganda coup. The British
Government has been lobbying hard for some time to prevent all of this
happening. Sir Patrick Mayhew, in Washington earlier this week, added
his considerable diplomatic skills to the effort but President Clinton
has another agenda, not far removed from the fact that the campaign for
the next presidential election in the United States has started already.
The Irish-American lobby has been active and the Irish Government under
Mr John Bruton is clearly able to demonstrate continuity with the
determined efforts of the previous administration in Dublin.
The affair appears to have been clinched by Gerry Adams's promise to
discuss the decommissioning of IRA arms, though this is not the sort of
word that should ever have been used to describe the process. Ships and
other military ventures are commissioned as a means of welcoming them
into honourable service. Terrorist weapons are no more decommissioned
than they are commissioned; they are simply used to murder people and
there is nothing honourable about that. Nevertheless, their removal has
to be discussed. The difference in the context of these proposed
discussions, between that agreed by President Clinton and Gerry Adams,
and that preferred by the British Government, is significant. Throughout
his Washington visit this week Sir Patrick insisted, both to his
American hosts and in discussions with a wide range of US politicians,
that any talks on the removal of IRA weapons had to be constructive.
Northern Ireland Office Minister Michael Ancram reinforced the message
on Wednesday with his stipulation that any talks must be serious and
constructive. As far as anyone is aware this morning, Mr Adams has only
agreed to discuss the removal of the arms and President Clinton has
accepted this promise as adequate.
It is, of course, nothing of the sort. Mr Adams has an inexhaustible
ability to discuss anything at the greatest length possible. Whether
these discussions are serious or constructive, in the sense of moving
towards an acceptable conclusion, is another matter. He knows that, and
he knows that Her Majesty's Government also knows it. He has managed to
extract maximum benefit from Washington by making a meaningless promise,
and any genuine moves to surrender IRA weapons will bring a double
benefit in the form of a future concession by the British and Irish
governments. What this does for the constant assertion that he does not
speak for the IRA is not explained. Mr Adams, meantime, will be able to
amass considerable sums of money from Irish-American sympathisers. The
pool of potential donors is large. The best estimate suggests that there
are 40 million Irish-Americans in the United States and even if only a
small proportion of them donate money a tidy sum will be gathered. Mr
Adams has promised that this will be used for political purposes.
Despite the peace process and the fact that the various parties are
talking to each other, he should not be taken at his word. It should not
be impossible for some sort of monitoring of money transfers from the
United States to be established. Perhaps the United States government,
which has so generously tipped this pot of gold into stained hands,
could assist? In the circumstances, it is the least they should do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
