<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>IMI set for expansion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIFE looks good at IMI at present with the engineers emerging from
1994 buoyed by a second half volume increase of 11% and that being
maintained so far into 1995.
Pre-tax profits last year jumped 19% to #85.3m but were offset by the
#35m write-off on the diversification into computing through Redwood
International so that stated profits slid from ##71.7m to #50.3m.
Chief executive Gary Allen said yesterday that with gearing at just
22%, IMI is looking for acquisitions in the US and Europe -- the Far
East is too difficult for takeovers and growth there will have to be
organic. The chosen areas would be in building products, fluid power,
and drinks dispensing.
Last year, the building side of the group continued to benefit from
the strength of the German operations. Eastern Germany is building at a
quick pace in an attempt to recover from the Communist era.
Well over half the company's UK copper tube production is exported to
Germany while in the UK prospects are improving in commercial building
which should more than offset any slowdown in the private sector house
building which accounts for about #40m out of divisional turnover of
#355m.
Fluid power benefited from the economic recovery in major markets and
with Australia looking good as a springboard for Pacific Rim expansion.
The drinks dispensing business was particularly strong in the US. IMI
has exclusive supply agreements with Coca-Cola and Pepsi which are
helping to place its coolers and dispensers into new markets as the two
soft drinks giants extend their empires into the developing world.
The sore point is titanium where losses of ''several millions''
continue. That is a result of weak demand from Rolls-Royce and intense
price competition --there is no serious threat as yet from Russian
suppliers which have still to get Western quality accreditaion.
However, there is no respite likely for 1995 with losses of around
#6m. Coin minting has been quite buoyant but the significant divisional
growth has been in producing tokens for casios in America where 16
states in the last year or so have lifted the restrainsts on gambling.
The dividend total has been raised just [1/2]p to 10.5p for a 4.6%
yield with the shares 15p easier on the day at 285p. Current year
profits seem set to jump by around a quarter to #107m where the shares
would be selling at 13 times probable earnings.
</TEXT>
