<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Laying down the law of the jungle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXPOSED: cuddly marine mammal is secret killer. Of course it is, and
not so secret at that. The dolphin kills fish to eat and -- according to
the evidence of last night's BBC Scotland film Operation Survival --
kills harbour porpoises, possibly to protect its food source. But here's
another moral dilemma for animal rights activists and New Age mystics
who believe that in saving the dolphin we save ourselves: what's the
pay-off for lovable Flipper's equally amiable wee cousin?
The dolphin is a nineties icon. Above the panda, beyond the whale, it
has become the supreme deity in the pantheon of animal worship. The
secular West still needs its gods, and the dolphin's divine powers have
been credited with faith healing, telepathic communication, and shark
protection duties.
There are any number of witnesses to the marine epiphany of swimming
with the dolphins, but who among you will now pop your boy on the back
of a bottleneck in the Moray Firth?
The sacred one has flippers of clay. I'm not being entirely flippant.
When the big sea predator is seen doing what comes naturally --
eliminating the competition -- it throws into further confusion all our
crazily scrambled attitudes towards animals. If we give animals
''rights'' equal to our own, do we also give them  ''rights'' equal to
each other's? Or when we save the dolphin do we punish the harbour
porpoise?
The point that seems to get missed by many activists is that we don't
liberate animals by giving them ''rights'', we reassert our supremacy
over them. We extend to them moral systems developed singularly because
we are human and unique. If we teach a child not to kick a dog, as the
old example goes, it's not only good for the dog but good for the child.
But will it stop the dog mauling the neighbourhood cats? You bet it
won't.
If we ban fox-hunting will the grateful fox renounce its own brutish
nature and leave the henhouse alone? Of course not; and neither is that
an argument for NOT banning fox-hunting. Like the case against capital
punishment it's not so much what execution does to the murderer which
matters as what it does to us.
My own position on fox-hunting is neutral, partly because the debate
is tainted by such vicious levels of class hatred and blind emotion it's
impossible to make sense of it, and partly because I don't know enough
about the hunt. A keeper of hounds, a veteran huntsman of humble rural
stock (note how it's necessary to define his social class), once told me
that the fox's death is swift; that the hounds break its neck in one
movement well before they start pulling it apart.
On the other hand, I don't doubt the fox feels terror in its beasty
breast when the pack bells its excitement, much as the chicken panics
when old Reynard comes a-calling; unless, of course, it's a battery
chicken, in which case it will be securely protected from all predators.
See what I mean about scrambled attitudes?  Spare the fox and you
condemn the free-range hen.
The most serious obstacle for animal rights activists, however, is
their own negativism. True, there are some disagreeable practices for
which they can provide options. It shouldn't be necessary to transport
live animals long distances for slaughter when we have abattoirs in this
country; it should be possible to re-educate the European palate to
enjoy pink veal, although I dislike the xenophobic,
we're-nice-they're-nasty undercurrents to the anti-crating case.
But the real opposition to organisations like, say, Compassion in
World Farming, is the enemy within: the extreme liberationists and the
proselytising vegan/vegetarian movement. They do speak such nonsense.
They do lack imagination, and even the most elementary knowledge of
human history.
The other day I read a claim by one of their missionaries that British
people had only become serious meat-eaters in the twentieth century
(which is true, for reasons of economy rather than ideology) and that we
should all therefore return to a ''more natural'' vegetarian diet.
If we followed his advice and returned . . . and returned . . . and
returned, we would find ourselves back in pre-agrarian societies happily
hunting and gathering. Might not be a bad thing. There's a lot of
evidence that pre-agrarian Europe was a carefree, creative place for
tribes not yet held in bondage to the back-breaking work of planting,
harvesting and grinding grain, or the year-round husbanding of
livestock.
Their social groups hunted and gathered when they needed to feed
themselves, and spent the rest of the time drawing pictures on rock
walls, making rudimentary jewellery and learning to sing for pleasure.
But they also spilt the blood of Brother Boar and Sister Deer.
The consequences of an exclusively vegetarian culture -- and even more
a vegan one -- seem to be overlooked by the zealots. For what destiny
are they sparing the animals? What will happen to the Aberdeen Angus
when no-one wants to eat him? What will happen to the Suffolk sheep when
no-one wants her lambs?
For the vegan not even the Friesian has a future, or the sheep for her
wool, and the welfare of the chicken will be left to the fox. Farm
animals will become endangered species. Those who investigate these
things already know that the cow  would be extinct if it hadn't been
useful to the human purpose, and I'm old enough to have experience of a
more recent example.
Everyone over 40 remembers the days when heavy horses were part of the
urban traffic and fixtures on the rural landscape. Everyone under 40 is
hard pushed to tell their Clydesdales from their Shires unless they seek
out the splendid great  beasts in ''heavy horse centres'', where -- like
redundant miners -- they've become part of the heritage and tourism
industries.
Is that what the campaigning vegetarian wants? The Charollais cow as
protected species? Perhaps it is. So let's assume that the movement
gathers momentum until its aim has been universally achieved, and we are
back in the Garden with only apples to eat. The animal rights activist
doesn't go away. There is still a serpent to sort.
There is still the problem of the sheep and the goats to resolve. Whom
shall we save?  Who are the justified sinners of the animal world? The
Siberian tiger, who slaughters his own cubs if he gets the chance? Orca
the whale, with her appetite for pretty penguins and soppy seals?  The
friendly neighbourhood dolphins of the Moray Firth?
And whom shall we reject? The tenacious rat, intelligent but unloved?
The ugly hyena, slavering scavenger and devoted mother?  Who will stand
up for the harbour porpoise when the smiling dolphin batters him with
his bottle nose?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger over rail policy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN those at the centre of the Tory Party start shunting gently in
the opposite direction it is time for Mr Major and his colleagues to
take notice. Viscount Whitelaw, an icon of decent Conservatism, is not
one of nature's rebels. By age and experience, and certainly by
inclination, he is interested in the unfashionable concept of service.
In the context of Britain's fragmented and soon-to-be-privatised rail
system that makes him distinctly steam-driven. His reservations over the
manner in which rail privatisation is being conducted are utterly
correct, if spoken with characteristic caution and grace.
Nevertheless his fears are evident. He undoubtedly believes that the
West Coast Line is in danger of abandonment through neglect and, despite
the protestations of Government Ministers, it is hard to find anyone
with knowledge of the railways who would disagree. Viscount Whitelaw's
anger on this issue was made clear when Transport Minister John Watts
cancelled a meeting with concerned MPs and peers on the grounds that he
was unprepared. This was understandable, and anyone who has witnessed
the unfortunate Mr Watts attempting to explain policy might have taken
it as a blessing. Nevertheless it stands as a perfect symbol of a policy
which is horribly misconceived, abortive in practice, and unlikely ever
to meet the requirements of the modern transport system which this
country needs so desperately.  Viscount Whitelaw knows this, Government
Ministers in their innermost hearts know this, and now we understand
that British Rail chairman Sir Bob Reid is in agreement. He admitted
yesterday that services have worsened in the run-up to privatisation and
claimed ringingly that he would not put his own money into any of the
new rail companies. If Viscount Whitelaw is a genteel shunter, Sir Bob
is definitely a buffer-basher. He tends to say what he thinks, and what
he thinks about rail privatisation is clearly of little comfort to the
Government. When charged in the Commons yesterday with Sir Bob's
disaffection and reluctance to put his money where his tracks used to
be, the Prime Minister responded, with one of his triumphant grins, that
all of Sir Bob's comments should have been mentioned, and particularly
the bit where he gives his assent to privatisation of a workable sort.
Frankly, this was pathetic. Much of Sir Bob's unease centres on the
proposed operation of Railtrack which will gather track access charges
from the train operators.
Railtrack is being used, through the raising of access charges and the
subsequent costing of the services which use them, as a handy vehicle
for discovering justifications for withdrawing services. This is a
simple indication of the deviousness of the system and its essential
impracticability. None of this passes muster in the country at large.
Now it is clear that it is no less acceptable at the centre of the Tory
Party or within the core of railway professionals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Westland order lifts GKN.  Group earnings morethan double to #200m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Ministry of Defence order for helicopters from Westland underpins
prospects for GKN, which staged a sharp recovery last year, with profits
more than doubling to #200m. GKN chairman Sir David Lees said 1994 was a
good year for the group.
Westland has been waiting years for the order and as deliveries build
up in coming years the company stands to make much higher profits. The
order is a fitting swansong for Alan Jones who has run Westland in
recent years but is now leaving to join BICC.
''Westland is in a very good position relative to its competitors and
will make good returns in future,'' said Mr Jones.
Until now the company has been living on a rather hand-to-mouth basis
through maintenance work and spares, though achieving considerable
success in winning update work on existing Westland helicopers in
service around the world.
It is hoping export orders will start flowing in now the UK defence
establishment has given a vote of confidence to the EH101 support and
Apache attack helicopters.
Mr Jones said Westland and its sub-contractors would be recruiting
more labour as a result of the contracts. The company's main production
facilities are at Yeovil. The new work will raise margins at Westland
through creating more volume and raising capacity utilisation.
Westland contributed its expected #19m of profits last year. GKN's
other defence interests were the only activity to show lower profits,
reflecting a gap between deliveries of Warrior armoured cars to the MoD
and the start of the Kuwaiti order. This will be in full swing by
mid-year.
The upturn in the car market in the US and a lesser extent in Europe
brought an upsurge in operating profits from the main vehicle driveline
business. They rose 61% to #122m on the back of higher volumes and
continuing productivity improvements which boosted margins. The group
accounted for 34% of world production of constant velocity joints, a
gain of 4%. It actually made 56 million joints.
The outlook is positive though there is some concern over the 15%
increase in raw material prices. The group will seek to recover this in
prices though Trevor Bonner, who heads the automative side, agreed that
this would be difficult.
GKN's cash position has been greatly strengthened by the cash
settlement of the dispute between Westland and certain Arab countries,
strong cash flow and customer advances. It has cash of #300m and even
disregarding customer advances has no debt. But acquisitions are not on
the cards because of the investment demands of existing activities.
The Chep pallet business, now in a simplified ownership structure with
the Australian Brambles Group, went from strength to strength, raising
profits by 35% to #42m. The reorganisation has made it easier to develop
the European activities, which are rapidly expanding, with a pallet
fleet of 33,000,000.
GKN's dividends are going up for the first time since 1989. The 13.5p
final raises the total by 5% to 21.5p. This is covered only 1.3 times
against the target of twice, averaged through the trading cycle, and is
a measure of the group's optimism.
Last year's trading trend is continuing into the current year and the
group is clearly confident of another strong advance in profits, which
solidly underpins the shares. They rose 14p to 579p as analysts upgraded
their profit forecasts to around #270m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foreign &amp; Colonial increases dividends ahead of inflation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN &amp; Colonial Investment Trust, the largest in the sector, more
than achieved its goal of increasing dividends ahead of inflation last
year.
With a final of 1.1255p, plus a foreign income dividend of 0.1532p,
the total is up 6.7% at 1.88p. But asset value dipped by 9%.
The number of shareholders in F&amp;C is poised to top 100,000 and small
shareholders will soon have more than 50%. This is largely a reflection
of the group's share-saving scheme which has also virtually eliminated
the discount of the shares to asset value.
The saving scheme did start pushing up costs, prompting questions at
the annual meeting. The costs of the plan, however, were reduced in 1994
as a result and a further reduction is seen this year.
Group expenses still rose 9% largely as a result of the management fee
which was up 15% because it is based on a three-year rolling average of
assets.
F&amp;C manager Michael Hart is confident about the longer-term outlook,
though the next few months may be difficult as a result of the likely
inflation numbers and higher interest rates. But overall he feels higher
rates have largely been discounted. The group has raised its gearing
slightly to 11% as it anticipates better investment conditions.
Mr Hart considers the UK economy is looking good, though there is some
concern over the policies of a future Labour government. He is cautious
about the US market because of high valuations, but is hopeful for
Europe where the economy is moving forward and industrial restructuring
is continuing. Japanese markets could be attractive in 1995 if local
investors recover their nerve.
So F&amp;C will remain fully invested. The portfolio ended 1994 with 43%
in the UK, 21% in the US, 12% Japan, 6% the Far East and 2% Latin
America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Green with envy over presidential paradise lost</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TOM SHIELDS DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NAE Luck Award to Jack McGinn, former chairman of Celtic FC and
vice-president of the Scottish Football Association.
Although Jack has no longer any position of power at Parkhead, the new
regime allowed him to remain as a Celtic representative on the SFA. He
had fond hopes of taking over soon as SFA president, with all the
honours, not to mention perks, the post carries.
This is now extremely unlikely because of the financial restructuring
which has taken place at Celtic Park. Celtic plc, the new public limited
company, has been registered with the SFA and Scottish Football League.
The plc has three directors. Jack McGinn is not one and therefore
cannot represent Celtic on Scottish football's ruling bodies. The
directors are Fergus McCann, Eric Reilly, and Willie Haughey. The
absence of Celtic club secretary Dominic Keane means that he too will
have no voice on the Scottish Football League.
Labouring it
CHRISTINE Richard, the Edinburgh Tory councillor and controversialist,
is taking the Labour Party to task. Hold the farming page, we hear you
cry.
But haud on. She is complaining that the comrades are taking too long
to process an application by her son Christopher to join the People's
Party. She claims to be miffed at the discourtesy shown to her
''champagne socialist'' son, as she describes him.
Mrs Richard is no doubt deeply unhappy that her offspring should jump
the dyke politically. But that's what she gets for sending him to Fettes
College. We all know what happens to Fettes' best and brightest. Yes,
they grow up to be leader of the Labour Party.
Time skelps on
A MR Bill Watson from Falkirk writes with an example of colourful
demotic language, a subject which greatly interests the Diary. When he
was in hospital some time ago, one of the nurses was a country lass with
a down-to-earth attitude. Returning from her mid-morning tea break, she
would invariably exclaim before getting on with her work: ''Hauf-past
ten an' no' an erse skelpt.''
Mr Watson adds: ''Another similar saying that comes to mind is
'Half-past ten and not a whore in the house dressed'. I'm sure your
readers will have other versions.''
Down Memory
Back Road
EFFIE Davidson, an old girl of Dollar Academy, writes to say that plus
ca change at her alma mater the more it stays the same. Effie, now
resident in Findochty, Banffshire, tells us: ''During my last year at
school (1938) it was announced at morning prayers by the then rector
that boys and girls must not be seen walking together along the Back
Road or walking into McBeth's Wood carrying a raincoat.''
Gaelic on a plate
ONE of our Gaelic chums has been taking an interest in motor car
registration numbers. Licence plates can mean something totally
different when they contain certain Gaelic words.
The letters BAS should be avoided since they mean death. MAS
translates as posterior, backside, erse even.
CEO means smoke. BEO is alive and would be entirely inappropriate if
included on a licence plate belonging to a hearse. LAS would be nice on
a fire engine since it means to light up.
The AA should note that the letters SAS mean ''stuck''. Those driving
around with DIA in the registration are getting above themselves. It
means deity.
That's all your Gaelic for today.
* We reproduce the above from a Glasgow newspaper and admit we can't
wait to see the applicants.
* This shop window was spotted by Lachie Munro of London, not
somewhere in Ireland as you might expect but in Bonnybridge, furthest
Falkirkshire.
Gown yersel
WITH technical colleges achieving university status, it was only a
matter of time before further education establishments aspired to higher
things.
Kilmarnock College, for example, has gone all gaudeamus igitur. It is
now compulsory for the sundry mechanicals and hairdressers graduating
from the college to wear academic gowns as they collect their Scotvec
certificates.
The college authorities are currently debating whether to go ahead
with a scheme similar to the honorary degrees doled out by universities.
Local businessmen and dignitaries will be created ''fellows of
Kilmarnock College''. Rumours abound, but are denied, that a publican
and a car dealer are on the short-list.
The yoonie that likes to say Yes, Yes, Yes!
HEIDIE of this parish writes to let us know that Strathclyde
University's faculty of education, Jordanhill College as was, is
offering places on a sex education course on ''a first come, first
served basis''.
WARNING sign in a hotel room in Kaushiong, Taiwan, spotted by
far-flung Diary reader Tom Tannahill of Langbank: ''In order not to
metamorphose please don't dry your clothes on lamp shade.''
NAME GAME: The Woman's Guild at Kilmacolm Church in Renfrewshire had a
talk this week on the subject of landscape gardening. From a Dr Alison
Moss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Strip, Royal Court, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE WODDIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PHYLLIS Nagy's The Strip, which runs until April 1, is certainly her
most ambitious play to date, a giant leap forward that flies and falters
but challenges us on almost every level. Set simultaneously in
Liverpool, a modernistic Las Vegas, and London's Earls Court (Tobias
Hoheisel's set is part chrome-plated airship, part virtual reality
pyramid and Sphynx landscape) it is a play of possibilities.
In Steven Pimlott's stylish though partly still unfathomable
production, Nagy taps into a world of personal choice, random events,
and current preoccupations, suggesting that though consumerism and
technology may be leading us by the nose, we ourselves are all at sea,
bobbing between identities.
At least, that's what I take to be the inference of a play that offers
few concessions to convention. Nagy's characters -- who include a female
impersonator (played by a woman), a southern racist and his wife,
several gay and lesbian couples (in quite restrained mode for Nagy) --
and a multi-strand narrative line all combine to push the boundaries of
audience credibility to their limits.
If you want comforting entertainment, Nagy is not for you. But if you
delight in wry humour, her wicked ability to play cultural and sexual
clashes (the US v England, straight v gay) against each other, then The
Strip is a tantalising, apocalyptic taste of the future. Even when, as
here, the picture is a flawed one.
A gold-edged cast includes Cheryl Campbell, Nicholas Le Provost,
Nicholas Farrell, John Padden, and Deirdre Harrison as a raunchy Madonna
lookalike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Best of baroque</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LESLEY STEVENSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the main arguments against introducing entrance charges to our
national museums and galleries is that it would deter occasional or
lunchtime visitors. Certainly exhibitions like The Taking of Christ,
currently showcasing Caravaggio at the National Gallery in London, would
make no economic sense. A great pity, as it's a little gem.
Three Caravaggio paintings normally on show in the main galleries
provide context and meaning for a fourth, The Taking of Christ,
discovered in 1990 in Dublin after having been thought lost. The
National Gallery's Supper at Emmaus, painted for the same patron as the
Dublin picture, helps remind us that Caravaggio produced some of the
most deeply moving religious works of the baroque period.
Both works are roughly the same size and may have been conceived as a
pair. The Taking of Christ depicts the moment when Christ was identified
by Judas to the Roman soldiers. Caravaggio has represented the scene at
night, with only a lantern's glow piercing the darkness. The effect is a
brilliant piece of theatre: the characters are isolated, we are not
distracted by superfluous detail, and the two heads meeting for the
fateful kiss provide a wealth of meaning in their contrast.
Caravaggio's appeal to a present-day viewer probably lies in his
realism. The interest in textures in the frugal meal in The Supper at
Emmaus or the virtuoso performance of the armour in The Taking of Christ
could hardly be bettered. Yet there is a more profound realism at play,
too, as well as a sense of historical accuracy suggested by dirty
fingernails, shabby clothes, and lined faces. Caravaggio's religious
figures, with not a halo among them, are among the most accessible and
appealing in Western art.
The Boy bitten by a Lizard comes as a shock after such sobering works.
Its unabashedly homo-erotic overtones, with the naked youth wriggling in
horror as the lizard bites his finger, is a reminder that
seventeenth-century artists had to court as wide a circle of patrons as
possible.
Yet the connection to the religious works resides in its still-life
details. The sensual gratification oozing out of the picture, apparent
in the fruit and flowers in front of the naked boy, would have been
recognised by a contemporary audience as a reminder of the frivolity of
pursuing earthly pleasures. It is only when an exhibition like this
regroups works afresh that such links can easily be made.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>John Lewis climbsby 25% to #116.8m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS' emphasis on value for money and good service from retailers
is good news for the John Lewis Partnership which has prided itself on
being ''never knowingly undersold''.
In the year ended 28 January 1995, the partnership increased its
pre-tax profits by 25% to #116.8m. This followed the 31% improvement
last year. Group sales grew by 6% to #2575m with department stores the
star performer.
The 34,000 partners, or permanent staff working in the business, are
to share a #43m bonus equivalent to 12% of annual pay, or six weeks
extra pay. Many organisations could benefit from adopting the
partnership's constitution which effectively caps the renumeration of
the chairman at around #500,000, based on a formula.
Despite this voluntary restraint, John Lewis said that in its entire
history it had never had any of its senior directors poached by rival
organisations.
Chairman Stuart Hampson said: ''This partnership style of trading was
very much better attuned to the 1990s'' compared with the brasher 1980s.
This ''inclusive approach'' to retailing, which recognises that there
are many stakeholders in the business including workers, customers, and
suppliers, has been part and parcel of John Lewis' trading philosophy
since its inception.
Mr Hampson added that the group had made ''strong headway in what has
been a generally weak market'', largely due to careful cost control.
The partnership currently has 22 John Lewis department stores
including sites in Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
The stores remain commited to selling a wide product mix, not just
clothes and accessories, from large High Street sites in established
retail areas. There has been talk of department stores being an outmoded
retail format for the future but the trading performance of John Lewis
suggests that this is not the case. John Lewis' reported sales per
square foot of #450 are the envy of many in the industry.
Mr Hampson attributes the success of the business to respecting its
customers, honest fair trading, and constant good value rather than
''spurious special offers and discounts''.
Although food retailing has been intensely competitive for the past
few years the partnership's Waitrose foodstores have managed to more
than hold their own by focusing on offering high-quality merchandise.
Current sales are 5% up on an underlying basis.
Waitrose has benefited from opening 20 of its foodstores on Sundays
and introducing scanning technology.
Waitrose stores are all located in the Midlands and southern England
and there are no plans to extend the chain northwards. It has 2% market
share compared with 11% held by Sainsbury, the market leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE I am in a favourite wee haunt of mine on the South Side, The
Elcho Bar, having a wee cup of tea with a wee goldie to wash it down and
a Danish pastry with Evelyn Sexton the proprietrix.
I have but an hour ago committed the splendid tones upon the wireless,
Radio Scotland's Annie Webster Show in fact, and the wee goldie is
rather a favorite blend of mine, a whisky from the bottom of the Fort
William heap, Ben Nevis. It is a good blend (though they also do a
superb 26-year-old malt, if you can get your hands on it). I am enjoying
the bathe in its aroma when in pops an old chum -- Art Sutter, the
entertainer and broadcaster who was bumped unceremoniously off the Radio
Scotland airwaves a while back there along with such luminaries as
Jimmie Macgregor.
I didnae care all that much then: I was still getting employed by the
Beeb. Och, I did care: I like both the gents. Well, Art is still
broadcasting of course, notably for Grampian, but what he was doing in
the Elcho was representing, criv, what else, Ben Nevis Whisky and, by
the cost of his cashmere raiment, doing very well at it. (Is that enough
to get my hands on a Ben Nevis 26-year-old?)
It was a year or so ago. Some of those who were permitted to ''rest''
I was pleased about. I think everybody in Scottish broadcasting was glad
to see Neville Garden going. I'd rather see Neville alive and not
hearing him on radio, than listening to his obituary over the morning
cereal, and Neville was in the business of working himself into the
grave. Yet some of the changes were definitely odd.
Mind you, Radio Scotland remains a remarkably capable unit. If you are
a radio listener you will know what I mean. I regret the passing of the
abrasive Lesley Riddoch, who went off to a ladies' newspaper in the
East, but her programme, Speaking Out, is still of interest, headed now
usually by a bete noire of mine, wur ain Ruth Wishart.
Tom Morton's programme which follows is grand (except for the music;
dear God, Tom, you are needing the Frank O'Hagan band, featuring the
Urban V on moothie: hint). Tom is a touch similar to The Herald's Tom
Shields: you only know how good they are when somebody else deps for
them.
The touchy Colin Bell has no rivals, and Edie Stark has the cheeriest,
and often the most idiosyncratic, radio show outside of Ireland. By and
large Radio Scotland does a good job, especially when I am on it myself,
with a Ben Nevis inside me of a morning.
The other week Tony Currie wrote a bitter piece about the private
radio boys and girls in Scotland. He was referring in particular to
Scot-FM, and a chap called Scotty McClue especially. This McClue -- who
doesn't actually use his own name and I am not surprised at that -- does
a phone-in in which he is rude and unpleasant to all and sundry.
He is a disgrace to broadcasting, but it appears he is popular and
indeed now is alleged to contribute a column of sorts to a Scottish
tabloid. Many years back I kicked off the same sort of phone-in -- the
sort of thing they all do now, the ''shock-jocks'' programming.
I did it then on Radio Clyde and we copied the notion from America,
especially a broadcaster called Captain Bad. The difference was that we
may have been pugnacious, but I never said a thing I didn't believe in
(and used to cop some criticism from Clyde deputy supremo Alex Dickson
for it). The difference was that a lot of broadcasters were a touch
professional then. Not that we were well paid.
My phone-in prog was hugely and surprisingly successful and they used
to repeat it twice over. They paid me twenty-five quid a week. That is
more than, for instance, the recent Scot-FM paid me for a two-hour stint
on the Margo MacDonald show in its first week.
They didn't pay me at all (though, having asked me to do another show
they say they will and it is all an oversight and I hope it is). A
Paisley mob called Q96 had me working for them for two months every
Saturday and me paying my taxis there and back and not a penny have I
seen.
Probably the most disgraceful was the prestigious Good Morning America
which had myself and wee Cliff Hanley on three mornings in a row and, on
being questioned regarding the poppy, said: what the hell, you got free
coffee.
I took a Ben Nevis from Art in The Elcho. ''You're well oot it, Art,''
I said. The phone rang. Evelyn took it. ''BBC looking for you Jack.'' My
cynicism swept into the darkness and my heart leapt. Something wrong
with broadcasters, ain't there?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BBC SSO, City Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SEEN the score; read the poem; interviewed the composer. But none of
it prepared me for the unveiling last night of the vast musical
landscape that is William Sweeney's setting of Sorley Maclean's poem,
The Woods of Raasay.
With the inevitable moments that, in any new piece, require a couple
of hearings to sort out their context, this is as evocative and
effective a piece as the composer has written.
Mirroring the duality of the poem, the music exists on two levels: it
has a beautiful simplicity and an impressive complexity. The simplicity
-- and it is gorgeous -- lies in the clarity of the music's expression.
The first section is underpinned by a gentle, lilting, strumming. The
second -- the slow movement -- is sheer luminosity, erupting into the
third, which features bellowing, driven music. And the finale, which
echoes the opening, is characterised by a swinging, psalm-like tune.
On top of this Sweeney has set Maclean's rich text for bass and
soprano in a vocal line that blends continuous lyricism with
mind-boggling virtuosity. Drenched in imagery and expressive beauty, the
vocal lines -- spectacularly performed by Virginia Kerr and Stephen
Varcoe -- take flight and settle only 35 minutes later at the end of the
piece. Atmospherically played by the SSO under Martyn Brabbins.
Shostakovich's Fifth Symphony -- the second-half piece -- can't fail
in the City Hall. The impact is immense and immediate. That said, this
was a fairly direct reading, packed with incident but rather lacking in
direction and overall thrust.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New Labour councils to unite in fight for services</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW single-tier Labour-controlled councils will work together after
the local elections to defend their services against privatisation,
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson promised yesterday.
He claimed the Tory Government did not care if local services were
surrendered to ''all manner of sharks and fly-by-night cowboys'' through
compulsory tendering.
Ministers had a ''hidden agenda'' in the reorganisation, which was the
emasculation of local democracy. Labour councils would resist the
privatisation process, if necessary by organising services across
council boundaries.
The Government's aim was to atomise our major public services in order
to leave them more vulnerable to privatisation and keep control in the
hands of St Andrews House, said Mr Robertson.
As a result, Labour councils would have little choice but to establish
joint arrangements between the new shadow authorities.
These in turn would take over the contractor's function of existing
Direct Service Organisations and Direct Labour Organisations, and would
be responsible for running the existing contracts for the rest of their
duration. As well as preparing ''in house'' bids for any future
tendering round.
''Above all we should try to ensure that large contracts are not
broken up and sold off to the private sector,'' said Mr Robertson.
It was utter madness to restart the tendering process as quickly as
the Government planned. There should be a moratorium until the next
General Election.
He also attacked the Government for not listening to the Staff
Commission, appointed to advise Scottish Secretary Ian Lang.
Ministers had ignored the warnings of the chairman, Mr Robert Peggie,
about the tightness of the reorganisation timetable, and had recommended
redundancy payments for staff far below the level suggested by the
commission. When they were defeated in committee they simply dismissed
the vote as irrelevant.
''If you take that attitude then what is the point of having a Staff
Commission or even, for that matter, votes in Parliament?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Waiting for Godot, Royal Lyceum, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979468504</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE academic overkill to which the work of Samuel Beckett has been
subjected can encourage the impression that a piece like Waiting for
Godot is an abstruse, esoteric and, above all, difficult enigma. What
Kenny Ireland's Lyceum production gloriously reminds us is that Beckett
was a writer who understood the mechanics of the theatre and, even while
he was stretching those mechanics to the full, knew how to write great
parts for actors.
I say this not to underestimate the impact of the play's many
resonances, rather to suggest that it takes a lively, irreverent and
theatrical team of actors, not a heavy directorial concept, to release
those resonances. And here they are released in full glory, from
music-hall knockabout to self-doubting angst, in a production that plays
for laughs with a piece that is seriously unsettling in return.
David Shaw-Parker and Tam Dean Burn as Estragon and Vladimir may look
and move like Laurel and Hardy, but their short-tempered relationship
and delight in daft diversions sets them closer to Reeves and Mortimer.
Appropriately, the Vic and Bob generation was out in force for last
night's free preview, lapping up Eric Barlow's Pozzo and Rab Christie's
Lucky like they were visitors to Fantasy Island.
The performers have developed a curious on-the-surface style of
acting, you see every emotion, every reaction rather like they were
children's TV presenters.
But for every dose of absurdist comedy there's a chilling moment of
empty yearning round the corner. Excellent stuff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
