<DOCNO>GH950310-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Warning on difficulties of new child care measures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton warned yesterday
that new powers being introduced on child care law in Scotland must be
treated with caution.
The Children (Scotland) Bill, currently going through its Commons
committee stage, brings in a number of new measures, many of which stem
from the inquiry into the removal of children from Orkney and the report
into child care policies in Fife.
One is the concept of exclusion orders, under which an adult accused
of abusing a child would be removed from the family home, rather than
the child or children concerned.
Lord James said: ''While there is universal agreement that it is the
abuser who should be obliged to leave the family home rather than the
child, there are very difficult issues which cannot be glossed over.
''The rights of the individual have to be taken into account and I
have some reservations on creating a situation where people could be
excluded from their own house without having an adequate opportunity
before an order is made even on an interim basis to defend themselves
against an allegation that might possibly be malicious.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crisp firm defends TV commercial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WALKERS, the crisp company, denied yesterday that television
commercials featuring footballer Gary Lineker encouraged children to
talk to strangers.
The Independent Television Commission is investigating 23 complaints
from viewers, in the main made because Lineker is shown stealing crisps
from a boy and a #10,000 cheque from a nun.
The commercials, which are part of a #10m campaign, could be dropped
if the ITC rules against them. It does not have the power to ban them.
It can only request that they be withdrawn.
An ITC official said: ''The main concern is that one advertisement
shows Gary Lineker stealing crisps and being chased by a small boy.
People think this might send signals that it is all right to walk away
with a stranger.''
Walkers said: ''In no way are the advertisements designed to encourage
children to talk to strangers. Gary Lineker is not a stranger, he is a
well-known personality and national hero.
''Walkers Snack Foods looks forward to hearing the final ruling by the
ITC.''
Lineker, the former England centre forward who now presents BBC sports
programmes after his playing career ended, was not available for
comment.
He is said to be receiving #750,000 for the advertisements. In one, he
is seen stealing a #10,000 cheque from a nun who finds her crisp packet
has a prize-winning blue bag inside. She shows him the cheque and he
fills in his name before running off.
Walkers said yesterday that justice would be done in the next episode.
Another nun, played by BBC sports presenter Desmond Lynam, will catch
the fleeing footballer and retrieve the cheque.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
