<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bigger profit opens wounds at Rolls-Royce</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR MP criticised Rolls-Royce yesterday after it announced
profits of #101m for 1994.
The aero engine giant, which is cutting 600 jobs at East Kilbride,
said it had lifted taxable profits from #76m the previous year.
However, Mr Adam Ingram, Labour MP for East Kilbride, found cold
comfort in the figures. He said the Rolls-Royce workforce in his
constituency had made a major contribution to the company's profits over
the years ''only to be rewarded with redundancy''.
Mr Ingram said the company's profit-driven approach had resulted
overall in thousands of jobs being thrown on the scrapheap.
''The recent announcement that 600 jobs are to go at East Kilbride
shows Rolls-Royce has put the pursuit of profits of the aerospace
industry first.''
The MSF union chairman at the plant, Mr Owen Thomas, said the profit
had not been unexpected. However, it was not sizeable for a company such
as Rolls-Royce and played straight into the union's hands, because East
Kilbride had been the major contributor towards it.
He said: ''We made #97m profit in 1993 and contributed the bulk of
1994's #101m profit. This only goes to underline that the board had got
it all wrong.''
Mr Owen was confident that they would eventually get the company to
change its mind on its ''transparently stupid'' decision to axe the jobs
at East Kilbride.
This would be brought about by a two-pronged approach -- a business
case backed by customers and a careful programme of industrial action.
Ballot papers on industrial action -- which would only be taken as a
last resort -- would go out within the next 10 days.
In the meantime the workforce hoped to have an emergency resolution
debated at the weekend at the Scottish Labour Party conference in
Inverness.
Sir Ralph Robins, chairman of Rolls-Royce, said in a statement that
restructuring at the company had continued ahead of plan.
At the year-end the workforce stood at 41,000, a reduction of 10% in
the year and more than 20% since the programme was announced in 1993.
During the year Rolls-Royce's job cutting cost #95m in restructuring
charges.
Sir Ralph added: ''Our 1994 results, despite lower sales, reflect both
the greater efficiency arising from our continued restructuring and the
successful development of the Trent 700 and 800 engines which have
passed significant milestones in the past year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'95 signals return of the Young Pretender</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BONNIE Charlie's coming back safely o'er the friendly main.
On August 19 the Young Pretender will return to Glenfinnan, to mark
the 250th anniversary of the Raising of the Standard there which
launched the 1745 Jacobite rebellion.
His reappearance is part of the celebrations of the event being staged
by the National Trust for Scotland announced yesterday in London, the
city Charles Edward Stuart failed to reach.
The re-enactment will take place before the opening of the annual
Glenfinnan Highland Games, and the end of the rebellion will be marked
on April 16, 1996, by a memorial service at Culloden.
Other events commemorating the '45 will include an exhibition in the
Clan Donald Library, Skye, showing the clan's role in the rebellion; an
exhibition of royal tartans in the Royal Museum of Scotland, including
the only proven one worn by a Stuart king; and Charlie's Year, an
exhibition in the Kelvingrove Art Gallery and Museum which will seek to
reveal the truth behind the myths. Other events will be held in the
Hebrides throughout the year.
The trust is looking to the National Lottery to provide it with the
funds for its work, Mr Douglas Dow, director of the National Trust for
Scotland said. A proposal seeking cash to allow it to operate the Mar
Lodge estate is currently being considered by the National Heritage
Memorial Fund, which will allocate the #150m the lottery is expected to
raise annually for heritage projects.
''The lottery is a marvellous thing for the heritage,'' said Mr Dow.
''The situation has changed out of all proportion and we may be able to
save a lot more of Scotland's heritage as a result.''
</TEXT>
