<HEADLINE>Estate with a pedigree is sold</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE estate in Inverness-shire where the golden retriever was first
bred in the nineteenth century has been sold.
Sprawling Wester Guisachan was the location for a Pedigree Chum
television commercial which ran for 18 months.
An unnamed Dutch industrialist paid more than #575,000 for the
10,000-acre estate at the foot of Glen Urquhart.
The new owner intends to manage the estate along traditional lines.
The deer stalker has been re-employed and a farm partnership arrangement
is be continued.
Sir Dudley Marjoribanks, the first Lord Tweedmouth, started breeding
golden retrievers as gun dogs around 1835 on the estate, which was said
to have had some of the finest stags ever killed in the Highlands.
Records kept by his family show how he created the new breed from
carefully planned matings between yellow retrievers and two Tweed
water-spaniels.
The estate was originally part of Clan Chisholm and Fraser lands until
bought by Sir Dudley.
</TEXT>
