<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police rebuke climbers who defy warnings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO Highland police officers based in popular climbing areas attacked
''nutter'' climbers who ignore avalanche warnings and urged them to stay
off the mountains when avalanches are forecast.
With police and mountain rescue teams bracing themselves for an
invasion of climbers this weekend -- despite renewed avalanche warnings
-- two officers regularly involved in co-ordinating rescue operations
launched a strong attacks on climbers who ignore a comprehensive
avalanche warning system which is paid for from the public purse.
A total of 14 people have died in climbing accidents in Scotland so
far this year while another six are still missing, including three from
West Yorkshire who are feared to have died in an avalanche in Glencoe.
The Scottish Avalanche Information Service, based at Glenmore Lodge
near Aviemore, receives #65,000 a year from the Scottish Office to
provide daily forecasts of avalanche conditions through the media and at
mountain resorts.
Avalanche risk information is also provided to climbers on a recorded
telephone information line and warnings are posted at all police
stations in the Northern Constabulary area.
Sergeant Bob Severn, who is based at Northern Constabulary's Aviemore
office, said yesterday: ''The readings help provide daily avalanche
reports and warnings are posted everywhere -- but very few climbers
appear to take any notice.''
A keen hillwalker, Sgt Severn said some climbers ''can only be
described as nutters'', adding: ''I would like to think that if more
people availed themselves of the facts about local weather conditions
then maybe we could reduce the number of deaths on the mountains. We
don't want to spoil people's fun, but the knowledge is there and should
be used.''
Inspector Sandy Mackenzie, who is based at Fort William police office
which co-ordinates rescue operations in the Lochaber area, said that
some climbers on excursions from far afield planned their trips for some
time and were reluctant to cancel their arrangements.
He said: ''The attitude some take is I've come all this way, so I'm
heading up into the hills come what may.''
He added: ''I can only plead that they will have more sense this
weekend and stay off the hills . . . it is looking very dangerous once
again.''
The Scottish Avalanche Information Service said yesterday that the
risk of avalanches in Lochaber and Glencoe would be very high and high
today and would probably remain high or considerable in those areas and
in Cairngorm this weekend.
The police officers' criticism was echoed by Mr Blyth Wright,
co-ordinator of the avalanche service, who said the service did not
describe its avalanche information as a warning but issued the
''advice'' in the hope that climbers would take notice.
A spokesman for Northern Constabulary in Inverness was not available
for comment yesterday.
Aviemore police office was at the centre of a rescue operation earlier
this week for two climbers from Cumbria who have not been seen since
they set off near the Cairngorm ski centre on Saturday.
</TEXT>
