<HEADLINE>Banners at centre vetoed as 'tacky'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANNERS with advertising have been used successfully at noted
buildings in Glasgow, London, New York, even Edinburgh itself, but now
according to certain councillors in the capital they're ''tacky'' and
''a second-class idea''.
Yesterday the critics of displays which would be inserted into five
tapering sails planned for the entrance to Edinburgh's #37m
International Conference Centre, due to open this summer, found support
from an amenity watchdog which urged the developers to drop the idea.
The Cockburn Association said it had ''a certain empathy'' with
criticisms made by two councillors on Wednesday when the proposal,
debated before, returned to the district council's development control
sub-committee.
The committee rejected by six votes to five the proposal to
incorporate ''signage'' within the sails element of the main canopy
structure.
Councillor Billy Fitzpatrick described the idea as ''tacky'' and
accused the applicants of trying to wear down the committee.
Councillor Douglas McKay felt the centre was a first-class building
but advertising banners were ''a second-class idea''.
Mr Terry Levinthal, secretary of the Cockburn Association, believed
the centre should now accept defeat. The association did not like
''things hanging off buildings''.
The sails were included in the original design and have planning
approval. Material which would be inserted on either side of the 25ft
high vertical sails is the stumbling block.
The signage would either identify the centre or advertise a particular
conference.
A report to the committee highlighted their successful use at Glasgow
Royal Concert Hall, Edinburgh's National Portrait Gallery of Scotland,
London's Design Museum, and New York's Museum of Modern Art.
Councillors in favour claimed it was the most important building in
the city for the last 10 years and there had to be some advertising to
let the public know what was happening.
A spokeswoman for the centre said that it had taken on board what was
said at the meeting and was looking at suitable options.
</TEXT>
