<HEADLINE>Musical mugging</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID BELCHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Belcher raves about the merchants of doom
ANY attempt to hymn the diffuse and bittersweet glory of Tindersticks
is bound to fail. What's their music like? It's a thing of shabby
gentility. It's like skeins of smoke, kinda blue and floaty.
Tindersticks' music is languidly propelled by multi-faceted lyrics which
were evidently written in a collaboration between Joe Orton, Edward
Thomas, and T S Eliot.
Tindersticks echo the Blue Nile, albeit with a greater air of
regretful resignation. Tindersticks may be the chamber-orchestral
version of Portishead. Crooning with doomed elegance, Tindersticks'
vocalist Stuart Staples could well be Bryan Ferry's younger brother.
But only if Bryan Ferry had a younger brother who was prone to 72-hour
drinking expeditions and undergoing baroque religious experiences in
strip clubs. And falling hopelessly in love with unsuitable women who
inevitably rebuff him. And only if Bryan Ferry wasn't merely a triumph
of style over content.
Above all, Tindersticks' music is complex without being difficult. So
despite the off-putting fact that jaded, know-all critics like me drool
over it, the Tindersticks are in fact easy to listen to, without ever
being facile.
Oh aye, yon critics blab on about ''Tindersticks' soiled romanticism
and obsessive melancholy'' and their penchant for ''subverting
miserabilism with dry wit''. Notwithstanding, decent God-fearing folk
can listen to Tindersticks and opine that, by gum, it's a bit funereal,
but they've got loads of knock-out chunes.
Tonight's sell-out crowd for Tindersticks' show at Glasgow's old
Athenaeum know all these things. They'll be looking forward to a
vigorous wallow in Tindersticks' woozy, moody, sombre, perverse, and
wholly compelling world. There will be strings attached, of course.
Thirteen sets of them, plus additional brass and woodwind.
All the better to perform some of the swirling, ominous stuff from The
Tindersticks' First Album which the sextet are usually unable to do
live, like City Sickness and The Not Knowing, as well as preview their
forthcoming second album, the laconically-titled and wholly-essential
Tindersticks' Second Album, released on the Polygram-offshoot label This
Way Up on April 3.
There's a song on the new album called My Sister, a bizarre yet
organic tour de force which sums up Tindersticks as well as any of their
creations. A spoken monologue underpinned by a jauntily-sinister musical
accompaniment, My Sister begins in somewhat mawkish childhood
reminiscence. It then encompasses mundane grotesquerie, bleak realism
and black comedy, before winding up standing at a graveside with tears
in its eyes.
Ah, but tears of laughter or tears of woe? Listeners may wind up
feeling unable to decide whether they've been mugged by Leonard Cohen or
Les Dawson, or both.
Reassuringly, Tindersticks' guitarist, Neil Fraser, has no time for
such airy posturing. He evinces a fetching modesty, opting to view
Tindersticks as down-to-earth artisans and not flouncing artists. How
else do you explain the band's decision to assemble all their record
sleeves themselves, even going so far as to hand-number and hand-crayon
some of their limited-edition singles? Of My Sister, Neil will merely
say that it is perhaps a little bit abstract, but definitely funny.
Tindersticks' audience: in this era of hideous blare at 143
beats-per-minute, who are your people?
''Forty-year-old lecturers . . . 15-year-old girls. There are some
records that you need to make an effort to get hold of, like ours . . .
and so the folk who've made the effort must have something about them.
But we carry on regardless. Some folk will like you; some folk won't.
''We're doing what comes naturally, which isn't always slow and
melancholy. But we aren't going to pander; to try to be more accessible,
whatever that means. We aren't going to go mindlessly up-tempo.''
Hurrah. I clutch my promotional CD copy of the new Tindersticks' album
to my breast, hotly. It is neatly hand-wrapped in a square of thick
brown paper, sealed with a blob of red wax bearing This Way Up's
imprint. So presented, it appears a useful gift and an everyday
surprise. Like Tindersticks.
* If you don't have a ticket for tonight's show, Tindersticks return
to Glasgow, minus the orchestra, on April 23 to play at the Garage.
</TEXT>
