<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Removing classroom curse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
An Aberdeen school is pioneering a scheme for promoting good
discipline in the classroom. The carrot is a reward system for positive
behaviour, and the stick for pupils who breach the code is banishment to
the Remove.
CLASSROOM indiscipline is the curse of teaching. It is persistent,
low-level indiscipline on the part of pupils that wearies teachers. The
most common types of bad behaviour include pupils talking out of turn,
being deliberately idle and avoiding work, hindering other pupils, and
eating in the class.
Indiscipline takes its toll on teachers and disrupts learning.
Research has shown that dealing with low-level indiscipline can cut
teaching and learning time by half.
At St Machar Academy, a 1200-pupil inner-city comprehensive in
Aberdeen, a survey of staff opinion confirmed the debilitating,
disruptive influence of such forms of bad classroom behaviour.
The headteacher, Doug Marr, recalled earlier this week: ''Discipline
came out as being a major concern of our teachers, as would be the case
in every school. Was there something that could be done to address the
behaviour which disrupts ordinary learning and teaching?''
Meg Price, the teacher in charge of the unit for pupils with social
and emotional behavioural difficulties, visited Bebington High in
Merseyside, a school which broke new ground in rewarding and promoting
positive behaviour.
Rowdy pupils who breach the Bebington code suffer the ''consequences''
of their actions, culminating in a spell in the Remove, a room where
they work under supervision until their parents come to school.
Meg Price came back to St Machar with the message that the initiative
could be adapted for the academy. The school's senior management and
senior pupils worked on producing a St Machar version of the classroom
partnership which has been in operation for less than a year. Many
schools are now involved in promoting positive pupil behaviour but none
has gone as far as St Machar.
Mr Marr and the staff most heavily involved -- Meg Price and assistant
head Paul Firth -- are careful not to exaggerate its impact but there
can be little doubt that it does work and is effective.
According to Judy Norton, head of the biggest department, English,
there is a calmer atmosphere about the school. ''More work is being
done, pupils have a greater understanding of why punishments are handed
out and argue less when they are imposed, and there's more of a feeling
among teachers that they should be looking to reward good behaviour,''
she said.
The partnership is for first, second, third, and fourth years, where
the vast majority of ill-discipline occurs. It is not intended to deal
with serious disciplinary incidents such as physical violence and verbal
abuse. St Machar, in common with other schools, has a procedure for
dealing with such incidents which are, in any case, rare.
The partnership is based on a code for pupils which requires them to
respect others and their property; enter and leave classes in a quiet
and orderly way; be prepared for lessons; do what they are asked at the
first time of asking; raise a hand and wait to be asked before speaking;
and stay seated unless they have been given permission to move
elsewhere.
The final two requirements can be relaxed, for example for PE, group
discussions in English, modern languages, art, and home economics
classes.
Pupils who behave well in each class are given a credit which goes
towards a certificate, or award, for each subject. Each department sets
its targets for the number of credits required for each award, which is
at five levels attainable through the school year -- merit, bronze,
silver, gold, and ultimately a diploma of excellence.
Said Mr Marr: ''The basis of the system is to praise and reward pupils
who conform to the classroom code, to try to change fundamentally the
climate in the classroom. Pupils are going to respond to the person who
responds positively to them, who values their contribution.''
Mr Firth said pupils enjoyed receiving awards, but it was also
important for teachers to have something positive to say to each
youngster in the class. ''It's bloody hard but it's a nice thing to do,
although I don't think we've seen the real pay-off from that yet,'' he
said.
There have, however, been teething problems. Some teachers have found
the emphasis on being positive difficult to come to terms with, seeing
it as a threat to the way they handle discipline in the classroom.
St Machar also has its Remove, which accommodates pupils who have
breached the code on five occasions in the course of a class lasting one
or two periods. They also remain there until their parents or guardians
come to the school to talk about the breaches of discipline with their
child and a senior member of staff.
''I think the vast majority of parents want us to get to grips with
the small minority who regularly disrupt learning and teaching. Some
parents are, however, expressing dissatisfaction because they are
constantly being summoned to the school to have their child released,''
said Mr Marr.
The Remove is not a nice place. The walls are bare and the room
contains the minimum of furniture. Pupils sit facing the wall and copy
material from textbooks, supervised throughout the day by a teacher.
They are not allowed to talk until permission has been granted, and may
leave only to go to the toilet and for lunch.
There are playground myths about the Remove being better than being
taught in the classroom, but the fact that 53 out of the 74 pupils who
have been detained do not return tells a truer tale.
Jade, a second-year pupil, has been in the Remove three times. She
said her present detention would be her last. ''It's not much fun. It's
quiet, stuffy, and you get bored a lot. It feels like a long day.'' She
had been in the Remove for three days -- for repeatedly talking back --
and said her mum was coming to the school the next day to secure her
release.
James, a first-year pupil, had also been in the Remove for three days,
and for the third time. ''Some folk get put in and show off about it but
I don't because I hate it. I live with my gran and grandad and they said
they'll leave me in until I've learned my lesson. I've learned it this
time.''
Pupils are as aware of the consequences of breaching the code as they
are of the rewards that go with being an ''honest citizen''. They start
each class with a clean slate.
As Meg Price put it: ''There is no discipline system which has all the
answers but, with the partnership, we're attempting to put the teacher
back in control in the classroom so that there is no diversion from the
school's central purpose of teaching and learning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
