<HEADLINE>Treasures from an angst-free age</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468525</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER 14 years at the top of Buchanan Street, Glasgow's Ewan Mundy
Gallery has relocated to a handsome new space in West Regent Street
which is more accessible and visitor-friendly. Mundy specialises in
top-class pictures from the first half of the century and has opened the
gallery with a stunning exhibition of work by that favourite Scottish
Colourist, Francis Campbell Boileau Cadell.
The show is a joy: full of colourful, angst-free pictures that
delight. No hand-wringing here, just unashamed indulgence in the good
things of life: the idyllic beaches of Iona, elegant Edinburgh New Town
apartments, and lovely women.
Cadell, by nature a wit and bon viveur, made hedonism into an art.
Mundy's star exhibit is Miss Don Wauchope, red-haired, beautiful and
aloof, in full glory wearing a big black hat and gold hoop earrings.
It's a magnificent picture, captured with an impressive economy of
means.
Cadell's passion for colour proved controversial. ''Vulgar screaming
farces . . . the drawing of which any schoolchild would be ashamed'',
raged one reviewer in 1920.
Yet the overall impression is of sunshine: a breezy-day Port Bhan,
cattle on the shore and a thatched croft perched by the deep blue sea
and miles of empty white beach. ''He captures the pulse of the place,''
says Mundy. ''The light in Iona is extraordinary. Cadell's colours, his
mauves, lilacs, azure, and turquoise blues are not exaggerated in any
way.''
Today when art has become so ironic and socially self-aware, these
refreshing, euphoric images of a less pressured era are to be treasured.
</TEXT>
