<TEXT>
* ''LAID back'' is scarcely the image that springs to mind with
pedal-pushing: huffing and puffing to the top of the Mound is more like
climbing Everest for all but the dedicated physically fit. But,
anatomically at least, that's the concept which Edinburgh-based
Aerobikes are hoping will excite cycling enthusiasts, and win new
converts.
Believed to be Scotland's only cycle makers -- bringing the craft back
to the capital after a century -- designers Loren Hufstetler and Robert
Turner claim comfort, safety and efficiency are better achieved with the
rider in a reclined position, butt resting on a low-level seat and legs
stretching out to pedals over the front wheel.
At first sight it's uncomfortable and ungainly; but once ''recumbent
riding techniques'' are mastered the machine's better stability and
improved visibility through a windshield can rapidly translate into
confident commuting and long-distance biking. Had it been around in the
eighties, though, Norman Tebbit could hardly have commended it as a
passport to employment, with a pricey tag of #1150 to #1850. Despite
this, Turner and Hufstetler expect a waiting list, both home and abroad,
for their hand-built, luggage-accommodating velocipede. To order, phone
0131-657 5655.
* SPRING . . . and a young man's fancy (even a young woman's) turns to
thoughts of picking up a trinket at the High Street jewellers that
betokens undying affection.
All too often, alas, it's a rash choice -- for nickel in costume
jewellery can spark off an allergic reaction in sensitive skin. Your
partner may be itching to tell you, but doesn't want to hurt your
feelings. Thankfully, a solution is at hand: Skin Guard 2000, produced
in Scotland, sets up an invisible protective barrier against irritants.
Odourless and non-greasy, it's available in 30ml bottles, costing #2.99
at selected chemists or phone 0131-557 3622 for mail order. Then you can
grin and wear it.
* TAILPIECE: The Scottish Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals is stepping up its efforts to eliminate ''cosmetic'' tail
docking with an appeal to the public to report suspicious cases. Docking
by vets is still allowed, although the Royal College of Veterinary
Surgeons believes it is unethical. If a new dog appears in your area
with its tail docked, contact a local inspector or the SSPCA's HQ on
0131-225 6418.
</TEXT>
