<HEADLINE>Italy will stand trial with Andreotti</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anne Simpson reports from Milan as the latest Mob murders serve to
remind Italy about the evil of its darkest secrets.
SHOULDERS hunched, the head jutting forward at a rigid angle, Giulio
Andreotti already looks like a man with his neck in a noose. This week
the former Italian Prime Minister once regarded as the custodian of his
country's wellbeing and now accused of Mafia cronyism, pursued his new
role of frail septuagenarian during the trial in Reggio Calabria of
Salvatore Riina, charged with involvement in the murder of an appeals
judge in 1991.
For Andreotti the timing could not have been more disobliging, for
elsewhere the Mafia was once again reminding Italians of its monstrous
lust for blood. As Andreotti was denying any acquaintanceship with
Riina, boss of bosses, the capo of Cosa Nostra, Sicily's gang warfare
had claimed another three victims, bringing the number of assassinations
to 10 in just over one week.
So far no blame for the killings has been attributed but the
indications suggest an inscrutable power struggle within the Mob itself.
Riina's capture in 1993 left the organisation in disarray and was the
result of evidence given to the authorities both in Italy and the United
States by disaffected members of the clan. A fugitive for 23 years,
Riina headed the Mafia's Corleone stronghold in the hills south of
Palermo where his ruthless control gained him the nickname of The Beast.
Andreotti, seven times Prime Minister for the Christian Democrats and
for six years the governing party's Foreign Minister, is now not only
alleged to have had political links with the Mafia but to have been seen
embracing Riina in 1987, a gesture indicating oneness with the
brotherhood. Today these present murders, bodies hideously frozen by
gunfire in Palermo streets, serve to remind Italy about the evil of its
darkest secrets. And for the first time this painful confrontation
appears to have real meaning. The old, complicated acceptance of
treachery as some sort of demonic gene in the country's national life
seems finally in scant supply.
This significant change of mood began emerging three years ago after
the brutal death of Judge Giovanni Falcone and his wife. Falcone's car
was bombed because his effective pursuit of the Mafia had led beyond the
usual territory in the south to secret, bulging bank accounts in
Switzerland and to corners of laundered riches in Milan. Since then the
investigations by Milan's own magistrates into bribery and the illicit
funding of political parties have located connections with the Mafia,
placing all manner of notable names under scrutiny, but none more
''respectable'' than that of Italy's most prominent post-war statesman.
''Once the ball of thread began unravelling it was perhaps inevitable
it would lead to Andreotti,'' says one political observer in Rome.
''There had always been rumours but they were jokey rather than anxious
suspicions, yet in this country a man doesn't remain pivotal to politics
for around 45 years without doing deals with nasty people.''
Even so, Italy's already troubled equilibrium has been further damaged
by Judge Agostino Gristino's decision the other week that Andreotti will
stand trial in September on charges that he acted as protector and
friend of the Sicilian Mafia during his long stewardship of the country.
Thus the stage will be set for a remarkable courtroom drama in which
the prosecution will seek to prove that the 76-year-old politician was
''a man of honour'', the cynical gangland euphemism for full membership
of the Mob, and that Andreotti also carried out favours for the most
notorious criminal organisation in the world.
For his part Andreotti denies the charges, calling the trial
''unjustified'', its only advantage being that those who accuse him will
be ''examined and cross-examined''. The prosecutor's case is contained
in more than 86,000 pages of testimony from prominent Mafia pentiti, the
Italian word for turncoats. In return for leniency these men have broken
their vows of silence, and among them is Tomaso Buscetta who lives in
America under an assumed identity but, on several occasions, has
returned to Italy to finger both local and national politicians.
However, the most threatening evidence is said to come from
Andreotti's own Sicilian Christian Democratic proteges who finessed
mutually beneficial arrangements between the party and the Mafia because
of their common hatred of communism. And here, in fact, may lie a key to
Andreotti's staying power in other contexts.
All through his tenure as Italy's most stable politician his stand
against the communists ensured support from US governments and the
church. His outward adherence to Catholic orthodoxy on abortion and
divorce, for instance, always won Vatican approval, and indeed he
attends Mass every morning, claiming that whatever woes may have
befallen him, his religious faith and knowledge of his innocence
safeguard him from thoughts of suicide.
Always respected as a brilliant tactician, Andreotti insists that he
is not the target of a conspiracy aided and abetted by enemies in
America. But increasingly he looks like an old fixer who is running out
of luck. Last month his lawyers were unsuccessful in arguing that the
autumn trial should be transferred to Rome where it would be heard
before a special tribunal for criminal charges against government
ministers. Dismissing the plea, Judge Gristino set the event for Palermo
on September 26.
Andreotti faces 20 years in jail if convicted, and today when he
speaks to the judiciary or to the press his words are precise but light
as a whisper as if the very breath that carries them is rationed.
''If he has done these things,'' says Angelo Ponte, a lecturer in
politics, ''he is the devil incarnate, but if not, nothing will ever
compensate for his character destruction.'' But because the implications
of this whole business are so shocking many hope for Andreotti's
acquittal, otherwise his guilt, they say, will tell Italians something
terrible about themselves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
