<HEADLINE>Get ready for meltdown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
For weeks, an array of sweetie gifts
has been out on the shelves to
tempt shoppers. Deedee Cuddihy
considers the advent of the
chocolate Easter egg and tests
what's on offer -- with the help
of some volunteer experts
We are the third
biggest eaters
of cocoa in the
world after the
US and Germany
IF all the Creme Eggs made by Cadbury during the run-up to Easter this
year were stacked on top of one another, the pile would be 900 times
higher than Mount Everest (or so it's claimed).
To save you all the bother of measuring a Creme Egg and dividing it
into the height of Mount Everest to discover just how many eggs we're
talking about, let me tell you that Cadbury produce about 300 million of
those gooey, sticky things each year; 200 million of which are consumed
in Britain, the rest exported mainly to Canada and the United States.
Here's another statistic for you, one which is even harder to swallow:
chocolate sales in the United Kingdom now total more than #3000m
annually, making Brits the third biggest consumers of cocoa in the world
after the USA and Germany.
Although there has been a drop in the number of 15 to 24-year-olds --
the age group that consumes the most chocolate -- an increase in
snacking means that sales have continued to grow.
Chocolate buying at Christmas (#650m!) accounts for more than 20% of
annual sales, but hardly have we smacked our lips over the last of the
festive Milk Tray or an edible Santa than the confectionery companies
are gearing us up for Easter (not forgetting the preceding special days
devoted to St Valentine and dear old mum, of course), when we will spend
a further #226m on eggs, eggs, and more eggs, as well as an increasing
number of assorted chocolate animals including bunnies, ducks and bears
and (new this year) the dreaded Power Rangers.
As well as the Creme Eggs -- and it can't have escaped your notice
that other confectionery giants such as Mars and Nestle -- Rowntree have
now come up with their own versions to rival the Cadbury's original,
which first appeared in 1971 -- we also buy 80 million chocolate-shell
eggs every Easter.
Cadbury, according to an interesting little leaflet produced by the
company, brought out its first Easter eggs as long ago as 1875 and by
1931 chocolate eggs were being attached to an extraordinary range of
Easter gift items, everything from watches and necklaces to saucepans
and sets of cutlery which make today's novelty mugs and egg-cups seem
quite modest by comparison.
The Second World War brought chocolate-egg production to a halt
between 1940 and the early fifties, but in the swinging sixties, when,
according to Cadbury historians, many of the Easter traditions like
Easter bonnets, new clothes and egg-rolling were forgotten, ''Easter
eggs had come to represent the crucial gift and all the major
manufacturers worked hard to provide a variety of products''.
Of course, eggs at Easter are a lot older than Cadbury's. At one time
they were a forbidden food during Lent but came into their own again on
Easter Day, when they were given as presents, in decorated form, to
friends and servants.
I remember the Easter egg hunt of my youth in America when we would
look for hard-boiled eggs whose shells had been delicately coloured with
special dyes. What I can't remember is what effect eating as many as six
hard-boiled eggs in one day had on me.
To say that these days we are spoiled for choice where chocolate
Easter eggs are concerned would be an understatement, although it's
worth pointing out that in 1925 Fry's Easter range comprised 50
different items, including chocolate bears, lions, pigs and elephants.
Now there is a foil-wrapped Easter egg in a fancy cardboard box to go
along with any chocolate bar you can think of.
A more recent development is something called character merchandising
where the product is tagged, not to an existing bar or brand of
chocolate but to a well-known character such as Postman Pat or Rupert
the Bear. Kinnerton, a British confectioner, was a pioneer in this field
when it first set up in business some 15 years ago. Its range now
includes numerous Beatrix Potter characters and while the confectionery
is, no doubt, excellent, it is Peter Rabbit and his chums and the
novelty packaging which attract consumers.
Always on the look-out for new ways to get us to spend even more money
on their products, confectioners must have been delighted with recent
claims that chocolate is actually good for you. The London-based
magazine, Natural Products News, reported that ''the main saturated fat
in chocolate is stearic acid, which is metabolised in the body to form
oleic acid, the mono-unsaturated fatty-acid that occurs in olive oil,
and which is widely considered to be good for the heart''.
So, who knows? Cadbury's and the like may soon be exhorting us to ''go
to work on a chocolate Easter egg''.
No article about chocolate Easter eggs would be complete without a
taste test of some of the hundreds of products available and without too
much difficulty, we persuaded the Lynas family -- Arthur, Monique and
daughters Kerry, and Eilis (nine-month-old Siobhan was asleep most of
the time) -- to try out a few on your behalf. Elizabeth Shaw
Chocolatiers supplied four examples for the test and the others were
bought from a variety of retail outlets.
At the end of a gruelling two-hour session, we were all feeling
somewhat jaded. However, it was generally agreed that the Kinnerton
Barbie milk-chocolate egg (#1.99 including badge, heart-shaped sweets
and cut-out bookmark) and the Elizabeth Shaw milk chocolate egg with
assorted truffles (#3.99) tasted the best and that the Power Rangers
milk-chocolate egg with jellies (99p exclusive from Woolworths) was the
least nice.
We also tested four creme eggs -- Cadbury's, Mars, Rolo (approximately
26p each) and Thornton's Champagne (49p) -- with the Cadbury's coming
out best followed by the Thornton's and the Rolo. No-one liked the Mars
egg.
In addition, we tried some Boots diabetic chocolate drops (95p a bag)
which everyone enjoyed; a carob non-dairy, non-chocolate egg (#1.05)
which I loathed but everyone else said was okay but not at all like
chocolate, and two environmentally and politically correct chocolate
bars, one orange-flavoured, the other with banana (approximately #1.70
each from Grass Roots in Glasgow), which everyone else loathed, but I
thought were far superior to everything else we tested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
