<HEADLINE>A Bosnian says thanks to the people with a big heart</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BOSNIAN girl scarred by a sniper's bullet which almost killed her
cuddled up to her father yesterday in a Scots hospital after a mercy
flight from her war-torn country.
Blonde-haired Dzenita Kurbegovic, who could have an operation next
week to rebuild a life shattered two years ago a by bullet, faced up to
media interest, despite an exhausting journey from Croatia.
The nine-year-old, who has speech, breathing and eating difficulties
caused by the throat wound, heard her father Shemso pay tribute to those
who had made it possible for her to travel to Edinburgh's Royal Hospital
for Sick Children.
Her few words as she prepared for a three-day spell of assessment by
medical staff brought no problems for the interpreter. ''She wants to
say cheerio,'' he told reporters.
The medical mission involving Dzenita, said to remember vividly the
day she got caught up in crossfire, was made possible by cash support
the Edinburgh Direct Aid charity.
Treatment at the hospital was recommended by Colonel Michael Staunton,
a Scots senior medical officer serving with the UN force, who knows the
hospital well through being involved in fund-raising for it.
Lothian Health Board has agreed to meet the costs, and hospital
administrators stressed neither patients nor people on waiting lists
would be inconvenienced or held back. Staff were working extra hours to
help the little girl.
Mr Graeme Millar, chairman of the hospital trust, said he was
confident the staff would do their best for a little girl whom many
people had taken to their hearts.
This is the first time the hospital, which has been on stand-by
before, has received a victim of the Bosnian war.
Shemso, a fabrics factory worker and father of two other daughters,
thanked ''the special people'' who had made it possible for her to
travel and ''all people with a big heart''.
Mr Kurbegovic said there were many Bosnian children in the same
position and he pleaded for people's help.
At that point Dzenita got her chance to say ''cheerio,'' but not
before she managed three other words -- ''war is terrible''.
</TEXT>
