<HEADLINE>Labour leader is strong on public ownership but shy on Clause 4 form Blair commits to win over the undecided</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN,POLITICAL REPORTER,ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468533</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair will today reaffirm his commitment to public
ownership in a desperate effort to persuade undecided delegates at
Labour's Scottish conference to back his proposal to rewrite the party's
constitution.
Although his speech this afternoon before the conference in Inverness
is being billed as the clearest signal yet of his intentions, Mr Blair
will stop short of revealing his preferred form of words to replace the
current Clause 4.
He will instead set out what principles he wants Labour to enshrine in
its new constitution and will appeal to the Scottish party to back him
by conceding that, without Scotland, Labour cannot win an election: ''By
working together we can achieve what we cannot do alone.''
He will tell delegates that there is more than devolution on offer.
Democratic renewal for Scotland will come with partnership in ''new''
Britain, ''a Britain where individuals flourish in a community in which
rights and responsibilities are recognised, where power, wealth, and
opportunity are in the hands of the many, not the few, where poverty and
prejudice are overcome, and where we act together to realise the
potential of all.''
He will say Scottish values are Labour's values -- social justice, the
fight against poverty and discrimination, belief in solidarity. To those
who accuse him of being interested only in the south, he will say that,
without a Labour Government in London, there will never be a Scottish
Parliament in Edinburgh.
Mr Blair will say that, far from being a distraction, the debate over
Clause 4 has strengthened the party by attracting new members. He wants
a constitution which makes clear the party's principles and values in
terms ''that cannot be misrepresented''.
A number of drafts for the new clause are in circulation but
leadership sources insist that a final draft has not yet been prepared.
It will be drawn up by Mr Blair and deputy leader John Prescott and
submitted to the party's national executive committee on Monday.
Last night, Mr Blair's staff said he acknowledged that the debate
would have been easier had there been an alternative form of words for
public discussion. His appearance at the Scottish conference is the last
of a series of addresses across the country.
Mr Blair has been under pressure to provide reassurances on public
ownership as a means of heading off an embarrassing defeat. He will say
he sees a role for public ownership but will disappoint traditionalists
by calling for the constitution to express support for a strong private
sector.
Critics of change who believe the current commitment to the common
ownership of the means of production, distribution, and exchange will be
told to argue their case.
A TINY number of the 500 delegates have it in their power to boost
their leader's modernisation of the party or to deliver a humiliating
setback, writes Robbie Dinwoodie, Scottish Political Correspondent.
Both sides in the Clause 4 debate emerged happy from the compositing
process which reduced 26 motions and several amendments to a single
issue: will the 1918 wording aspiring to common ownership survive into
the twenty-first century?
The party's Scottish secretary, Mr Jack McConnell, normally given to
bullish, upbeat assessments, admitted that, with the unions evenly
divided, it was down to ordinary representatives of the rank and file to
call the shots.
''There are two clear positions,'' he said. ''One is that the current
Clause 4 should remain unaltered. The other is the call from the Unison
trade union for a redraft.''
However, supporters of the Campaign for Socialism later made the point
that their motion, while leaving the existing wording intact, did allow
for additions which could modernise its sentiments. This position --
known in internal party jargon as Clause 4 plus -- was seen as having
the potential to sway many waverers who want to modernise the party and
support Mr Blair without jettisoning traditional principles.
However, the left also agreed that the outcome was in the balance.
Campaign co-convener Mary Picken said: ''It all comes down to perhaps a
couple of dozen unmandated constituency delegates. I wouldn't bet on the
outcome, and I'm a betting woman.''
The wording which will be supported by the party leadership today
recognises that the current clause needs to be ''toughened and
sharpened, defining Labour's fundamental principles and values in a
clear and up-to-date manner''.
It calls for a reaffirmation of commitment to public ownership where
justified on grounds of efficiency and equity.
The traditionalists call for Clause 4, and its crucial fourth section
to ''remain unaltered in any redrafted constitution'' because they
represent the ultimate object of Labour's democratic socialism. It does,
however, support a review of the constitution provided it clearly
declares commitment to a public sector, full employment, and social
control of medicine, transport, education, and public utilities.
The campaigners have also inserted a reference to reinvigorated and
devolved local government and to a Scottish parliament based on gender
equality -- a deliberate addition given that Mr Blair this week appeared
to cast doubts on the practicality of this.
</TEXT>
