<HEADLINE>Supermodels too big for their boots, says designer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rome, Thursday,
ITALIAN designer Gianfranco Ferre today said supermodels had become
too big for their boots and had helped turn Milan's twice-yearly fashion
shows into a circus.
''Fashion is becoming a circus. The top models are in decline, with a
few exceptions, and they have abused their roles,'' said Ferre, who will
show his autumn and winter 1995-96 collection tomorrow.
''There are even those who come to Milan, like Claudia Schiffer and
Naomi Campbell, to publicise their books,'' he told Corriere della Sera
newspaper in an interview.
The interview was published hours before Schiffer, one of the
industry's top models who is paid about $10,000 a show, began signing
copies of her new book, Souvenirs et Confidences, (Memories and Intimate
Details) in Milan.
Hundreds of young and old people thronged the bookstore in Milan to
catch a glimpse of the German blonde as she signed autographs and smiled
for the cameras.
Last year, Campbell was in the spotlight, promoting her ghost-written
novel, Swan, an inside look at the modelling industry, and her record
album Love and Tears.
Last October, during the spring and summer fashion shows, Campbell
only appeared in two fashion shows, Prada and Versace, because she was
too busy to do the rest.
Modelling agents say Ferre is wrong and that the supermodels have a
right to do more than just stride down the catwalk.
''The supermodel is not in decline, she's going stronger than ever,
and now she has more commitments,'' said David Brown, a modelling agent,
who represents Campbell and Carla Bruni.
''Ferre's comment is unjustified. Unfortunately, the top girls like
Naomi now have other commitments that are just as important as
modelling,'' Brown said.
No matter what side of the catwalk they are on, the supermodels are
treated like celebrities.
Before the Prada show today, Schiffer was backstage getting a massage
and Campbell was dogged by reporters and photographers.
Miuccia Prada showed off a collection which either flattered models'
figures or turned them into frumps.
There were neat navy or black cashmere coats, double-breasted coat
dresses, and grey suits whose trim-waisted jackets puffed out around the
hips. Black and white leopard print skirts and jackets were also
featured.
</TEXT>
