<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Widespread approval for MPs' Post Office plc plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS,INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREATER commercial freedom for the Post Office, including the removal
of all restrictions on the business activities of sub-postmasters, while
retaining a core number of Crown Post Offices was urged by a powerful
committee of MPs yesterday.
At the same time, Labour pledged to halt the closure and franchising
of post offices if it wins the next election, and joined the Union of
Communications Workers in campaiging for the retention of the remaining
750 Crown offices.
The all-party Trade and Industry Select Committee was unanimous in its
call for legislation to convert the service into a 100% Government-owned
plc, outside of the Public Sector Borrowing Requirement, as a way of
loosening the financial ties with the Treasury.
Board of Trade President Michael Heseltine had wanted to sell off 51%
of the Royal Mail and Parcelforce while retaining PO Counters in the
public sector, but was forced to pull back for fear of a rebellion by
back-bench Tories.
In evidence to the committee in January, Mr Heseltine left no doubt
that he would still like to privatise, and it is believed that if he
does accept the committee findings, it is likely to be on the basis of a
compromise towards possible privatisation at a later stage -- although
presumably not before the next General Election.
Labour trade and industry spokesman Brian Wilson suggested the report
left Mr Heseltine ''isolated and petulant'', and said ''he should now
show some respect for public opinion and the conclusions of the
all-party committee by adandoning privatisation once and for all.''
The MPs concluded that continuing uncertainty over the future was only
benefiting foreign competitors.
Their recommendations included: Legislation to convert the Post Office
into a 100% Government-owned plc; sale of Government shares subject to
parliamentary approval; removal of restrictions on the activities of
sub-postmasters; and a minimum acceptable number of post offices,
including Crown offices.
The report states: ''No solution will be perfect, but we believe that
the plc option is the only realistic opportunity available at present.
It would enable greater commercial freedom in the short term, and pave
the way for a successful future in either the public or private
sectors.''
Committee chairman, Labour MP Richard Caborn, said converting the Post
Office into a limited liability company with the Government as sole
shareholder was the best way out of the present ''malaise''.
Post Office chairman Mike Heron ''applauded'' any proposals that would
lead to genuine commercial freedom.
Mr Bill Cockburn, PO chief executive, said: ''The select committee
report is very supportive and we look to the Government to respond
quickly and decisively. We want the Post Office of the future to be a
dynamo, not a dinosaur.''
The Communication Workers' Union welcomed the report and said the main
recommendation to convert the Post Office into a Government-owned plc
was ''imaginative''.
Mr Colin Baker, general secretary of the National Federation of
Sub-Postmasters said the federation was ''extremely pleased''.
</TEXT>
