<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UK voices fears on plan for EU police agency</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels, Thursday
THE European Union yesterday took a step closer to setting up its own
cross-frontier intelligence agency, Europol, which will fight organised
crime.
But progress was slowed by Britain whose Home Office Minister of
State, Mr Michael Forsyth, warned that the British Government is worried
at the prospect of the European Court of Justice (CoJ) having an
overseeing role in the agency's work.
The Government's view of the Luxembourg-based court has been soured by
a series of judgments which have gone against Britain in recent times.
If EU plans are adopted, the court would have jurisdiction in
Europol's work, a fact which would infuriate Conservative Eurosceptics
and provide another stick with which to beat Premier John Major.
Mr Forsyth told reporters: ''We are anxious to see Europol up and
running, but we underlined our reservations about the involvement of the
CoJ.
''This is an inter-governmental matter and we don't see there is any
role for the CoJ. It is important it should remain inter-governmental.''
Europol exists already in embryo form in The Hague. It is currently
the European Drugs Unit.
Eventually, once agreement is reached, it will work with EU member
states' police forces combating a series of cross-border crimes
including drug trafficking, car theft, illegal immigration and the
so-called ''trade in human beings'' mostly involving refugees who are
bought and sold for cheap labour.
Ministers want Europol eventually to tackle terrorism but not until it
is established and working smoothly, perhaps two years from its
start-up.
The new agency will have no active units and the EU has been at pains
to play down the idea that it will be Europe's answer to the American
FBI.
Europol will, instead, be mainly a data base for cross-border criminal
intelligence and will act as a liaison agency with various police
forces.
For the past few months, member states have been bickering over the
question of how much sensitive information can be made available by
Europol and to whom.
Ministers have now made progress towards resolving this question by
setting up an elaborate scheme in which intelligence will be graded
according to sensitivity.
Some will be readily accessible to any police force but the more
sensitive intelligence will only be released once police forces have
satisfied Europol and, if necessary, other states, that a ''need to
know'' genuinely exists.
The French, holders of the rotating EU presidency, want the Europol
issue agreed before they hand over the leadership of the community to
Spain in July.
A special informal meeting of home affairs and justice ministers is
scheduled for next month before a meeting in June, just before the
Cannes summit, when final agreement should be reached.
The EU believes an effective Europol is essential if the new single
European market with its disappearing border posts is not to be
exploited by organised crime.
The Community is concerned that public worry about border insecurity
and crime does not express itself in the blocking of further European
integration.
</TEXT>
