<HEADLINE>Envoy warns of all-out war in Bosnia and Croatia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Thursday,
CEASEFIRES in Bosnia and Croatia are beginning to unravel, according
to United Nations special envoy Yasushi Akashi, who appealed to
combatants today to avoid sliding back into war.
Bosnia's current four-month ceasefire is regarded as more unstable
than Croatia's, which has generally held since 1992, and Akashi planned
urgent talks with Bosnian government and separatist Serb factions in the
coming days.
But UN sources said little hope remained in the peacekeeping mission
that Bosnia's ''cessation of hostilities'' accord, which expires on May
1, can be salvaged.
''The ceasefire agreement is dead in the water,'' said one UN official
who asked not to be identified.
Akashi said the ceasefire forged by Croatia and rebel Krajina Serbs a
year ago was also ''progressively degrading'' in the wake of Zagreb's
decision to cancel the mandate of 12,000 UN peacekeepers effective from
April 1.
He said the number of truce violations along the UN-patrolled
separation line between the two parties had risen from 140 at the end of
December to 220.
Bosnia's UN-brokered ceasefire, signed on December 31, is become
increasingly unstable around Sarajevo and elsewhere.
''Unless the parties to the conflict renew their commitment to the
cessation of hostilities agreement, a further deterioration of the
ceasefire in the coming weeks is almost inevitable, with all its dire
consequences,'' Akashi said.
''Both sides are clearly undertaking military preparations in
violation of the spirit of the agreement,'' added Akashi, the civilian
head of the UN Protection Force (Unprofor) in a statement.
Peacekeeping troops faced new restrictions on their movement and both
the Muslim-led Bosnian government and Serb forces were violating the
Nato-backed UN ban on military flights over Bosnia with increasing
frequency.
He also accused the Croats and Krajina Serbs of military
preparations.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
