<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PLO and Israel kick-start peace bid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Erez, Gaza Strip, Thursday.
ISRAELI Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and PLO chief Yasser Arafat
today set July 1 as the deadline for a detailed accord on a West Bank
troop withdrawal and Palestinian elections.
A timetable had eluded negotiators for months, amid deadlock over how
to expand Palestinian self-rule to the West Bank without endangering
Israelis, and today's announcement was seen as a much-needed
breakthrough in the bedeviled peace process.
United States Secretary of State Warren Christopher welcomed the
success on arrival in Tel Aviv today, less than an hour after the
announcement.
''I congratulate him (Peres) and his team on the progress in
unblocking the negotiations,'' Christopher said after arriving in Israel
on a new Middle East shuttle in which he hopes to break the persistent
deadlock between the Jewish state and Syria.
Christopher arrived from Cairo on the second leg of his Middle East
mission and will meet Arafat in Gaza tomorrow.
Tonight, after a 90-minute meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin and Peres, he said: ''My strong perception is of a renewed
commitment on their part to push ahead in seeking the comprehensive
peace in this region.''
Peres and Arafat were relaxed and smiled after their two-hour meeting
at a joint Israel-PLO command station between Israel and the PLO-ruled
Gaza Strip.
''I would consider it as a breakthrough in the second stage of our
negotiations,'' Peres said.
In the first phase, Israel withdrew from the Gaza Strip and the West
Bank town of Jericho last May, turning over control to Arafat and the
Palestinian police.
Palestinian Economics Minister Ahmed Qureia, who participated in the
meeting, agreed the statelemate was over.
''I think the breakthrough is Israel's commitment to a specific
date,'' Qureia said. ''This time, I'm optimistic about the date.''
Under the initial Israel-PLO accord, Israeli troops were to have
withdrawn from Palestinian towns in the West Bank by mid-July 1994, and
the pullout was to have been followed by Palestinian general elections.
But Israelis balked at ceding West Bank land after Islamic militants
carried out a rash of suicide attacks, killing 56 Israelis since last
October.
Rabin said he considered the time until July 1 as a test period in
which Arafat must prove he can foil attacks by Islamic militants. ''The
only and the main obstacle to moving ahead with the Palestinians is
terrorism,'' Rabin said.
Arafat talked at length about a new security policy. ''I want to
confirm again that we understand the Israeli security needs,'' he said
in a joint news conference with Peres. ''We are doing the best we can in
this regard.''
He hinted he would meet one of Israel's key demands and disarm his
militant opposition, saying he planned to license guns and crack down on
arms dealers.
''We will not hesitate in confronting those who are carrying out acts
of violence and try them before special courts,'' Arafat said.
Peres repeatedly referred to Arafat as ''rais,'' using the Arabic word
which can mean president or head. ''I like the name. I'm studying
Arabic,'' Peres said.
Arafat thanked Peres for what he perceived as a concession by the
Israeli leader. Israel has not recognised Arafat's claim to be president
of the would-be state of Palestine.
Christopher's six-day tour of the region, his first this year, will
also take him to Jordan, Saudi Arabia and Syria and he will be hoping
that any mood of conciliation in the air may prove infectious.
Rabin, who has resisted Syria's long-standing insistence on a full
Israeli pullout from the Golan Heights, captured in the 1967 Middle East
war, said: ''I would like to make it clear: we are capable to achieve
peace with Syria. We want to achieve peace with Syria.''
Referring to Israeli-Syrian talks suspended since December, Rabin
added: ''I believe there is no reason why we shouldn't continue these
negotiations.''
Israeli officials, citing the impact of elections in the United States
and Israel next year, have called 1995 a now-or-never opportunity for
peace with Syria.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
