<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Howard signals 'boot camp' regime for young criminals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468549</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US-STYLE ''boot camps'' where young offenders are sent for a taste of
military discipline could be introduced in Britain, Home Secretary
Michael Howard told the Commons yesterday.
He disclosed at Question Time that he and the Prison Service were
evaluating a study that had been undertaken on the camps.
Mr Howard told Home Affairs Select Committee chairman Sir Ivan
Lawrence (Burton -- Con.), to Tory cheers: ''I share some of your
enthusiasm for some of the facets of the boot camp system and I hope to
make an announcement shortly.''
Mr Howard and Sir Ivan have both visited ''boot camps'' in the United
States -- so-called because of their rigid discipline which includes
parade ground drilling.
A Scottish Prison Service spokesman said last night: ''We have no
proposals to introduce such regimes in Scotland, but of course we will
watch the experience in England and Wales with interest.''
Mr Derek Turner, general secretary of the Scottish Prison Officers'
Association, said Mr Howard's suggestion on ''boot camps'' was a
''knee-jerk reaction'' to public opinion.
Mr Turner said that the Government had abolished detention centres,
believing they were too austere and rigorous.
He added: ''I start to wonder whether the Government knows what it is
doing and why it interferes so much with penal policy. It is driven by
dogma and knee-jerk reactions to public opinion.''
A spokesman for the Prison Service in England said last night that if
the camps were introduced in Britain there would be more emphasis on
vocational training, rather than ''square bashing''.
They would want to see young offenders achieve specific goals before
leaving the camps, with some indication they did not intend to
re-offend.
Sir Ivan had called for Mr Howard to introduce a pilot scheme based on
the US camps.
''These camps provide training in discipline and respect for other
people, which we have lost since the abolition of National Service. They
provide training in the work ethic and respect for other people in
society, particularly families.
''The advantages of this are beginning to percolate into the American
system and ought to be imitated here.''
In the United States, the camps operate on a rigid timetable, normally
starting with early morning runs, followed by periods of skill training,
parade ground drilling, and special sessions with social workers, who
try to discourage the inmates from re-offending.
British ''boot camps'' could replace some of the ''short sharp shock''
centres introduced by former Home Secretary Lord Whitelaw during the
early 1980s.
It has not been decided whether British camps would be run by private
companies or the Prison Service, the spokesman said.
Later, Tory Nigel Evans (Ribble Valley) called for a debate on the
prison regime.
He said: ''I could then have an opportunity to give my full support to
the military-style boot camps that are so popular in the US.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UN seeks blueprint to end world poverty</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FREDRIK DAHL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468550</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Copenhagen, Thursday,
THE United Nations social summit, striving for a formula to end global
poverty, raced against a midnight deadline today to agree a blueprint
for narrowing the yawning gap between the world's rich and poor.
Hours before world leaders were due to start arriving in Copenhagen,
officials struggled to bridge their differences on the summit
declaration, which aims to eradicate poverty, slash unemployment and end
social injustice.
Although progress was made on key areas such as aid to developing
countries and debt, the wording regarding child labour, trade unions and
education remained unresolved.
Delegates from participating states, already under fire from aid
organisations who say the summit proposals are weak, prepared to
continue negotiations throughout the evening.
Government and political leaders from around 120 countries are due in
Copenhagen for what has been billed as the biggest summit in world
history.
Presidents Nelson Mandela of South Africa, Fidel Castro of Cuba and
Francois Mitterrand of France, as well as US Vice President Al Gore and
Chinese Premier Li Peng are among those who will attend the final
meeting tomorrow and Sunday.
Several thousand officials are already in the Danish capital, guarded
by more than 3000 police as they discuss ways of cutting debt, making
aid work harder and other vital issues for the world's 1.3 billion poor.
The whole week-long event will cost more than $30m.
Hundreds of charity, aid, peace and religious groups criticised the UN
conference today for not going far enough to rid the world of poverty.
They blame rich Western governments which are mostly cutting aid
budgets.
Meeting at a former naval base in Copenhagen, the ''alternative
summit'' presented its own resolution urging world leaders to close the
gap between rich and poor.
''No nation so dramatically divided has ever remained stable; no
frontier or force can withstand the despair and resentment that a failed
system is now actively generating,'' it said.
The document called for full and equal rights for women, cuts in
military spending, and an immediate cancellation of the debts of
developing countries.
As officials at the official UN World Summit on Social Development
tried to complete their declaration, the conference devoted its fourth
day to speeches on unemployment -- seen as a ''malaise of the modern
world''.
The meeting hear that out of the world's total workforce of 2.8
billion, more than 800 million people were either hunting vainly for
jobs or were underemployed.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foulkes protest on bank overdraft for the Tories</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MP George Foulkes yesterday questioned how the Conservative
Party had managed to secure a #14m overdraft from the Royal Bank of
Scotland when some of his own constituents could not even get ''a few
hundred quid''.
Calling for a Commons debate on the funding of political parties, Mr
Foulkes (Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley) highlighted claims that the
Tories were struggling to get funds.
He told the House during questions on next week's parliamentary
business that a debate was needed in view of a newspaper report that
Tory Party treasurer Lord Hambro ''has returned from a fund-raising trip
to Hong Kong empty-handed''.
He added: ''I think the Tory Party is in need of some assistance.''
Mr Foulkes demanded: ''I would also like to know why or how they are
able to get a #14m overdraft from the Royal Bank of Scotland -- chairman
Lord Younger of Prestwick -- and they haven't got any collateral.
''They don't own their headquarters. They have got no basis to get
that loan, when some of my constituents can't even get a loan of a few
hundred quid from the Royal Bank.''
Commons leader Tony Newton replied: ''I am sure Conservative Party
chairman Jeremy Hanley will be grateful for your offer of help.''
</TEXT>
