<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>War declared on the ex-commando</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMONS SKETCH,</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979468552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEIR eyes met across a crowded room and in an instant they both
realised it was true. All the messages were there -- the body language,
the subtle signals given out one to another.
Could they resist the temptation to openly declare their relationship,
or would its strength and power forever remain shrouded in mystery?
Then, at last, it was clear for all to see. Yes, John Major and Paddy
Ashdown have absolutely no time for each other.
It has been building for some time, let's face it. Every time Mr
Ashdown gets on his feet in the Chamber these days there is a
perceptible groan from the Tory benches which manages to sort of waft
itself up to the Press Gallery as smoke rises to the ceiling of a room.
Tory eyes roll, eyebrows are raised, knowing smiles and glances are
exchanged, elbows nudged, guffaws released and probably unfortunate
comments -- none of which can usually be clearly heard -- are exchanged
across the floor.
Mr Ashdown duly does his stuff, to dutiful support and roars of
approval from his tiny band of faithful supporters, and Mr Major duly
knocks him down.
It is all a far cry from the days of the Gulf war when Mr Ashdown,
former commando and all sorts of other things which gave him
credibility, was actually listened to by Tory MPs and even the
Government Front Bench. What exactly he has done wrong in the interim --
apart perhaps, from winning almost every by-election in sight by miles
and trying just a little too hard to be all things to all men -- is hard
to discern.
Anyway, Mr Major's animosity could hardly be deeper or less closely
concealed. The Prime Minister had delivered to the House an explanation
of (apparent) shenanigans over electricity and so on which, frankly,
would have baffled dear old Rumpole of the Bailey and had even the most
experienced shorthand writers in despair.
Labour leader Tony Blair came back with a series of questions which at
least earned him praise from the Prime Minister for being ''a
distinguished lawyer,'' but there was no such accolade for Mr Ashdown.
He wanted the Prime Minister to ''cut out the waffle,'' and Liberal
Democratically propounded the theory that the real question was not what
was legally possible but what was right.
Mr Major swept him aside as one might an insect. ''Well, you are not a
distinguished lawyer,'' he witheringly told Mr Ashdown. If you let fly
like that I hope you are never sitting down when you have to take a cool
and calm decision on what is in the national interest.''
Elsewhere, there was a great deal of talk about the European Exchange
Rate Mechanism, with former Trade Minister Neil Hamilton to the fore on
the fact that interest rates in France had had to be raised by 1.5% this
week, notwithstanding the fact that inflation was virtually non-existent
and unemployment was standing at 12.5%.
This, he claimed enthusiastically, had been necessary to confirm
France's status as an ''economic vassal state of Germany,'' and was it
not therefore a cause for congratulation that the Government had not
been obliged to take the same course of action this week?
Mr Major chortled on about exchange rate turbulence, made clear
Britain would not in the foreseeable future be shadowing the
Deutschmark, and trumpeted the current performance of both British
industry and the British currency.
Much talk, then, about the franc and the mark. Not much trouble, as
far as he is concerned, for the John. But what price the Paddy?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
