<DOCNO>GH950310-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Public hoodwinked' claim as Premier tells of legal advice to Treasury Major defends power sale decision</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister yesterday was involved in fresh controversy over
the Government's handling of the #4bn sell-off of the electricity
generators National Power and PowerGen.
Amid noisy exchanges in the Commons, he produced a complicated legal
justification for what the Government had done -- which prompted an
angry response from Labour and a claim from the Liberal Democrats'
leader Paddy Ashdown that the public had been ''hoodwinked.''
Mr Major confirmed that the flotation had gone ahead after the
Treasury's lawyers advised that an impending review of electricity
prices was ''not material'' to the sale.
The admission brought an accusation from Labour leader Tony Blair that
the whole privatisation programme was tarnished by ''at best
incompetence and at worst double-dealing by the Government.''
Millions were wiped off the value of shares in the two companies after
the announcement on Tuesday by the regulator, Professor Stephen
Littlechild, of new curbs on electricity prices -- the day after the
start of trading.
Mr Major told MPs that although the Treasury and the Department of
Trade and Industry were aware Prof. Littlechild was considering a review
of prices the regional electricity companies could charge, he did not
notify them he was going ahead until after trading had begun on Monday
afternoon.
Nevertheless, he said the Treasury had taken independent financial and
legal advice at the end of last week on whether, in the light of the
possible uncertainty, the original share prospectus was still accurate.
''The legal and financial advice they received was that even if the
issue of price controls for the regional electricity companies was
reopened, that was not material to the share sale of the generating
companies,'' he said.
''It was in the light of that legal and financial advice that the
Treasury decided to proceed.''
The explanation failed to satisfy Labour. Shadow Trade and Industry
Secretary Dr Jack Cunningham last night wrote to Chancellor Kenneth
Clarke and President of the Board of Trade Michael Heseltine demanding
an explanation over why the sale had gone ahead.
He said that the information that the regulator was considering a
review was clearly price sensitive and failure to disclose it to
investors amounted to insider dealing.
In the Commons, Mr Blair asked: ''Is it true that when Government
Ministers proceeded with the sale of electricity shares on Monday they
already knew that the electricity regulator was actively considering
making an announcement to cut prices?''
Mr Major told him: ''The fact is that Prof. Littlechild did not decide
to undertake his review until Monday afternoon, after trading had begun
in the shares of PowerGen and National Power. Although the Treasury and
the DTI were aware he was considering the possibility, he had not
notified them even on Monday morning, when stock exchange trading began,
that he had taken any decision to go ahead.''
Mr Major said the Treasury had taken independent financial and legal
advice at the end of last week on whether, in the light of the possible
uncertainty, the share prospectus was still accurate.
He told the House: ''The legal and financial advice they received was
that even if the issue of price controls for the regional electricity
companies was reopened, that was not material to the share sale of the
generating companies.''
To shouts of ''Rubbish'' from the Labour benches, Mr Major said the
generating companies were subject to a wholly different basis of
regulation. ''It was in the light of that legal and financial advice
that the Treasury decided to proceed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
