<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minutes lost as fire kills three</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE children died yesterday after their mother phoned her husband
for help rather than the fire brigade.
Fire swept rapidly through their home in Bradford, West Yorkshire.
About five minutes were lost before rescue services arrived. By then a
girl of three and a boy of 14 months had died in their beds upstairs.
Their two-year-old brother died downstairs.
Mrs Razai Begum, who is eight months' pregnant, escaped from the
blazing house.
Assistant Divisional Officer Vincent Rolfe said: ''We were not
contacted straight away. She phoned her husband and as a result there
was a four or five-minute delay.
''The mother was in the bathroom and we think had smelled smoke, but
the fire was already well alight. She must have panicked.
''When we arrived the front and back doors were kicked in by
neighbours trying to help, but this allowed the air to get in and fuel
the fire.''
Mrs Begum had recently moved to the house with her husband, a taxi
driver. She was was detained in Bradford Royal Infirmary suffering from
smoke inhalation.
The cause of the fire is being investigated but there are not thought
to be any suspicious circumstances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Student numbers set new record</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE number of students at Scotland's higher education institutions is
the highest yet, according to figures issued today.
A bulletin published by the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council
shows that the equivalent of 114,000 full-time students are being taught
this year, up 3% on 1993-4.
The increase includes a 4% overall growth in the subjects of priority
recruitment -- science, engineering, maths, and computing.
Mr John Sizer, the council's chief executive, said: ''In general,
universities and colleges have acted very responsibly and have coped
well with the difficulties arising from the new applications system.''
The controlled expansion in Scotland contrasts with the situation in
England and Wales, where a number of institutions have been financially
penalised after recruiting excess numbers of students.
The largest subject group was science, with 18,800 students (up 5%);
followed by business and administrative studies, 16,200 (up 2%);
humanities, languages, and mass communication, 15,000 (up 4%); and
engineering and technology, 12,500 (up 2%).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Inquest jury sees video of body find</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN inquest jury last night saw a video showing the naked body of an
appendix patient who crawled among heating ducts in a hospital boiler
room to die.
The jury was shown a police video of the basement cranny in which the
remains of Mr Carlos Padillo were found, a month after he threatened a
nurse and disappeared from his ward at St Thomas's hospital in London.
The shocked hospital engineer who found the decomposing body told the
inquest at Southwark Coroner's Court how he began searching after staff
complained of a bad smell.
Mr Brian Shrubsole said he wriggled through a small gap and saw the
missing patient's body on January 20.
The video showed the body, still with surgical stockings on the legs,
huddled beneath the ducting.
The boiler room -- directly accessible only by a service lift -- was
on the third floor, eight floors away from the ward where Mr Padillo had
been recovering from surgery.
The inquest heard that Mr Padillo, 40, who had a drinking problem,
told doctors he had tried to commit suicide and wanted to die during his
routine operation.
After he disappeared early on December 22 last year, hospital security
staff and police with sniffer dogs searched the hospital and the
surrounding area.
The surgical gown he was wearing was discovered on a stairwell but no
other trace was found, the inquest heard.
On December 22, Mr Padillo got out of bed and threatened a senior
nurse with an intravenous painkiller pump unit. He then ran out of the
ward, smashing a fire-escape window as he left.
It was found he had a ''markedly'' low amount of oxygen in his blood,
suggesting a potentially fatal blood clot on the lung.
Senior physician Dr Ananth Prasan said ''it would be essential'' the
patient be found so his condition could be monitored and the correct
drugs administered.
But senior surgical registrar at the hospital Andrew Northeast -- in
charge of the patient -- told the inquest he was happy that ''adequate
steps had been taken by the relevant authorities to find the missing
patient''.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judge to rule on refusalof treatment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HIGH Court judge will decide today if a health authority's refusal
to fund life-saving treatment for a 10-year-old girl is in breach of her
''fundamental right to life''.
The father of B, who cannot be named for legal reasons and is
critically ill with leukemia, asked the judge to overturn Cambridge
Health Authority's ''unreasonable'' decision last week, not to pay the
estimated #75,000 it would cost for chemotherapy and a second bone
marrow transplant.
The authority said B was unlikely to survive the ''unpleasant'' and
distressing treatment and its ''limited resources'' could be spent more
effectively on other patients.
Mr Bruce McIntyre, appearing for the father, who gave up work to look
after his daughter at their home in the Cambridge area, told the court B
was bound to die without further treatment, and her fundamental right to
life was threatened.
''It (the authority) has, by refusing funding of this treatment,
effectively taken a step whereby life is denied to this child''.
Mr Nigel Pitt, for the authority, denied it was taking away B's
fundamental right to life.
He said: ''If health authorities spent their money on treatments which
doctors thought extremely unlikely to succeed and then had no money left
to treat hundreds of other patients who might have been effectively
treated, what would the public say about that?''
The court was told that at the age of five B developed Hodgkins
lymphoma and was sent to Addenbrookes Hospital, Cambridge, where she
received chemotherapy and, by August 1992, appeared to have made a full
recovery.
However, 15 months later she was diagnosed as suffering from acute
myeloid leukaemia and was transferred to the Royal Marsden Hospital for
her first bone marrow transplant, the donor being her sister, now aged
nine.
She was released around May 1994, and returned to school. In January
this year she had a relapse and her father was told she had about six to
eight weeks to live and could not be treated further.
Mr McIntyre argued that doctors had agreed that B would have ''a
significant chance'' of her leukemia going into remission if she had
further chemotherapy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concern grows over death of turned-away patient  Hospitals exposed as failing to cope</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HEALTH Minister admitted last night that it was ''entirely
unsatisfactory'' that a patient had to be flown 200 miles for urgent
hospital treatment because he could not be offered a nearer bed. The
patient later died.
Mr Tom Sackville spoke as a row developed over the treatment of
Malcolm Murray, who was taken to Leeds General Infirmary by helicopter
after being hit by a van outside a bar in Orpington, Kent, on Monday
night.
Despite efforts by doctors to find a neurosurgical unit in the
South-east which could take him, the only available bed was in Leeds,
where he died on Wednesday night.
The Prime Minister appeared to seek to justify Mr Murray's treatment
during heated exchanges in the Commons.
He told MPs: ''I have to say, although the final facts are not yet in
front of me, I understand Mr Murray required a very specialised form of
treatment and Leeds was in a position to help.''
But Mr Sackville, in a letter to Mr Murray's MP, Citizen's Charter
Minister John Horam, seemed to suggest the flight could have made
matters worse for the patient.
''It is not clear to what extent Mr Murray's condition deteriorated as
a result of being transferred to Leeds,'' he said.
''It is, however, entirely unsatisfactory that he could not be
admitted to a closer hospital.''
In a letter to Health Secretary Virginia Bottomley, Labour's health
spokeswoman Margaret Beckett said Mr Horam had demanded: ''What on earth
happened here?''
She added: ''I understand he is not the first Minister to complain
about the effect of the reforms and the loss of important local NHS
hospitals and beds.''
She said that Mr John Taylor, a junior Minister in the Lord
Chancellor's department, had reportedly chaired a protest meeting in
support of his local hospital.
She urged Mrs Bottomley to make public the names of other Ministers
who had attacked the effects on their local hospital of NHS ''reforms''.
Mr Horam later accused Mrs Beckett of using his constituent's death
''as a pretext for party political mud-slinging''.
He wrote to her: ''I deeply regret that you should instantly seize
this case to make a cheap political attack, particularly one of such a
puerile and tenuous nature.''
He was satisfied that the investigation launched by the South Thames
Regional Health Authority was the correct response.
Mr Murray, 45, the victim of an alleged hit-and-run incident on
Monday, was initially taken to his local hospital, Queen Mary's at
Sidcup.
He had severe brain injuries which could not be treated there. It has
no neurosurgical unit.
Doctors tried to get him admitted to units in London but the nearest,
the Brook Hospital at Shooters Hill, was closed to new admissions
because of a flu outbreak and all the others refused to take the case.
The Liberal Democrat health spokesman, Mr Alex Carlile, said: ''This
is evidence that the Government has been listening to anyone but the
doctors who have to deal with trauma.
''Why was Mr Murray not airlifted straight to the helipad on top of
the Royal London Hospital where American boxer Gerard Maclellan is being
treated so skilfully by neurosurgeons?
''What would have happened if, yesterday in Orpington, there had been
a disaster involving a number of people with brain injury? Would there
have had to be a procession of helicopters to Leeds?''
The pressure group London Health Emergency said six intensive care
units -- including specialist neuro units at the Brook Hospital,
Atkinson Morley's in Wimbledon, and Oldchurch in Romford -- were under
threat of closure.
Its campaigns director, Mr Geoff Martin, said: ''The pressure on
intensive care beds, and particularly specialist neuro beds, is already
past breaking point as this latest tragedy highlights only too
clearly.''
A 33-year-old landscape gardener has been remanded in custody charged
with the attempted murder of Mr Murray.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anger over legal aid for Adams</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLITICIANS reacted angrily last night to the news that Sinn Fein
president Gerry Adams has been granted more than #9000 in legal aid to
contest an exclusion order -- now lifted -- barring him from mainland
Britain.
A total of #9234 has been paid so far, but the final bill is expected
to be much higher.
Mr Adams has applied for a judicial review of Home Secretary Michael
Howard's decision to exclude him from entering the mainland under the
Prevention of Terrorism Act.
He claims the exclusion order breached European law by preventing free
movement of people within the EU.
The issue has been referred by the High Court to the European Court of
Justice for an interpretation of the relevant EU law.
The figure was disclosed by Lord Chancellor's Department Minister John
Taylor last night in a parliamentary written answer.
He said: ''In dealing with his application for legal aid, Mr Adams was
assessed on the same means and merits criteria as any other applicant
for legal aid, in accordance with the appropriate regulations.''
Earlier this week. Mr Howard promised: ''I shall never authorise any
payment of damages as a result of this case.''
He was speaking amid fears of similar claims by up to 500 other IRA
sympathisers who have also been banned from Britain at some time under
emergency laws.
Mr Andrew Hunter, chairman of the Tory backbench Northern Ireland
committee, said the legal aid rules needed changing.
''I'm horrified. I do not believe a man who has been an apologist for
the murder of British citizens should receive a penny of British
taxpayers' money.
''I condemn this development. It's entirely unacceptable. I can think
of lots of people who have a far better case for legal aid than Mr
Adams,'' he said.
Legal aid is granted to people with limited means who cannot afford to
pay the fees.
Ulster Unionist David Trimble, MP for Upper Bann, asked: ''Has there
been a proper investigation of his means because we know that Mr Adams
is a leading figure in a multi-million- pound empire.
''Sinn Fein-IRA has an income of #6m per annum, and the answer is no
there hasn't been a proper investigation of his means because they are
too scared.''
Liberal Democrat Northern Ireland spokesman Lord Holme said: ''Gerry
Adams would be better advised to concentrate on de-commissioning his
armoury of terror than raking over the coals of his dubious past.
''British taxpayers' money should not be used to help him in his
appeal.''
Tory Peter Bottomley, MP for Eltham, said: ''There are far better
cases for the money to be spent on.
''This will come as a surprise to many people and will upset many
people. The best advice for Gerry Adams is to drop the case and get on
with creating a better future for Northern Ireland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Newly-built lodge to be demolished</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RESEARCH lodge in a Highland glen is to be torn down because of
flaws in the construction, 18 months after it was built at a cost of
#150,000.
Scottish Natural Heritage has decided to build another lodge on the
same site for a similar price.
Iolaire Lodge, in Glen Doll, Angus, was to be used as a research and
educational base for the nearby Caenlochan National Nature Reserve and
sites of scientific interest.
Mr Iain Rennick, SNH regional administrator, said: ''The contractors
made a number of flaws in the way the building was held together. The
flaws raised doubts about safety.
''Surveyors were concerned that part of the building may have been
able to blow in. There was a possible danger to anyone using the
building and we couldn't take any risks.''
Mr Rennick said that the Fife-based contractors involved had gone
bankrupt since the building was finished and the flaws were spotted.
He said: ''We would have asked them to make good the mistakes, and if
they had failed to do that we would have sued them.
''The organisation is very disappointed about this because of the cost
involved.
''It has not been a good experience.''
Work to demolish the lodge is expected to be finished by next month.
It is hoped that the new building will be completed in the autumn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Computer giants criticised for 'excessive' prices</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPUTER games giants Sega and Nintendo ''operate against the public
interest'' in pricing their goods and controlling the market, an
official report by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission disclosed
yesterday.
The report found that ''monopolistic practices'' existed in the
industry, which ''operate against the public interest and have adverse
effects on the prices and availability of video games''.
The two companies, which dominate high street sales of video consoles
and games, are criticised for practising ''discriminatory pricing''
which results in software prices which are ''excessive'' in comparison
with the cost of hardware.
The commission's findings were announced yesterday, 14 months after
the matter was referred to them by the Director General of Fair Trading.
Accepting the report, Corporate Affairs Minister Jonathan Evans
criticised Sega and Nintendo for the restrictive conditions applied to
independent publishers producing games on their consoles, thus
''enabling them to control the supply of video games''.
''The MMC has concluded that the appropriate remedy to open the games
market to more competition is to require certain restrictions in the
licence conditions to be removed,'' said Mr Evans.
He said there would be three months' consultation on the commission's
key recommendations, with a threat that price controls might be imposed
if suitable remedies cannot be agreed.
The commission found that a monopoly existed in favour of Sega Europe
for hardware and software for the year ending June 1994.
It also found that Sega and Nintendo exercised a complex monopoly by
supplying more than one quarter of video games sold in the UK.
The report also noted that the companies incorporated technical
features into their products which made it ''very difficult to produce
software that can be played on their machines''.
The companies also conducted their affairs ''so as to prevent,
restrict, or distort competition'', it said.
The key recommendations are that:
* Restrictions in licensing conditions limiting the number of games
published and requests for approval prior to publication should be
lifted;
* Controls on packaging and presentation should be removed, ''in
particular'' the requirement that Sega and Nintendo arrange or control
the manufacture of cartridges;
* If this does not prove possible, there should be an ''alternative
remedy'' of price controls.
* Restrictions on games rental should be removed, and software
supplied by Nintendo and Sega be ''freely available to rent''.
A statement from Sega Europe said the company's initial reaction to
the commission's findings was one of ''disappointment''.
However, it welcomed the Department of Trade and Industry's decision
to invite comment, and pledged ''full participation'' in the
consultation process.
A spokesman for retailer HMV said: ''We now await the commission's
final recommendations in the hope that we will be able to pass on any
resulting price reductions to our customers.''
Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, Mr Nigel Griffiths, said the
inquiry was ''overdue'' and demanded immediate action.
''I raised with Ministers two years ago the high prices and refusal to
permit rental of these games and nothing was done. Yet millions of kids
have now paid a packet for the games.
''This has been another missed opportunity by the MMC. Even now it's
letting these companies off for another three months. Immediate action
is required.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Future of two more at SNH is uncertain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of two other members of a Scottish National Heritage
regional board has been questioned because of opposition to the proposed
superquarry at Lingerbay, south Harris.
Western Isles Islands Council vice-convener, Mr Angus Graham, was
removed from the north-west regional board of SNH this week for publicly
attacking the organisation's opposition to the quarry.
The two members, Mr Peter Peacock, vice-convener of Highland Regional
Council, and writer and historian Dr Jim Hunter, have never hidden their
deep concern over the SNH approach to the quarry. They are not great
supporters of the proposed operation but are troubled at how SNH arrived
at its stance of outright opposition.
Neither, however, would comment yesterday on speculation that their
continued membership of the regional board was in doubt.
Mr Peacock told The Herald: ''I was in Edinburgh at a meeting of the
Convention of Scottish Local Authorities when all this blew up over
Angus Graham so I really am just catching up with it all. I certainly
can't make any comment on the background to Mr Graham's departure,
neither can I say anything about my own future.''
Dr Hunter, who has been reported as already considering his future for
personal reasons, yesterday would say only: ''My views on Lingerbay have
been well publicised and I have nothing to add. I have no comment to
make on Mr Graham leaving the board or on its future composition.''
Meanwhile, more information has emerged concerning the project which
Mr Graham is convinced finally led to his removal from the regional
board.
He had opposed SNH giving #150,000 to one of the Countess of
Sutherland's family trusts in compensation for not clear-felling 100
hectares of Scots Pine on the shores of Loch Fleet where it was proposed
to establish a national nature reserve.
Lord Strathnaver, the Countess of Sutherland's heir, is also a member
of the SNH north-west regional board which had been asked to support
this project. The propriety of Lord Strathnaver's role in this, however,
is not in doubt.
Mr Graham said last night: ''I am not questioning Alistair
Strathnaver's integrity in any way. It wasn't the case of the trust
coming to SNH and looking for money but rather SNH rushing out and
trying to persuade them to take it.''
An SNH spokesman said: ''Negotiations have been under way for over two
years on the possibility of setting up an NNR on this internationally
important Site of Special Scientific Interest.
''But these have still to be concluded and, until that time, it would
be quite wrong and may prejudice the negotiations themselves to talk of
particular figures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whitelaw in rail attack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VISCOUNT Whitelaw, the former deputy Prime Minister and one of the
Conservative Party's most respected figures, has expressed fears over
rail privatisation and warned Ministers it threatens the existence of
the west coast main line.
In an exclusive interview with The Herald, Lord Whitelaw cast doubts
on its chances of success, and said it was up to Transport Secretary
Brian Mawhinney to provide reassurances.
He has made his views known privately to Ministers, and pledged to
fight for the future of the west coast line, which passes near his home
in Penrith, Cumbria then on to Glasgow.
He said there was no sign that privatisation is working. ''I have
always had doubts, and remain with doubts, about the privatisation of
the railways, simply because there is no evidence yet that this is going
to succeed.''
Lord Whitelaw has joined the campaign to safeguard the west coast main
line organised by MPs and peers along the route.
''My suspicion is that in the end most of the traffic to Scotland will
go up the east coast line. So the future of the west coast line is of
course the great worry.''
Lord Whitelaw's comments coincided with stinging criticism from
out-going BR chairman Sir Bob Reid, who accused the Government of going
about privatisation the wrong way and insisted he would not put any of
his money into it. ''When the chairman of the railways says he thinks
the Government has gone about it the wrong way, there must be something
not quite right.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blackmail claim  over ex-Minister 'stupid'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE woman alleged to have been Robert Hughes's mistress yesterday
surfaced for the first time since he resigned as Citizen's Charter
Minister.
Janet Oates, his Commons secretary, faced journalists gathered outside
her flat in his West Harrow constituency.
According to newspaper reports, she was the woman with whom he had the
affair which led 43-year-old Mr Hughes to announce his resignation on
Monday.
When she arrived at her home, Miss Oates, 36, avoided questions as to
whether she was his lover. In an angry and tearful confrontation, she
was reported as telling journalists: ''I am not saying I had an affair
with him.''
She added: ''I am not in hiding. I am just being hounded. All my
family are being hounded. Just leave us alone.''
When asked if Mr Hughes quit because he was being blackmailed, she
reportedly retorted: ''Don't be stupid. Who would want to blackmail
him?''
The MP's political future looked bleaker yesterday as local Tory
officials began to sound out activists over whether they wanted him to
stay on.
According to some reports, Mr Hughes started a relationship with Miss
Oates after she turned to him for help because she feared her former
boyfriend, who was jailed for nine years for assaulting her, would be
released early from prison.
His constituency chairwoman, Mrs Joyce Nickolay, said the latest
allegations left a question mark over the MP's judgment.
She would take soundings within the constituency over whether people
wanted him to continue as the MP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Canada accused of seizing vessel</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ottawa, Thursday,
THE European Union's executive Commission accused Canada of piracy
today, saying it had seized a Spanish vessel in a row over fishing
rights.
Emma Bonino, the EU commissioner in charge of fisheries, told a news
conference the seizure had taken place outside Canadian waters.
But in Ottawa, Canada denied a news agency report about a Spanish boat
being boarded.
Canada is trying to stop a surge in EU catches of Greenland halibut,
also known as turbot, which it says are threatening stocks of one of the
last commercial species in the region.
Canada later said it had arrested a Spanish fishing boat off its east
coast in the Atlantic Ocean.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whitelaw waves a warning flag Loyal lieutenant hands railway  poser to Major</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VISCOUNT Whitelaw is worried about rail privatisation. He does not
rate its chances of success, and thinks it will mean the slow death of
the west coast main line.
His fears are not the sort of thing Mr Major would wish the public to
hear.
The Government cannot afford to have one of its elder statesmen
expressing concerns -- however politely -- about a policy that is
already in difficulty.
Lord Whitelaw has done it before. Little more than a year ago, he was
one of the Tory peers who gave Home Secretary Michael Howard a roasting
over the Criminal Justice Bill. ''When I find I am anxious and
concerned, surely it must be my duty to speak out firmly, and that is
what I am doing.''
This time it is the railways that are causing him anxiety. Yesterday
in his office in the Lords he spoke cautiously, but his message was
clear: he has always had doubts about this privatisation.
Lest Labour and privatisation's opponents get too excited, he
emphasises his support for the Government. His political longevity and
success are based on an old-school loyalty to the party and its
leadership.
Even on the railways he acknowledges a duty to give ''fair wind'' to a
policy that has been decided by Cabinet. But those closest to the throne
are often the most dangerous.
He is equally adamant about his commitment to the west coast line.
Despite repeated assurances from Ministers, he thinks it is in trouble.
He believes that what he considers the economic lifeline of the rural
area he served at Westminster for 28 years is being eroded, and that it
will eventually be supplanted by the modernised east coast line.
Yesterday's comments from outgoing British Rail chairman Sir Bob Reid
have not helped. Sir Bob said the Government is going about it the wrong
way, and admitted he would not put any of his money into a passenger
franchise.
The break up of BR into a myriad of companies is designed to bring
transparency into the railway's finances. Transparency, where each line,
service, and activity is expected to know its costs and income, will
open the way for private sector investment. Or so the argument goes.
Lord Whitelaw is happy for the Government to give it a try. But woven
through his conversation is an obvious lack of confidence. ''The course
it set to do it, and whether they have got their plans right I don't
know. One is bound to be anxious at whether it is going to work.''
William Whitelaw is not a natural rebel. He once admitted that he
would have been a ''fatal'' choice to lead the party, adding: ''I'm not
good at always being against things.''
His background -- both grandfathers were MPs -- is steeped in public
service. He was born in 1918 in Edinburgh, though the Whitelaws come
originally from Coatbridge.
After entering the Commons in 1955, his career took him to the highest
offices: Chief Whip, Leader of the House, Northern Ireland, Home Office,
Chairman of the Conservative party, and, ultimately, Margaret Thatcher's
deputy Prime Minister.
As the loyal lieutenant he was overshadowed by the Iron Lady --
''Everyone needs a Willie,'' she said.
0 His interest in the railways is a family affair. His grandfather was
chairman of the Highland railway, and when the railways were
amalgamated, he served as chairman of the LNER.
He has expressed his views in private to Ministers. And he has written
to the chairman of the Rail Users' Consultative Committee over the loss
of sleeper and motorail services.
Last month Transport Minister John Watts added to his worries by
failing to turn up for a meeting with MPs and peers fighting for the
west coast line.
The abrupt cancellation -- Mr Watts claimed he wasn't sufficiently
briefed -- still angers Lord Whitelaw. An uncertain Minister does not
reinforce confidence in an unpopular policy.
Lord Whitelaw is too loyal to lead privatisation's opponents from the
front. But by going public the Tories' senior peer has drawn attention
to the disquiet over privatisation that exists at the heart of the
party. And by pledging to continue his efforts to save the west coast
main line, he has effectively warned Mr Major, in the nicest way
possible, that all is not well with the railways.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>By-election battle can commence for the unwitting bystander after an 18-year-old issue is put aside. Back to politics for an angry advocate of independence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN WHAT is destined to become one of the great political
understatements of the year, Roseanna Cunningham looked back on the
SNP's now infamous preliminary selection meeting for the Perth and
Kinross contest and said: ''It is probably not the way I would have
chosen to start the campaign.''
Nor is there likely to be a more optimistic comment than: ''I suppose
that at least there can be few people left who don't know who I am.''
For the benefit of these remarkably few people, Ms Cunningham is the
advocate who contested the seat at the last General Election and came
within just over 2000 votes of taking it from the late Sir Nicholas
Fairbairn. She was then dropped from the provisional shortlist 12 days
ago after an astonishing onslaught concerning her private life during a
preliminary selection meeting.
It was soon clear when details of this secret meeting were leaked, it
concerned an accusation from party president Winnie Ewing that Ms
Cunningham had been responsible for the break-up of the first marriage
of her daughter-in-law, SNP parliamentary leader Margaret Ewing. Ms
Cunningham says she had a relationship with Mr Donald Bain in 1977 only
after the couple had publicly announced their separation.
''I had literally only minutes warning that this issue was coming
up,'' she said, ''and none whatever that it was going to be raised as
dramatically as it was. Had I known I could have taken steps to deal
with it, instead of it becoming the mess it did.
''There is a saying that there is no such thing as bad publicity.
Whether that's true is another matter. What there is, is publicity that
puts you under enormous physical and emotional stress. I was just the
unwitting person, hunkered down while the storm raged overhead.''
Her first reaction was that, although the episode, from 18 years ago,
was a supposed sex scandal that never was, the screaming tabloid
headlines would cause the SNP damage and so she withdrew her name from
the selection process.
However, after what she described as the fantastic support from both
the party leadership and from grass-roots supporters, she put her name
forward again at national conference in Stirling last weekend.
''I am tired but I am angry,'' she said. ''That will see me through. I
am absolutely determined not to be brought down by this and allow it to
affect me politically. It cannot be right that we let tabloid newspapers
dictate to us how our politics should be conducted, as if we have to be
submitted to them for approval.''
For Ms Cunningham, the headlines made strange reading: ''I saw myself
labelled in some pretty amazing ways, ways that meant I did not
recognise myself. I don't think any of my views are particularly
startling.'' One label which has often been applied has been that she is
some kind of republican socialist firebrand on the far left of the SNP
who would be entirely the wrong candidate to fight a rural, conservative
seat.
She claims that the labels are wrong both in terms of herself and the
constituency, pointing out that more than half the electorate of the
seat live in Perth itself, where people living in council houses are
unlikely to be ''more tweedy, or Conservative than anywhere else''.
She says: ''At the end of the day people struggling to pay their fuel
bills face the same problem, whether they live in a city in a council
house, or live in the country in a tied cottage . . . flooding is just
as devastating, whether you live in Perth or Paisley. People are so busy
looking for differences, they don't see the similarities.''
In any event, her own views put her very much in the Scottish
mainstream, she says, and while she is not in favour of the monarchy she
has always adhered to the party line on this. Part of the problem, she
believes, is that because she did not come to the SNP with a background
in Scottish left-wing politics, people don't know where to place her in
the spectrum.
Ms Cunningham was nine when her parents decided to emigrate to
Australia. That was in 1960. ''These were the days of 'you've never had
it so good.' They looked round and thought, if this is as good as it
gets, we're better off out of it, and they booked their #10 ticket to
Australia.''
She attended university in Perth -- Western Australia -- and in 1976
decided to return to Scotland.
''I joined the SNP because of my belief in independence, not because
of any of my other views, and certainly not because they took primacy. I
have been on different sides of debates and have won some and lost some.
That's the way political parties work.
''Once defeated, I always accepted the party line. The royalty issue
is not important enough to make a difference to my party politics.
''I suppose I am left wing, but I am never too sure what people have
in mind by that phrase. I believe in public ownership of some things,
for example, but not centralised state ownership. Housing associations
are a good argument for decentralised public control.''
After a spell of two years as a party researcher on her return from
Australia, she did a law degree and became a solicitor carrying out
court work for local authorities and building up a background in the
local government union Nalgo.
Just over four years ago she became an advocate. In that same year,
1990, Jim Fairlie, the SNP candidate for Perth and Kinross, quit the
party over its pro-European stance, and Ms Cunningham, who was already
on the shortlist for Paisley South, was adopted. Having come close to
capturing the seat in 1992, she was keen to finish the job, but how much
damage has been done to the SNP campaign by the public spat with the
party president?
''There is a danger that this personal issue could have stopped us
running a campaign on political issues. But once the by-election gets
under way I will be put under pressure for my politics and I can handle
that. I can't see where the press can take the personal stuff now,
without simply appearing vindictive, so once the campaign starts in
earnest the focus will shift back to politics.''
Was she sure of that? There was a long pause. ''Yes,'' she said. We
shall see.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chirac widens lead in polls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PAUL TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris, Thursday.
FORMER rivals and show business personalities jumped on Paris mayor
Jacques Chirac's bandwagon today as his lead over fellow conservative
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur widened in France's presidential race.
In a tell-tale sign of shifting winds, Charles Millon, parliamentary
floor leader of the centre-right Union for French Democracy (UDF), came
out in support of Chirac and 22 UDF members of parliament followed suit.
Millon, who briefly toyed with standing himself and hopes to stand for
mayor of Lyon in June, said Chirac was not only a more energetic leader
and reformer than Balladur but also a more committed European.
Most of Millon's movement has backed Balladur and five of its six
component parties demanded his resignation as floor leader. But Millon
retorted that some of his critics were already making their own secret
approaches to Chirac.
Two new opinion polls showed Chirac was now seven points ahead of
Balladur on the April 23 first round and would easily beat either the
prime minister or Socialist candidate Lionel Jospin in the May 7
run-off.
A Louis Harris poll for the magazine Valeurs Actuelles, taken on
Monday, gave Chirac 26% of the vote, Jospin 22 and Balladur 19 on the
first round. It said Chirac would beat Jospin 56-44 in a run-off and
would crush Balladur 60-40.
An IPSOS survey for the weekly Le Point, taken on Tuesday and
yesterday, credited Chirac with 27% on the first ballot, with Jospin and
Balladur tied on 20. It too saw Chirac winning a run-off easily over
either opponent.
Jospin, a former education minister, sought to counter Chirac's surge
in popularity by saying the Paris mayor was too inconsistent and
indecisive to be president.
''If I have to fight Chirac in the run-off, I will recall how he
changed positions on crucial issues for the country and how he has
successively been influenced by totally contrasting ideologies,'' he
told Socialist parliamentarians.
Balladur, hit by new controversy over his share sales and consultancy
earnings from a computer firm he used to head, tried to revive his
campaign with a message of optimism about France's economic recovery.
During a tour of the western Sarthe region he said he expected growth
this year to exceed the government's three percent forecast.
--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears for boy jabbed with needle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE parents of a seven-year-old boy who accidentally jabbed himself
with a discarded needle he found in a lavatory at a McDonald's
restaurant face an anxious wait to see if he is at risk from the HIV
virus.
Doctors have told Mr Andrew Chapman, 32, and his wife Josephine, from
Maryhill, that it will be three months before any sign of HIV infection
could become evident.
They fear the needle may have belonged to a drug user and could pose
the risk of the HIV virus or hepatitis.
Their son Scott was rushed to hospital after the incident on Tuesday.
Yesterday, the fast food chain said it had launched an investigation and
stepped up security after he found the syringe at the restaurant in
Maryhill, Glasgow.
The child has been placed on a six-month course of antibiotics and his
parents have been offered counselling on HIV.
Scott had been at the restaurant with his parents and sister Nicola,
10, as part of the children's weekly treat.
A spokeswoman for McDonald's said the matter was under investigation.
She said the safety of customers was a priority, and added: ''This
should not have happened. We are investigating how it could have
occurred and have been in touch with the parents.
''We are trying to take as many measures as we can to try to stop
drug-takers using our restaurants. We are as vigilant as we can be in
the dining rooms, and toilets are checked every 15 minutes,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Top brass shown the door</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST 100 of the Army's most senior officers were told yesterday that
they are to be made redundant. In all, 17 major-generals, 32 brigadiers,
and 48 colonels learned that they were to be the latest casualties of
last year's Defence Costs Study, intended to save #750m a year.
The redundancies are compulsory and across the board. Pensioning off
the top brass will start next month and take until March 1997. The ages
of those affected range from the early 40s to early 50s.
The fact that there would be job losses at two-star level and below
had previously been made public. Yesterday's notices will leave the Army
with only 27 major-generals. Six full generals and nine
lieutenant-generals have survived.
They are part of a total Army manpower cut of 500 jobs under the
Defence Cost Study. The remaining 400, mainly in the medical service,
will be told of their fate in September. This latest reduction has to be
seen in the context of a cut of almost 17,000 over the past three years.
The Ministry of Defence insisted last night that the severance
payments to major-generals would be on the same scale as that for other
ranks -- adjusted for differences in pay. The salary of a major-general
currently stands at #63,500.
Under the redundancy terms, a two-star officer with 21 months to serve
will receive a lump sum of #116,741 made up of a terminal grant of
#85,964 and a capital payment -- a so-called golden farewell -- of
#30,777. Thereafter he will receive an index-linked retirement pension
of #28,655.
</TEXT>
