<DOCNO>GH950310-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tories accuse Janner of conflict of interests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MPs yesterday demanded that senior Labour backbencher Greville
Janner should resign from his post as head of the parliamentary probe
into ''fat cat'' salaries.
They accused Mr Janner, MP for Leicester West, of offering the
services of his private company to the very executives summoned to
appear before the Commons employment select committee.
The committee is involved in a lengthy inquiry into alleged excesses
in the pay and perks of boardroom executives of privatised companies.
But 16 Tories accused committee chairman Mr Janner -- a director of
training and publishing company JSB Group -- in an emergency Commons
motion of having a conflict of interests.
He was condemned for his role in the award of a massive salary and
share options scheme to the chairman and directors of betting and
leisure company Ladbrokes.
Mr Janner is a non-executive director and member of the Remuneration
Committee of Ladbroke plc, whose chairman earns #583,000 a year.
The MPs said five Ladbroke directors were also granted share options
worth #2.3m.
The Commons motion calling for Mr Janner's resignation noted that he
was ''interviewing leading industrialists and businessmen on their
remuneration packages, while at the same time offering these people his
services on how to improve their public speaking and presentational
skills''.
It claimed that Mr Janner also offered advice on redundancies and said
''these activities represent a conflict of interest with his current
position as chairman of the employment select committee''.
After tabling the motion, the MPs later demanded a Commons debate on
the question of referring their claims about Mr Janner to the Nolan
Committee examining standards in public life.
The motion was raised with Commons Leader Tony Newton during questions
on next week's business. He told them their remarks ''do indeed indicate
some concern about these matters''.
* Meanwhile, Britain's highest paid coal industry executive Richard
Budge may face industrial action by the National Union of Mineworkers in
protest at a three-year pay freeze. And he may be called before the
Commons employment committeee to explain how his salary has leapt by
45%.
</TEXT>
