<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BR chairman delivers sell-off broadside</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON, CHIEF REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL chairman Sir Bob Reid yesterday admitted that the
performance of train services has worsened in the run-up to
privatisation -- and said he would not put his own money into the new
rail companies.
His critical comments will further embarrass a Government striving to
win over a sceptical public about the merits of privatisation.
Sir Bob, standing down at the end of the month, said he backed
switching the rail network to the private sector, in principle. But he
stressed he would have done it differently, and it would have worked.
When it was put to him that the first consequence of the Government's
reorganisation of the network in the privatisation run-up was that
services have worsened, he replied: ''Performance has gone down . . .
and nobody can deny that, and figures show that.''
He also said he would not have introduced Railtrack as a separate
track authority, but stayed with an integrated operation. He would also
have kept a nucleus of very experienced executives and not needed a
franchise director.
Asked if he would personally put money into a passenger franchise, he
replied: ''At this stage, no, I wouldn't.''
His reactions are as damning as those of Mr Chris Green before his
resignation last month as director of ScotRail.
Mr Green, frustrated by running trains on track over which he had no
control, was ''gagged'' as a direct result of his bleak assessment and
critical comments in an article in The Herald about the network's fate
leading up to privatisation.
He was ordered by Mr John Welsby, chief executive of the British
Railways Board, to stick to the company line and not speak directly to
the press unless it benefited the company.
Mr Welsby is taking over as chairman from Sir Bob who, like Mr Green,
has refused to pay lip-service to the Government and has reinforced
public concerns about the quality and standard of services after
privatisation.
The white-collar rail union, TSSA, yesterday welcomed Sir Bob's
comments -- and said it believed Railtrack would soon announce a
reduction of its regions from 10 to seven.
''Railtrack is desperately trying to make an unworkable system work,''
said general secretary Richard Rosser. He added: ''Just as the
Government is setting up 25 passenger operating companies, Railtrack is
going in exactly the opposite direction and is about to reduce its
zones.''
Railtrack said the suggestion of a reduction in regions was ''complete
speculation''.
Liberal Democrat transport spokesman Paul Tyler urged the Government
to heed Sir Bob's advice. He said: ''With both opposition parties
opposed to the Railtrack sell-off and with no election mandate for its
privatisation, the Government would be prudent to postpone a decision.''
Sir Bob's predecessor at BR, Sir Robert Reid, also made a strong
attack on rail policy towards the end of his chairmanship. He was
critical of the level of Government investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
