<DOCNO>GH950310-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Antics were no aerial avid and Goliath</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EFFORTS to sell a Scottish aeroplane led to unfounded fears of a
''near miss'' fears over Strathclyde last night.
A number of people contacted Strathclyde police, Glasgow Airport, and
the Civil Aviation Authority after spotting a large, distinctively
coloured passenger plane bank away from a smaller twin-engined aircraft
before completing a 360-degree turn and appearing to pursue the smaller
plane.
Mr Andrew Walker, from Bellshill, said it looked as though the smaller
craft had cut the bigger, turbo-prop plane up and the ''big boy'' was
going after him to give him a ''right talking-to on the radio''.
However, the truth was less sensational. The low flyers were making a
promotional film for British Aerospace, which manufactures the Advanced
Turbo Prop aircraft at its Prestwick plant.
The small, twin-engined plane was filming the larger ATP and flew in
tandem for some time, scouting out the best backdrops.
A spokesman for Glasgow's Air Traffic Control said the operation had
been fully approved by the Scottish Air Traffic Control Centre.
The Glasgow office and Glasgow Airport received a number of calls.
Mr Walker said last night he had heard the distinctive engine noise of
a ''twin turbo-prop revving hard'' at about 4.30 yesterday, and looked
up to see the big plane banking away from the smaller craft: ''These two
looked far too close together for safety. I thought they must just have
missed each other.''
</TEXT>
