<HEADLINE>Surgeon left 'missing' swabs inside patients</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SURGEON who left two patients in agony with swabs inside them after
birth operations, was found guilty of serious professional misconduct by
the General Medical Council yesterday.
The council's professional conduct committee heard that Dr Karen
Wilson, 32, endangered the life of a caesarian section patient by
leaving a swab inside her at the North Middlesex Hospital in Edmonton,
North London, on March 31 last year.
Dr Wilson refused to heed advice from nursing staff that there was a
''missing swab'' after the operation on Mrs Valerie Rolph, of Stoke
Newington, North London -- and failed to acknowledge her mistake when
she was shown an X-ray indicating the distinctive ''bird's-nest'' shape
of the swab two days later.
Dr Wilson, who admitted failing to act on information about the
missing swab, also pleaded guilty to ''forgetting'' that she had left a
roll of five (four by four inch) swabs inside patient Mrs Helene Brett,
of Sidcup, Kent, after a forceps delivery of her daughter, Charlotte,
while she was working as a locum at Queen Mary's Hospital in Sidcup in
August last year.
Council barrister Miss Rosalind Foster said both patients had suffered
''excruciating'' pain following the operations.
Glasgow-born Dr Wilson also admitted failing to check the blood
pressure of ''at risk'' patient Mrs Annabelle Easom, also of Sidcup, at
Queen Mary's and inserting sutures into the bladder of Mrs Yvonne Martin
while she was a locum registrar at Basildon General hospital.
Miss Foster told the committee the three offences at Queen Mary's and
Basildon were committed while Dr Wilson was on suspension from the North
Middlesex, following the incident involving Mrs Rolph.
Dr Wilson claimed she had been tired and under pressure because of
trivial accusations made against her by midwives and other non-medical
staff at the North Middlesex, when she performed the caesarian section
on Mrs Rolph -- although she was ''ashamed'' of what she had done.
The committee stopped short of ordering the erasure of Dr Wilson's
name from the register but imposed stringent conditions on her
registration for a period of two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP hands the banner to late re-entry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROSEANNA Cunningham last night had the SNP banner for the Perth and
Kinross parliamentary by-election thrust into her hands.
Despite the murky weeks along the road to the candidature, she won it
with 15 of the 20 votes cast at the constituency's selection committee
meeting in a Perth hotel.
Immediately after her victory was announced, Ms Cunningham, 42, an
advocate, declared: ''I am pleased that, despite what has happened in
the last two weeks, I have now been selected. I expect to have a hard
fight ahead of me and I fully expect to defeat the Tories in this
by-election.''
Ms Cunningham told media representatives: ''I will be speaking to you
in greater detail tomorrow.'' She is due to take part in a press
conference in Perth with party leader Alex Salmond today.
She did respond last night to one pointed question -- was her
selection a personal triumph? Her reply was: ''It is a triumph for the
SNP.'' Pressed further, she would only repeat that it was a triumph for
the party ''and for the democratic process within the party''.
Four of the five votes which she did not collect went to local
district councillor Mr Bruce Crawford. The single remaining vote was
cast for Alasdair Morgan, national secretary of the party.
Councillor Crawford pledged his support for Ms Cunningham. ''I am 110%
behind her,'' he said. He announced that he would be standing in the
shadow local government elections in Perth and Kinross next month.
A fourth contender, Mr Keith Brown, the SNP transport spokesman,
withdrew only hours before the selection meeting.
Party president Mrs Winnie Ewing put what the party will be hoping is
the final seal of approval for Ms Cunningham in a quickly produced
statement.
She said: ''I send my heartfelt congratulations to Roseanna. I am very
hopeful that we will have an SNP victory in the by-election and I firmly
believe that Roseanna will be the first by-election victor to hold the
seat at a General Election. I am greatly looking forward to campaigning
in Perth and Kinross.''
Last night, one branch member said as she left the hotel: ''I think
that all the publicity which seemed to be going against Roseanna, and
the way she handled it, helped her tonight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
