<HEADLINE>Companies win interdict against families in bitter Cormorant Alpha compensation battle. Judge bans US court moves in oil case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE bitter legal battle over compensation for the families of those
who died in the Cormorant Alpha helicopter tragedy was joined again
yesterday.
The families and survivors are attempting to sue oil giants Shell and
Esso in the US, but this is being resisted by the oil companies who
claim that the natural venue for the case is Scotland.
The families can expect to win up to 20 times as much compensation if
damages are awarded in the US.
In Brazoria County, Texas, Judge Neil Caldwell has already ruled that
an action in the name of 53 relatives and survivors should be allowed to
go ahead in the US.
Apart from deciding that the Texas courts had jurisdiction because of
the oil companies' business links in the state, the judge was highly
critical of the way the case had been conducted.
He alleged that the oil companies had undertaken a series of
deliberate, calculated manoeuvres to obstruct and impede the families.
Judge Caldwell also stated that there were reasonable grounds for
alleging that Shell and Esso had been responsible for the helicopter
crash because of their ''unrelenting push'' to reduce ''non-productive''
time by using the Super Puma helicopter to cut waiting time in storm
conditions.
These allegations are denied by the oil companies, who want to
challenge Judge Caldwell's finding on jurisdiction in the Supreme Court
in Texas.
Eleven men died when a Bristow-owned Super Puma crashed just after
taking off from Shell's Cormorant Alpha platform in atrocious weather
conditions on route to a nearby accommodation platform in March 1992.
Six men, including the pilot survived.
There have already been a number of lengthy hearings in the Court of
Session, and yesterday Mr Colin Moynihan, for the oil companies, asked
Lord Abernethy for an order banning the 53 plaintiffs from moving the US
proceedings from the District Court in Brazoria County to the probate
court.
Mr Moynihan said the application was being made to transfer the case
in Texas at 9pm British time last night.
He reminded Lord Abernethy that at a previous hearing the judge had
made it clear that no procedure should take place in the US apart from
the decision on jurisdiction.
In December last year, a guardian had been appointed to the ''minors''
involved in the case in the US. Some of these were, in fact, in their
mid-20s, and there was more than a suspicion that the guardian had been
appointed by Keaty and Keaty, the US lawyers who continued to act for
the families.
Then, on February 14 this year, the guardian had appointed an
administrator to look after the interests of the estates of those who
had died in the disaster. The administrator was someone in control of at
least part of the action beyond the reach of the Court of Session.
The next step was that on March 1, the administrator filed a motion to
transfer the whole US damages action involving the 53 plaintiffs from
the district court to the Probate Court in Brazoria.
That sequence of events aroused the suspicion that the whole exercise
was a device on the part of Keaty and Keaty.
The conduct of the litigation in America would be placed, at least in
part, beyond the control of the families and survivors, with the result
that an order from a Scottish court would be of no practical value.
The oil companies were apprehensive that the current transfer
application was no more than a preliminary step to dealing with the
merits of the case in the US. They were also concerned that it would put
a spanner in the works of their jurisdiction appeal to the Texas Supreme
Court.
Mr Colin Sutherland, QC, for the families, denied that they had filed
a motion in Texas to transfer the case. This had been done by the
administrator, who was an officer of the court in the US who had been
appointed by the guardian, also an officer of the court.
Both were outwith the jurisdiction of the Scottish court and Lord
Abernethy could take no action over it.
But the judge said he had to do all he could to preserve the position
previously reached by the Scottish courts -- that the oil companies had
made out an arguable case that Scotland was the proper venue for the
case.
He granted interdict against the 53 relatives to ban them from taking
any steps to move the US proceedings to the probate court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000145</DOCNO>
