<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nursing home owners fail to win ban on broadcast</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE owners of a Scottish nursing home yesterday failed to win a court
order banning a BBC Scotland television programme being broadcast last
night. Raymond and Margaret Baigent, of Orchard House Nursing Home,
Crossford, Lanarkshire, said their reputations would be damaged by the
Frontline Scotland documentary.
They have instructed their solicitors to raise court proceedings for
defamation. The programme alleged ''appalling'' standards of care.
At the Court of Session in Edinburgh yesterday, the Baigents' counsel,
Mr Neil Davidson, QC, claimed the accusations were ''unfounded, unjust,
and untrue''. The couple wanted the court to block the screening of the
programme but Lord Morton of Shuna refused their request.
Lord Morton said: ''There is a public interest at the moment in
Scotland about the running of nursing homes for the elderly.''
He refused the application on three grounds. He said: ''It is
impossible to grant an interdict in the terms sought. That is the first
ground.
''The second is that I consider even if the terms of the interdict
sought were varied, the balance of convenience in the light of the
publicity that appears to have happened makes it better that the thing
should be broadcast. Thirdly, there is a remedy of damages.''
During the hearing, Mr Davidson read out parts of a report in
Thursday's editions of The Herald about the BBC programme and the home.
He said The Herald article raised questions over the accuracy of the
Frontline Scotland programme.
Mr Davidson went on: ''I accept the topicality of this has increased
but material that has been discovered by The Herald as stated here
fortifies the strengths of the pursuers' case.''
He produced 93 letters from staff, residents, and former residents and
their families in support of the home.
Mr Davidson added: ''The Herald article appears to give greater
information about the notion that there was some conspiracy against the
Baigents and their home that comes from dissatisfied, sacked, resigned
former members of staff.
''The position now, I would submit, given the correspondence that is
produced, is that there is a very, very strong case that lies are being
told and will be broadcast by the BBC.''
Executive producer of Frontline Scotland Val Atkinson said: ''We are
delighted that viewers will be able to see the programme.''
In a statement issued through their solicitors last night, Mr and Mrs
Baigent said: ''Our nursing home has at various times, including very
recently, been checked by various independent medical authorities,
including Lanarkshire Health Board, a consultant surgeon, and the local
general practice. On no occasion have these authorities found any cause
for concern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
