<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bright future predicted for North Sea gas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Professor Peter Odell says the North Sea oil industry has at
least another 30 years to go and the gas industry will be of growing
importance people should sit up and take notice.
Scorn was poured on his predictions in 1973 that the North Sea would
be a much larger oil and gas province than the oil industry was prepared
to concede.
''Quite simply we say his estimates are rubbish,'' a BP spokesman said
at the time.
However, Professor Odell's predictions have proved to be largely
correct and, as well as at least one BP spokesman, he believes the
Labour Party must also rue the day it ignored him.
Professor Odell was in Aberdeen last night presenting a lecture: North
Sea Oil and Gas, 30 Years Gone -- 30 to Go? which was organised by
Aberdeen University and the Royal Scottish Geographical Society.
He outlined how the North Sea oil had proved extremely important to
the international oil industry in terms of the impact it had by bringing
oil down in price and also in the context of introducing the industry to
a new environment.
He emphasised its importance to the UK economy and said: ''I often
think that if it had not been for oil, Britain might have just
disappeared beneath the waves.''
Professor Odell said the discovery of oil and gas in the North Sea was
one of the most important post-war events for Britain and Europe.
He said there was enough oil already discovered to maintain three
million barrels a day UK North Sea production for well into the early
years of the 21st century but most importantly Britain was now moving
into a period when the importance of gas in the North Sea was being
recognised.
The professor added that since the early 70s gas had been dominated by
oil but early in the 21st century the output of gas would exceed the
energy output of oil and would nearly double its current levels by about
2020, setting up a flow of jobs and a flow of revenue.
Speaking of the criticism of his 1973 study he said: ''We were thought
to be way off beam and were defined as having made serious errors in our
calculations.''
He said that Tony Benn had appointed him as a special adviser in the
early 1970s but then failed to take his advice and it meant the Labour
Government had ''to go begging to the IMF'' to help it out instead of
securing what it needed from the North Sea, probably bringing a
premature end to the Callaghan Government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#4m appeal is launched for opera school</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN appeal was launched yesterday to raise #4m to build a National
Opera School for Scotland in Glasgow.
The new building will be on the premises of the Royal Scottish Academy
of Music and Drama, and will be called the Alexander Gibson Opera
School, after the conductor who founded Scottish Opera and was president
of the RSAMD until his death in January.
The project is intended to enhance the professional training already
given at the RSAMD, and to expand it by attracting high quality students
of opera from throughout the UK and abroad.
It was launched yesterday with a feisty optimism and determination
reminiscent of the heady days of Glasgow's year as European City of
Culture.
Already #800,000 has been secured -- with the Queen Mother, patron of
the RSAMD, a primary benefactor. The building, which will include
teaching, rehearsal and performance facilities, should be completed by
August 1997.
Mr Morrison Dunbar, appeal chairman, and a former chairman of the
board of governors of the RSAMD, said there was a critical shortage of
space for opera coaching, despite the excellence of the facilities in
the Renfrew Street building, opened in 1988.
At present, coaching in the opera department takes place in rented
accommodation in Bath Street. ''These premises,'' said Mr Dunbar, ''are
not even available to us in the evenings or at weekends.''
The Alexander Gibson Opera School, he said, will be situated at the
rear of the Renfrew Street building, where there is at present a car
park. It will be linked to the main academy building, but with its own
entrance on Cowcaddens Road.
The organisers yesterday stated their intention of going for the big
money. Principal targets will be the Foundation for Sport and the Arts,
the Millennium Fund, and the National Lottery, whose money is available
for capital projects. Banks and the biggest businesses can also expect a
knock on the door.
The #800,000 already secured has come from, as well as the Queen
Mother, a range of trusts and individuals, including the RSAMD and
Broadwood Trusts, Lady Veronica Gibson, widow of Sir Alexander, and the
Dunard Fund.
The organisers intend, however, to cast the net as wide as possible,
seeking covenants, donations, in-kind sponsorship, specialist equipment,
and the sponsorship of individual rooms and seats.
Chartered architects Boswell Mitchell and Johnston have been appointed
the school's architects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hogg dropped from visit 'to avert row with Israel'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS for Foreign Office Minister Douglas Hogg to go with the Prime
Minister this weekend to Israel apparently have been dropped in what is
seen by Middle East watchers as a move to avert a diplomatic row.
Mr Hogg had been widely expected to travel with Mr Major, although
this was never officially announced and the Foreign Office insisted
yesterday that no final plans were made.
His expected visit was reported to have prompted diplomatic
representations from Israel to try to stop Mr Hogg visiting Orient
House, the Palestine Liberation Organisation's headquarters in east
Jerusalem.
Israel says the Palestinians, who claim east Jerusalem as their
capital, can use Orient House as a cultural centre but not for political
meetings.
East Jerusalem is viewed by the Palestinians as the capital of their
future state.
The Foreign Office said last night that the decision that Mr Hogg
should remain in London was taken on Wednesday by the Prime Minister and
Foreign Secretary because somebody was needed to ''mind the
shop.''Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd will be in the Gulf over the
weekend while Mr Major is in Israel.
Peace drive8
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950310-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950310-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950310</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Comic's former gardener guilty</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FREDDIE Starr's gay ex-gardener is facing a prison sentence for
stealing thousands of pounds worth of jewellery from the comedian and
his former wife Sandra.
Robin Coxhead, 44, was found guilty of two theft charges after a jury
at Reading Crown Court dismissed his claim that he had been given the
jewellery by Mr Starr in exchange for sexual favours.
Coxhead showed no emotion as Judge John Crocker said he would pass
sentence on April 7, after reading reports.
Coxhead denied stealing any of the gems, claiming the comedian asked
him to perform oral sex at his mansion in Maidenhead, Berkshire, and
afterwards gave him gifts, including a #12,000 diamond engagement ring
belonging to his then wife, plus bracelets and a pendant necklace.
The judge had already directed the jury to find Coxhead not guilty on
another charge of stealing a watch belonging to Mr Starr.
Coxhead, of Audley Street, Reading, was released on conditional bail.
Judge Crocker told him: ''I want you to be under no illusion
whatsoever that these offences are very serious. It involves a breach of
trust and a very large amount of money.''
During the four-day trial, the court heard allegations that Mr Starr
was addicted to valium and diazepam and would fly into uncontrollable
rages, during which he would abuse Coxhead both verbally and physically.
Coxhead told the court that Sandra Starr, now divorced from the
comedian, had told him she feared for her life on several occasions. Mrs
Starr denied the claim when she spoke from the witness box.
Mr Starr, a teetotaller, admitted to the court that he had had a drug
problem in the past, but said he had got help for it.
The couple's former housekeeper, Susan Englefield, said Coxhead told
her about his sex romps in the Berkshire mansion while the family were
on holiday in Florida.
The court heard that the loss of #41,000 worth of jewellery belonging
to Mr and Mrs Starr was discovered on their return from holiday in
February 1994.
Later Coxhead told police he had #38,000 debts.
When Coxhead was arrested in March last year, he denied stealing the
jewellery.
Arrested for a second time in April, he admitted he had the jewellery,
but had thrown it in the Thames when he realised Mr Starr had ''set him
up''.
When he finally admitted to police he had the jewellery, including a
Cartier watch valued at #10,000, Coxhead said: ''I did not want this to
come out about me and Freddie.''
But Mr Starr strongly denied the sex favours claim, telling the court:
''I am 100% heterosexual -- the allegations are totally despicable.''
</TEXT>
