<HEADLINE>Fury over Sinn Fein funds Fury over Clinton's move on Sinn Fein</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Clinton's signal that he will permit Sinn Fein leader Mr
Gerry Adams to resume fundraising in the United States was met with cold
fury by the British Government last night.
It is seen as an acknowledgment that Mr Adams is now entitled to join
political talks before the IRA has handed over a single weapon.
The President is inviting seven party political leaders in Northern
Ireland to a St Patrick's Day reception in the White House. Dr Ian
Paisley rejected the invitation immediately and Mr Jim Molyneaux, the
Ulster Unionist leader, was expected to do the same.
Mr David Irvine and Mr Gary McMichael, recognised spokesmen for the
loyalist paramilitaries, are consulting their party executives about the
invitation, but it is likely that President Clinton will be left with Mr
Adams and Mr John Hume, the SDLP leader, and Mr John Alderdyce of the
Alliance Party, as his guests.
The St Patrick's Day reception will be toasting the Irish Prime
Minister, Mr John Bruton. Whitehall regards this as a politcal stunt by
President Clinton pressed on him by his National Security Adviser in the
White House, Mr Tony Lake, and the Kennedy Democrats in Congress.
Mr Major, who is to visit Washington in the first week of April, now
finds himself in a situation that might affect his control of the
ongoing delicate negotiations to force the IRA to give up their
offensive weapons before Mr Adams is allowed to meet British Ministers
as an accredited political negotiator.
The American decision to allow Sinn Fein to restart fundraising in the
United States is a desperate blow to Mr Major and his Northern Ireland
Secretary, Sir Patrick Mayhew, who only last week believed that he had
persuaded the United States Government to continue the ban on Sinn
Fein's fundraising there.
Last night Mr Major was contemplating whether to contact President
Clinton personally to try to persuade him not to take two steps forward
before Mr Adams and the IRA have taken the essential one step forward --
to begin delivering up their stores in the Republic and elsewhere of
Semtex explosives, ground-to-air missiles and heavy machine-guns.
What has infuriated British Ministers is what they regard as a
specious argument advanced by the White House that there is no ban on
Sinn Fein fund-raising in the UK. This is not technically correct.
Furthermore, it has been pointed out to Washington that the IRA robs
banks and murders people on this side of the Atlantic in order to raise
serious funds.
This new crisis for No 10 and the White House has deeply irritated not
only Downing Street but also the US Secretary of State, Mr Warren
Christopher, who once again has been overruled by Mr Lake.
The President and Mr Lake are judged here to have taken too literally
a statement from Mr Adams yesterday, indicating that he is now prepared
to start serious talks about ''decommissioning'' of weapons. But he
links this with what he calls ''movement on a range of issues, including
repressive legislation, prisoners and the decommissioning of weapons''.
Mr Adams insisted: ''Everyone must be at the table and every issued
must be on the table. It is in this context that progress can be made on
the whole range of relative issues -- justice, discrimination in
employment, prisoners, political and constitutional matters and
demilitarisation.''
Without President Clinton's stunning intervention the British
Government would have taken the Adams statement as an encouraging step
forward in the peace process. Last night there was profound gloom in
Whitehall, particularly as Mr Dick Spring, the Irish Foregin Minister,
expressed gratitude to President Clinton for his keen interest and that
of Congress.
Mr Spring also welcomed Mr Adams's acknowledgment yesterday ''that the
decommissioning of weapons is among the important issues which must be
addressed, and confirming that his party is now ready to include this
issue among the matters they look forward to discussing in dialogue with
British Ministers''.
The British view is that this sentiment also races ahead of what has
actually happened. Sir Patrick has indicated to Mr Adams that, if he
begins to arrange the hand-over of IRA heavy weapons, he could be
allowed to meet Mr Michael Ancram, the British Minister in charge of
developing political negotiations.
In particular Downing Street did not wish the American Government to
sanction a resumation of Sinn Fein fundraising in the United States
until the IRA had taken this essential first step towards
decommissioning their arsenal -- almost 90% of which is believed to be
lodged in the Republic.
Sir Patrick last week in Washington emphasised this and thought that
he had won agreement.
He pointed out to Mr Christopher that the IRA is still recruiting,
still intimidating and still using violence such as knee-capping and
other tortures.
</TEXT>
