<HEADLINE>Pensioners on alert over hoax police letters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN, ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PENSIONERS were last night warned to be on their guard against a
hoaxer sending letters out on Lothian and Borders police headed
notepaper.
Two pensioners have already notified police about the bogus
correspondence sent out within the last fortnight.
One was sent to an 84-year-old Edinburgh man telling him he was a
witness in a rape case, and that he should report to a city court on a
certain date. Failure to do so would result in a #150 fine.
In the other case, a 74-year-old man from Bathgate in West Lothian
received a hoax letter claiming he owed several hundreds of pounds to
cover the costs of the services of police officers and RSPCA officials
in the hunt for his stolen car containing his dog.
The Edinburgh pensioner, Mr Alex Hope, yesterday warned other elderly
people who may have received suspicious letters to take them to the
police.
Mr Hope said: ''I have no idea where they got my name or why they
picked me out.
''The letter looked official and did cause me great concern and
worried both me and my wife. I had no knowledge of any court case or
anything like that.
''What raised my suspicions was that the envelope wasn't properly
sealed and there were some spelling errors in the letter.
''I took it to the police straight away and would advise any other
pensioners who may have had the same sort of letter not to worry and to
do the same thing.''
A Lothian and Borders police spokesman said both cases had caused the
people involved great concern.
The spokesman said: ''In both these cases elderly people have been
picked out to be sent the hoax letters. These sort of letters do cause
alarm to people.
''Our inquiries are continuing into the sending of the letters and we
would ask any other pensioners who have received similar ones to contact
us immediately at police HQ at Fettes in Edinburgh.''
Last month a hoaxer sent a letter to residents in a narrow Edinburgh
street telling them a ''fast lane'' for drivers was to be created
outside their homes.
The correspondence, purporting to come from Lothian Regional Council,
claimed the move would not pose any danger to householders.
A number of residents who received the communication initially
believed it to be genuine.
</TEXT>
