<HEADLINE>Botha cry for the beloved country</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG, ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world's three great trading blocks -- Europe, North America, and
the Asia-Pacific region -- should band together in a tri-lateral
initiative to boost economic regeneration in South Africa and, through
that, save the rest of the sub-Saharan Africa from oblivion.
That was the impassioned plea to a Glasgow audience last night from Mr
Pik Botha, former South African Foreign Minister, and now Minister of
Mineral and Energy Affairs in the Mandela government.
Mr Botha told the annual Petroleum Dinner at the Hospitality Inn:
''Without a successful South Africa, sub-Saharan Africa will slide
further into anarchy and misery.''
He said companies coming to do business in his country, instead of
paying taxes, should contribute to the building of new schools and
hospitals.
Acknowledging the nature of the audience, he pointed to South Africa's
300 years of coal reserves and its offshore oil and gas prospects as
clear commercial opportunities.
Again and again, he returned to the theme of hunger and disease on the
continent, and the need for action. The greatest challenge facing the
world, he added, was global economic inequality.
</TEXT>
