<HEADLINE>Sheridan claims cover-up in council repair delays</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST one in three families living in council houses in Glasgow are
waiting for repairs to be carried out on their homes, it was claimed
yesterday.
The figure emerged after Scottish Militant Labour councillors accused
the city's Labour administration of a cover-up over the true level of
the repairs backlog in the city.
Councillor Tommy Sheridan alleged: ''There is a massive repairs
scandal in Glasgow. Many repairs are simply not being carried out while
the waiting time for others is several months.
''I have been given figures for Pollok, my ward, which show there are
7000 outstanding repairs. There are only 9200 houses in the ward. It is
obvious people in the schemes, where problems are concentrated, are
bearing the brunt of this crisis.''
Councillor Sheridan also claimed that the council's repairs budget had
been cut by #2.5m in the last two years and said #3m should be taken out
of the city council's #6m reserves immediately to redress the situation.
Since 1989 ''non-essential repairs'' have been suspended by the
council, but Councillor Sheridan said tenants were waiting for repairs
that were not on the suspended list.
Mr Ronnie MacDonald, depute director of City Housing, admitted that
there were 57,000 repair lines outstanding for council houses last
month. The council has a housing stock of 120,000.
However, Mr MacDonald said: ''It's wrong to say that 50% of tenants
are waiting for work to be done. Some of these repair lines will be
duplicates and some houses need several repairs. There's also the effect
of the floods in Pollok a couple of months ago.''
The Herald visited a number of tenants in Pollok yesterday who said
they had been waiting months for work to be done.
The front door of Miss Margaret Cryans's flat on Linthaugh Road was
kicked in by burglars in November. ''There is a huge hole in the
panelling of the door, the mortice has gone, and the Yale lock is only
held on by one nail,'' she said.
''When I go out the house I am scared to come back in case somebody is
in. And when I am in bed at night I am terrified someone will break
in.''
At nearby Dormanside Road neighbours Miss Kath Lynch, 27, and Miss
Margaret Doherty, 44, said the security door at the entrance to their
close had been destroyed three years ago and never repaired. The close
is invaded nightly by up to 30 youngsters.
The housing convener, Councillor Madge O'Neill, said that tenants were
not waiting longer for repairs than in the past. In fact, she added, the
repairs backlog had been reduced.
</TEXT>
