<HEADLINE>Scots hand Blair a Clause 4 present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979468595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair received a boost for his drive to reform
Clause 4 when he won the backing of the party's Scottish executive.
It voted 18-12 in support of a reforming motion to be voted on at
today's conference in Inverness. This would water down the commitment to
nationalisation.
By a similar margin, the executive also voted to oppose a hard line
motion urging no change to Clause 4.
It is now expected that the reformers will win the day, although
opponents were still saying last night that the vote would be too close
to count.
Mr Jack McConnell, general secretary of the Scottish party, said the
executive's vote mirrored a substantial change of mood in the party over
the past three months. ''People's opinions have been changed as they
have listened to the debate.'' Last month, the executive tied 17-17 when
it voted on the principle of reform.
However there is still uncertainty about how the GMB union will vote.
Delegates were in a caucus meeting last night trying to reach a
decision. If they swing behind Mr Blair, he could have a more decisive
victory.
Mr McConnell said Mr Blair regarded it as most important that a
majority of constituency parties should support his plans. He said Mr
Blair had made clear throughout the campaign to replace the 77-year-old
Clause 4 of the party's constitution that he wanted to win the vote by
convincing individual party members he was right.
On Grampian TV's Crossfire last night, Mr Blair said he had no
intention of pursuing the policies set out in Clause 4 when in
government.
He said he did not regret starting the debate on the Clause and denied
it was a distraction.
''To win we need to be trusted and to be trusted we need to be
clear,'' he said.
There were industries which should be in the public sector, like the
railways, but he also wanted Britain to have a strong competitive
private sector.
On the same programme Mr Dennis Canavan, Labour MP for Falkirk West,
said: ''It would be contrary to the principles of democratic socialism
to say that just because the man at the top says something we should all
bow down and agree with him'.''
Mr McConnell said: ''The Scottish party now faces a very stark choice.
It can go for the status quo or it can vote to spell out party policy in
words that people can understand and endorse in the 1990s and beyond.''
Opponents will line up behind a motion to be moved by Glasgow Maryhill
party, which provided, in Mr Jim Mearns, a speaker who galvanised last
year's national conference. The key part of the motion says that Clause
4 and the principles it contains ''represent the ultimate object of
Labour's democratic socialism and should therefore remain unaltered in
any redrafted constitution''.
Meanwhile, Mr Blair moved swiftly last night to deny a report saying a
new 50% top rate of income tax would be introduced by an incoming Labour
Government.
A spokesman for the Labour leader said: ''No such decision has been
taken. The discussions that would be necessary for such a decision to be
taken have not been held.
''The Labour Party will not decide its tax rates until much nearer the
General Election.''
According to an ''exclusive'' report in yesterday's Daily Telegraph,
Mr Blair has decided to go into the next election promising that there
will be no return to the penal 83% top rate on earned income when the
party was last in power, but a new 50% top rate of income tax will be
introduced, it says.
The newspaper says no decision has been reached on the level at which
the rate will come into effect.
The newspaper says Mr Blair is understood to favour levying the new
top rate on earnings of at least #80,000 to #100,000 a year, to prevent
a backlash from the middle-income professionals Labour is trying to woo.
But Labour left-wingers -- says the newspaper -- want the higher
levels of tax to bite much lower down the scale, probably at around
#40,000 a year, to raise money to improve health, education, and other
services.
