<HEADLINE>Celtic to sue ex-manager Lou Macari for #727,000 Celtic in claim for damages</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979468596</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC Football Club yesterday launched a #727,000 damages claim
against Lou Macari, listing a catalogue of alleged incompetence on the
part of the club's former manager.
As part of the action, Celtic allege that the team's failure to
qualify for Europe under his ill-fated stewardship cost the club more
than #380,000.
The action by Celtic in the Court of Session is a counter-claim to the
former manager's action in the same court for #431,000. Mr Macari is
claiming breach of contract over his dismissal in June last year.
In its counter-claim, which Lord Prosser allowed to be lodged
yesterday, Celtic alleges that the #250,000 paid to Stoke City to
recruit Mr Macari was a waste of money. Mr Macari is now back with the
Potteries club.
Celtic says the former manager spent most if not all of his working
week elsewhere than at Parkhead.
''He perceived his role as in large measure that of a sort of
super-scout scouring the country for new players,'' the club maintain.
''He infrequently attended coaching sessions with the players. He failed
to monitor injuries.''
His alleged lack of leadership is also criticised. ''He avoided even
discussing team formation. On occasion, the team were told immediately
before the game or not at all the formation in which they should play,''
say Celtic.
The Parkhead club allege that the players had little confidence in the
manager and made their views known within the club.
In their claim, Celtic say: ''Exceptionally, for only about the second
time in 20 years, they (the team) failed to attain a final position in
the league sufficient to earn them a place in a European cup
competition.''
The club allege that the poor performance of the team reflected the
low morale, the lack of discipline and organisation, and a lack of
leadership and add that but for Mr Macari's ''breach of contract'' the
team would have qualified for Europe.
Detailed losses alleged by Celtic are:
* #380,851 for failing to get into Europe.
* #250,000 ''wasted'' in payment to Stoke City.
* #23,777 in ''wasted'' management time.
* #67,794 in recruitment costs to find a relacement manager.
Mr Macari's ''excessive'' travel to and from Stoke is also said to
have cost #4928.
In his action against Celtic, Mr Macari claims that, under the terms
of his contract, the club were required to give him two years' notice of
termination of employment, but failed to do so.
He explains that he rented a house in Glasgow but that his wife and
children continued to stay in Stoke-on-Trent because of the children's
schooling.
He says he came to Glasgow from Monday to Saturday during the playing
season and worked every day of the week on Celtic's behalf.
Although he attended matches looking for new players, senior staff
were always present at Parkhead, delegated to carry out duties in his
absence.
Mr Macari alleges that the club's chief executive, Mr Fergus McCann
''appeared to be keen to and did generate paper complaints based on
misinformation or a misapprehension on his part of what the working of a
football manager required''.
Mr Siggi Bennett, counsel for Celtic, told the judge Celtic were
disputing Mr Macari's action on the basis that his sacking was fully
justified.
A further hearing in the case is expected.
Mr Macari was successful as a manager at Swindon Town, West Ham
United, and Stoke City before Celtic asked him to return to the club
where he had been popular as a player.
